  'Food',
  ARRAY[]::TEXT[],
  '<h2>Introduction: Before You Understand What Beijing Eats, Understand How Beijing Eats</h2><p>Beijing''s flavour is a "hybrid" that this city has been accumulating for 800 years — the refinement of Ming and Qing imperial palace cuisine, the Shandong culinary foundations brought north by Grand Canal grain carriers, the lamb-eating traditions left behind by Mongolian garrison troops of the Qing dynasty, the Muslim culinary arts of the Hui community that settled along Niujie Street over 1,300 years ago, and the full spectrum of China''s eight great regional cuisines absorbed since the Reform Era. So "Beijing cuisine" is not a single concept. <strong>It is a stack of flavour strata built up over centuries in an imperial capital.</strong></p><p>For an international visitor, the single most important thing to understand about eating in Beijing is: <strong>don''t fixate on Peking duck.</strong> Duck is not to be missed, but it represents only one-tenth of what this city tastes like. This guide opens four doors — <strong>The Four Pillars / Morning in the Hutongs / A Thousand Years on Niujie / The Michelin Era</strong> — and closes with a complete "one week of eating Beijing" itinerary.</p><h2>Part One: The Four Pillars</h2><p>If a foreign visitor has only four days in Beijing, these are the four things that cannot be missed — because <strong>each one corresponds to a completely different Beijing</strong>.</p><h3>1. Peking Duck — The Imperial Ritual</h3><p>Peking duck has become much more than a dish. Its real magic is that <strong>it is a dish performed in front of you</strong> — the chef wheels a glistening, mahogany-lacquered whole duck to the table and slices it into 108 pieces (a technique called "slicing the skin"), beginning with the crispiest skin to be eaten dipped in sugar, then rolling the meat in thin pancakes with sweet bean sauce, scallion, and cucumber. The process itself is a performance.</p><h2>2026 Practical Guide: Restaurants by Budget and Occasion</h2><p>| Level | Restaurant | Price per Duck | What Makes It Special | Advice for International Visitors | |------|------|------|------|------------------| | <strong>Popular First Choice</strong> | <strong>Siji Minfu (Forbidden City Branch)</strong>&lt;br/&gt;11 Nanchizi Street, Dongcheng District | 259 RMB per duck&lt;br/&gt;(half duck 159 RMB) | By 2025 expanded to more than 20 locations across major Chinese cities; window seats at the Forbidden City branch overlook the palace moat | Must book ahead or expect a long queue; the Forbidden City and Wangfujing branches have the best locations — walkable after visiting the palace | | <strong>New-Wave Refined</strong> | <strong>Dadong (Nanxincang Branch)</strong>&lt;br/&gt;22A Dongsi Shitiao, Dongcheng District | 400+ RMB per person | The "not greasy" roast duck — a lighter interpretation more accessible to international guests unaccustomed to the traditional fat-rich version; artful presentation | Suitable for business entertaining or a high-end experience; book in advance | | <strong>Hutong Experience</strong> | <strong>Liqun Roast Duck</strong>&lt;br/&gt;11 Xiangfeng Hutong, Qianmen East Street, Dongcheng District | 238 RMB per duck | Hidden in the hutongs behind Qianmen; the chef trained at Quanjude; a faint fruitwood fragrance; known to attract Chinese celebrities and foreign visitors alike; the decor is worn, the service occasionally rough, but the atmosphere is genuine | The best route into "finding old Beijing hidden in a hutong" | | <strong>Chain Heritage</strong> | <strong>Quanjude</strong> | 260+ RMB | Founded in 1864, the most famous state-owned duck restaurant — but quality has declined | Worth skipping; overcrowded with tourists, heavily commercialised |</p><h3>2. Instant-Boiled Mutton (Lamb Shabu) — The Northern Winter</h3><p>If you are in Beijing between November and March, instant-boiled mutton is not optional. It is nothing like the spicy southern hotpot — <strong>a tall-chimneyed brass pot, charcoal burning underneath, surrounding broth that is almost clear</strong> (just ginger slices, scallion, dried shrimp, and mushrooms), with hand-sliced lamb that needs only seconds in the bubbling water, dipped in a house sesame sauce (tahini, chive flower paste, fermented tofu) before eating.</p><p>This style of eating traces back to the Mongol Yuan court and was refined by Beijing''s Hui Muslim community during the Qing dynasty. The essence of it is <strong>"clear broth reveals the true flavour"</strong>: the thinnest possible slices of lamb, the purest possible broth, the richest possible sesame sauce — letting the natural sweetness of the lamb speak.</p><h2>Recommended restaurants:</h2><ul><li><strong>Donglaishun (Wangfujing APM Branch)</strong>: Founded in 1903 and located on the fifth floor of the APM mall at 138 Wangfujing Avenue, this is the original and most historically grounded option. The hand-sliced lamb is described by its four hallmarks — thin as paper, uniform as crystal, straight as a line, beautiful as a flower. Around 150 to 250 RMB per person. Halal-certified; Muslim-friendly.</li><li><strong>Jubaoyuan (Niujie Branch)</strong>: Local consensus pick for the best hotpot mutton in Beijing. Always a queue (a two-hour wait on holidays is normal). Around 120 RMB per person. <strong>Niujie has more than a dozen other Halal hotpot restaurants nearby</strong> — all worth trying. A reliable method: follow whichever queue has the most elderly Beijing locals in it.</li><li><strong>Nanmen Hot Pot (Temple of Heaven Branch)</strong>: A convenient stop after visiting the Temple of Heaven. Around 90 RMB per person, excellent value.</li></ul><h3>3. Old Beijing Zhajiangmian — The Soul of the Everyday</h3><p>Zhajiangmian is Beijing''s "daily bread" — thick hand-rolled noodles with a slow-fried yellow soybean paste and minced pork sauce, topped with seven or eight thinly sliced seasonal garnishes (shredded cucumber, radish, Chinese toon, green peas, edamame, beauty-heart radish, celery, shredded cabbage). The traditional way to eat it is to rinse the noodles in cold water first to make them chewy, then pile on the garnishes and sauce and mix.</p><h2>Recommended:</h2><ul><li><strong>Haiwanju (Zengguang Road Branch)</strong>: Pure old Beijing flavour; the servers announce each order in the traditional calling-out style — itself a form of intangible cultural heritage</li><li><strong>Fangzhuanchang Number 69</strong>: Near the north end of Nanluoguxiang; queues are common; open late</li><li><strong>Old Beijing Zhajiangmian Dawang</strong>: Multiple branches along Guijie and elsewhere</li></ul><p>Around 30 to 60 RMB per person. One bowl is a full meal — the lowest-cost entry point to the spirit of old Beijing street life.</p><h3>4. Imperial Snacks — The Palace''s Gift to the Streets</h3><p>This is the category that most foreign visitors most underestimate. <strong>About 80 percent of Beijing''s old-style snacks trace their origins to the Qing imperial kitchen</strong>, developed further by chefs who entered civilian life after the last emperor was expelled from the Forbidden City:</p><p>| Snack | Description | Where to Find It | |------|------|------| | <strong>Lv Da Gun (Glutinous Soybean Roll)</strong> | Sticky rice rolled in toasted soybean flour, filled with red bean paste | Huguo Temple Snacks / Niujie Baiji | | <strong>Wandou Huang (Pea Cake)</strong> | Empress Dowager Cixi''s favourite dessert — a golden, cooling square of smooth sweet pea paste | Fanzhan Restaurant / Huguo Temple | | <strong>Aiwowo</strong> | Glutinous rice skin filled with white sugar, sesame, and nuts, rolled in white starch powder | Niujie Halal snack stalls | | <strong>Yundou Juan (Kidney Bean Roll)</strong> | Kidney bean paste rolled with red bean filling — snow-white and delicate | Fanzhan / Huguo Temple | | <strong>Miancha</strong> | Millet flour paste with sesame sauce and spiced salt poured over — a uniquely Beijing breakfast item | Old Ciqi Kou Douzhir Shop | | <strong>Douzhir (Fermented Mung Bean Drink)</strong> | <strong>Beijing''s most debated food</strong> — a fermented mung bean drink, accompanied by crispy fried dough rings and salted vegetable shreds | Same as above |</p><h2>Where to go:</h2><ul><li><strong>Huguo Temple Snacks (Shichahai Branch)</strong>: A "museum-style" collection of classic Beijing snacks in one place</li><li><strong>Old Ciqi Kou Douzhir Shop (near the Temple of Heaven north gate)</strong>: The best place to try Douzhir; open from 6:00 AM</li><li><strong>Niujie Halal Supermarket / Baiji Nian Gao</strong>: Buy and eat on the spot — cheap and completely real</li></ul><h2>Part Two: Morning in the Hutongs — the Most Underrated Two Hours of the Day</h2><p>The most underrated food moment in Beijing is not dinner — it is <strong>the hutong breakfast between 6:00 and 8:00 AM</strong>. This is the true rhythm of local life: retired elders fresh from their morning exercise, taxi drivers heading home after a night shift, children walking to school, all converging at a cluster of tiny shops or street carts to eat a hot meal. The living, breathing warmth of this city is at its most concentrated in these two hours.</p><h3>Four Breakfasts Worth Trying (grouped by proximity)</h3><p>#### 1. Jianbing Guozi (Savoury Crepe) Mung bean flour spread on a hot iron griddle, a cracked egg smoothed over it, scattered with spring onions, coriander, and sesame seeds, brushed with sweet bean sauce and chilli paste, then wrapped around a crispy fried dough wafer. <strong>Around 8 to 12 RMB.</strong> Any street breakfast cart does this well.</p><p>#### 2. Chaogan (Braised Offal Stew) The name is misleading — it is actually pork large intestine and short sections of pig liver braised in a thickened broth with garlic paste, eaten alongside steamed buns. A characteristically bold Beijing breakfast.</p><ul><li><strong>Yaoji Chaogan (Drum Tower Branch)</strong>: Obama ate here in 2009. Near the Drum Tower. The steamed buns alongside the stew are the classic pairing.</li><li><strong>Tianxingju (Qianmen Xianyu Kou Street)</strong>: A century-old institution.</li></ul><p>#### 3. Baozi (Steamed Buns)</p><ul><li><strong>Qingfeng Baozi</strong>: Known because a former Premier ate a 21-RMB set meal at the Yuetan branch — a genuinely everyday people''s restaurant</li><li><strong>Mending Rou Bing (Doorknob Meat Pie)</strong>: The Halal version from Niujie is best — crisp pastry, generous filling</li></ul><p>#### 4. Sesame Flatbread with Meat Filling Sesame-crusted flatbread stuffed with soy-braised beef or lamb. Cheap and filling, 10 to 15 RMB each.</p><h3>A Sample Morning Route (Drum Tower Area)</h3><p><strong>6:00 AM</strong>: Walk to <strong>Yaoji Chaogan (Drum Tower Branch)</strong> for chaogan with steamed buns → Walk 10 minutes to <strong>Drum Tower Square</strong> to watch the tai chi and diabolo-spinning morning crowd → Cut the corner to <strong>Fangzhuanchang Number 69</strong> for zhajiangmian if still hungry → Stroll the surrounding hutongs to walk it all off.</p><p>This route combines breakfast, watching daily Beijing life, and exploring hutongs — all compressed into 90 minutes. It is the most concentrated way to experience this city.</p><h2>Part Three: Niujie — a Living Museum of 1,000 Years of Muslim Food</h2><p>If you could choose only one "Beijing food geography point," it should be <strong>Niujie</strong>. The street''s origins go back to the Northern Song dynasty (996 CE), and the Niujie Mosque within the neighbourhood is Beijing''s largest — a palace-style complex that fuses Chinese imperial architecture with Arabic decorative forms. For over 900 years, Beijing''s oldest Hui Muslim community has lived here, developing a Halal food culture entirely independent of Han Chinese cooking — centred on lamb, with almost no pork, using fermentation, slow braising, and roasting as core techniques.</p><h3>Niujie Must-Eat Map (All within roughly one kilometre on foot)</h3><p>| Restaurant | Address | Must Order | Price | |------|------|------|------| | <strong>Jubaoyuan</strong> | 5-2 Niujie | Hand-sliced fresh lamb, sesame flatbread | 120 RMB per person | | <strong>Baiji Nian Gao</strong> | 87 Niujie | Nian gao rice cake, Aiwowo, Lv Da Gun (take back to the hotel as a midnight snack) | 10 to 30 RMB | | <strong>Turpan Restaurant</strong> | South end of Niujie | Xinjiang big plate chicken, baked stuffed buns (not Hui but very authentic) | 80 RMB per person | | <strong>Hongji Snack Shop</strong> | 67 Niujie | Beef pieces, nian gao, cream fried cake | 20 to 40 RMB | | <strong>Nianji Sesame Oil Chicken</strong> | 88 Niujie | Sesame oil flash-fried chicken | 35 to 50 RMB | | <strong>Ma Jia Fried Meat</strong> | Shuru Hutong | Pepper-salt lamb, fried meat strips | 30 to 50 RMB |</p><h3>Suggested Niujie Day Route</h3><p><strong>11:00 AM</strong>: Visit Niujie Mosque (experience 1,300 years of Islamic architecture fused with Chinese style) → <strong>12:00 PM</strong>: Lunch at Jubaoyuan for hotpot lamb → <strong>2:00 PM</strong>: Walk the street picking up Baiji Nian Gao and Aiwowo → <strong>3:00 PM</strong>: Walk to <strong>Fayuan Temple</strong> (500 metres away, a Buddhist temple founded in the Tang dynasty over 1,000 years ago) → <strong>4:00 PM</strong>: Return to Niujie for a bowl of covered tea and Ma Jia Fried Meat.</p><p>Niujie is a living museum of Beijing''s Halal food tradition and <strong>deserves half a day on its own</strong>. It has none of the polished tourist packaging of Nanluoguxiang — but the flavours, the density of history, and the authenticity are entirely real.</p><h2>Part Four: Three Food Streets — Which One?</h2><p>| Food Street | Character | Best For | Best Time | |------|------|--------|----------| | <strong>Guijie</strong> | A 24-hour street that never sleeps; birthplace of Beijing''s spicy crayfish craze; 1.5 kilometres of spicy hotpot, crayfish, and grilled fish restaurants | Young visitors who want to experience Beijing''s nightlife | Gets lively after 10:00 PM | | <strong>Huguo Temple Snack Street</strong> | The concentrated home of old Beijing street snacks; worn and traditional | Foreign visitors who want to sample classic snacks in one stop | Breakfast and lunch | | <strong>Wangfujing Snack Street</strong> | <strong>Abandoned by locals since around 2016 and redeveloped in the 2020s</strong> | Not recommended | — | | <strong>Qianmen Avenue / Xianyu Kou</strong> | South of Tiananmen; rebuilt Ming-Qing-style historic street; home of state-owned heritage brands like Quanjude | Group tours; first-time visitors | Daytime | | <strong>Sanlitun</strong> | Beijing''s most international dining zone: Michelin restaurants, Western cuisine, trending cafes | Upmarket visitors, travellers who follow food trends | Dinner and late supper | | <strong>Wudaoying Hutong</strong> | A laid-back creative dining street near Yonghegong; cafes, Western bistros, wine bars | Leisurely afternoon visitors | From 2:00 PM |</p><h3>Going Deep on Guijie (For Night Owls)</h3><p>Guijie''s most famous item is <strong>spicy crayfish</strong> — which arrived from Hubei in the late 1990s and exploded in popularity here. Order a basin of crayfish, a round of beers, and settle in past midnight. This is the flavour of contemporary Beijing youth.</p><ul><li><strong>Huda Restaurant (Guijie Main Branch)</strong>: The most iconic crayfish on the street. Queuing at midnight is standard — consider arriving at 4:00 PM to collect your queue number.</li><li><strong>Hua Jia Yi Yuan</strong>: Old-school Beijing cuisine in a Guijie location — a more reliable choice overall.</li></ul><h2>Part Five: The Michelin Era — Beijing Fine Dining Today</h2><p>If you are willing to spend more on food (800 to 3,000 RMB per person), Beijing has developed in the past five years into a world-class fine dining destination. The Michelin Guide Beijing 2026, published on 29 October 2025, awarded three stars to Xin Rong Ji (Xinyuan South Road) and Chao Shang Chao (Chaoyang), gave two stars to six restaurants, and awarded one star to 24 restaurants.</p><h3>2026 Three-Star Restaurants (Beijing has just 2)</h3><p>#### 1. Chao Shang Chao (Chaoyang) <strong>Teochew Cuisine</strong> | 1,500+ RMB per person | Chaoyang District</p><p>The inaugural Michelin Mentor Chef Award — the first of its kind in mainland China — was presented to head chef Zhang Yifeng of Chao Shang Chao. Teochew cuisine is the branch of Cantonese cooking most dedicated to preserving natural flavours, with a particular strength in slow-braised seafood and delicate sweet soups.</p><p>#### 2. Xin Rong Ji (Xinyuan South Road) <strong>Taizhou Cuisine (East Zhejiang Seafood)</strong> | 1,500 to 3,000 RMB per person | Chaoyang District</p><p>A sustained multi-year three-star holder. Must-try dishes include family-braised yellow croaker, pan-seared ribbonfish, and honey-glazed sweet potato. Xin Rong Ji''s defining philosophy is "mastering a single fish" — it is the benchmark restaurant for Eastern-style Chinese fine dining.</p><h3>Two Stars and Notable One-Star Restaurants</h3><p>| Restaurant | Cuisine | What Makes It Stand Out | |------|------|------| | <strong>King''s Joy</strong> | Premium vegetarian | Holds both the Michelin Green Star for sustainability and two stars; near Yonghegong Lama Temple; <strong>strongly recommended for vegetarian or Buddhist visitors</strong> | | <strong>Blackswan</strong> (promoted to two stars in 2026) | Creative cuisine | Elevated from one to two stars in 2026 | | <strong>Dadong (Tuanjiehu Branch)</strong> | New-wave Beijing cuisine | The originator of the roast duck-meets-contemporary plating approach | | <strong>Opera Bombana</strong> | Italian | Beijing''s best Italian restaurant | | <strong>TIAGO Cucina Italiana</strong> | Italian | Sanlitun; one Michelin star |</p><h2>Part Six: One Week of Eating Beijing — the Practical Itinerary</h2><p>For a stay of five to seven days, here is a full eating plan <strong>optimised by geography and time of day</strong> to avoid crisscrossing the city:</p><h3>Day 1: Central Axis Day (Forbidden City)</h3><ul><li><strong>Morning</strong>: Hotel breakfast</li><li><strong>Lunch</strong>: <strong>Siji Minfu (Forbidden City Branch) Peking Duck</strong> — exit the Forbidden City at the Gate of Divine Prowess and walk five minutes; window seats overlook the palace moat</li><li><strong>Afternoon tea</strong>: A small teahouse opposite Jingshan Park for a covered bowl of tea</li><li><strong>Dinner</strong>: <strong>Kaorouji at Shichahai</strong> — a venerable Halal grilled-meat restaurant with a lakeside setting</li></ul><h3>Day 2: Great Wall Day</h3><ul><li><strong>6:30 AM</strong>: Hotel breakfast before departing (no good food options en route)</li><li><strong>Lunch</strong>: Rainbow trout at the foot of Mutianyu (a Huairou local speciality — freshwater trout grilled over open flame)</li><li><strong>Dinner</strong>: Back in the city — <strong>Huda Restaurant for Guijie crayfish</strong> (if energy allows)</li></ul><h3>Day 3: Temple of Heaven + Summer Palace</h3><ul><li><strong>6:30 AM</strong>: <strong>Old Ciqi Kou Douzhir Shop</strong> (just outside the Temple of Heaven north gate) — drink the Douzhir and eat the crispy rings; consider it becoming a Beijinger before entering the temple</li><li><strong>Lunch</strong>: <strong>Tingli Guan</strong> near the Summer Palace''s east gate (a restaurant built inside the former imperial kitchen, serving Qing dynasty-style palace cuisine from the Empress Dowager era)</li><li><strong>Dinner</strong>: <strong>Jingwei Xiaoguan</strong>, a small Beijing-style restaurant near the south gate of the Old Summer Palace</li></ul><h3>Day 4: Yonghegong + 798</h3><ul><li><strong>Morning</strong>: Cafe in Wudaoying Hutong</li><li><strong>Lunch</strong>: <strong>King''s Joy</strong> premium vegetarian — five minutes'' walk from Yonghegong Lama Temple</li><li><strong>Afternoon tea</strong>: Coffee at a cafe inside 798 Art District</li><li><strong>Dinner</strong>: Your choice of Michelin restaurant in Sanlitun (<strong>Xin Rong Ji, Xinyuan South Road branch</strong> is recommended)</li></ul><h3>Day 5: Niujie + Fayuan Temple</h3><ul><li><strong>Morning</strong>: Take away Baiji Nian Gao rice cake from Niujie</li><li><strong>Lunch</strong>: <strong>Jubaoyuan hotpot</strong> (arrive early to avoid the queue)</li><li><strong>Afternoon</strong>: Walk to Fayuan Temple</li><li><strong>Dinner</strong>: <strong>Hongji Snacks</strong> on Niujie</li></ul><h3>Day 6 (if you have it): Deep Hutong Day</h3><ul><li><strong>5:30 AM</strong>: Wake up — <strong>Yaoji Chaogan (Drum Tower Branch)</strong> for chaogan with steamed buns</li><li><strong>Lunch</strong>: <strong>Fangzhuanchang Zhajiangmian</strong> (north end of Nanluoguxiang)</li><li><strong>Afternoon</strong>: Hutong walk + small local cafes</li><li><strong>Dinner</strong>: <strong>Liqun Roast Duck</strong> — the full hutong-hidden Peking duck experience</li></ul><h2>Part Seven: Practical Tips for International Visitors</h2><h3>1. Payment (Most Important)</h3><p><strong>Almost all Beijing restaurants accept Alipay or WeChat Pay, and many no longer take cash.</strong> Before you leave:</p><ul><li>Download <strong>Alipay</strong> international version and link a foreign credit card (Visa, Mastercard, or American Express)</li><li>Or use <strong>WeChat Pay international version</strong> (slightly fewer features, but sufficient)</li><li>The WeChat mini-program <strong>Alipay Tour Pass</strong> is a prepaid card for short-term visitors — <strong>the most convenient option</strong></li></ul><p>Michelin restaurants and high-end hotels accept international credit cards, but <strong>hutong small restaurants accept mobile payment only</strong>.</p><h3>2. Ordering Food</h3><ul><li><strong>Download Google Translate offline pack</strong> (Google services are blocked in China, but the offline pack works) or use <strong>Microsoft Translator</strong></li><li>Dianping (the Chinese Yelp) is the most useful app for reading restaurant reviews in 2026 — the most reliable signal of a genuinely good place: a queue of elderly locals</li><li>Michelin restaurants all have English menus; most hutong small restaurants do not — pointing at what the next table is eating is a completely legitimate strategy</li></ul><h3>3. No Tipping</h3><p><strong>Mainland China has no tipping culture.</strong> Michelin restaurants automatically add a 10 to 15 percent service charge; everywhere else, no tip is needed or expected. Leaving a tip makes the staff feel awkward rather than appreciated.</p><h3>4. Spiciness</h3><p>Beijing cuisine itself is <strong>not spicy</strong>, but Sichuan and Hunan restaurants are everywhere. If you cannot handle heat, <strong>say "Bu yao la" (no spice) or "Hen shao la" (very little spice)</strong> when ordering.</p><h3>5. Food Safety</h3><ul><li>Street jianbing carts: choose <strong>the busiest ones</strong> — high turnover means fresher ingredients</li><li>Grilled skewers: choose Halal stalls run by <strong>Hui or Uyghur owners</strong> (food safety standards are generally stricter)</li><li>Seafood: Beijing is inland — <strong>don''t chase seafood</strong> unless you are eating at a top-tier restaurant like Xin Rong Ji, which can guarantee quality</li><li>Tap water: <strong>Never drink it directly.</strong> Bottled water is available everywhere.</li></ul><h3>6. Vegetarian and Vegan Dining</h3><p>Chinese restaurants have a weak understanding of strict veganism — "vegetable dishes" often contain small amounts of meat stock or lard. For strict plant-based eating:</p><ul><li>Go directly to <strong>King''s Joy</strong> (Michelin Green Star vegetarian)</li><li>Or Buddhist vegetarian restaurants near major temples (near Yonghegong or Jietai Temple)</li><li>Simple approach: say "Wo chi su" (I''m vegetarian) and specify "Bu yao rou, bu yao yu, bu yao ji" (no meat, no fish, no chicken)</li></ul><h3>7. Queuing</h3><p><strong>Popular restaurants always have queues</strong> — Siji Minfu, Jubaoyuan, and Huda Restaurant can mean one to two hours on weekends. <strong>Solutions</strong>:</p><ul><li>The Dianping app allows you to join a virtual queue remotely</li><li>Or arrive outside of the 12:00–1:00 PM and 6:30–8:00 PM peak windows</li><li>Michelin restaurants must be booked in advance</li></ul><h3>8. What to Bring Home</h3><ul><li><strong>Vacuum-packed roast duck gift boxes</strong>: Siji Minfu, Dadong, and Quanjude all sell them; airline-safe</li><li><strong>Lv Da Gun / Wandou Huang and other pastries</strong>: Short shelf life of two to three days; not suitable for long journeys</li><li><strong>Tea</strong>: Zhang Yiyuan, Wu Yutai, Maliandao Tea Market — absolutely worth it</li><li><strong>Erguotou (Beijing baijiu white spirit)</strong>: Red Star Erguotou is around 15 RMB a bottle in supermarkets; makes a good souvenir</li></ul><p>*May every meal you have in Beijing leave a lasting mark on your memory of this city. Bon appétit.*</p>',
  '[]'::jsonb,
  1,
  TRUE
) ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
