INSERT INTO city_guides (
  id, city_id, title_en, title_zh, subtitle, icon, badge,
  cover_images, body, meta_items, display_order, is_published
) VALUES (
  'beijing_coffee',
  'beijing',
  'Beijing Independent Coffee Guide · Top 10 Must-Visit Cafes',
  '北京独立咖啡体验指南 · Top 10 必打卡清单',
  'How these were chosen: From over 6,000 cafes in Beijing, these ten were selected based on five criteria: independent spirit, spatial distinctiveness, coffee qua',
  '☕',
  NULL,
  ARRAY[]::TEXT[],
  '<h2>1. Metal Hands</h2><p>📍 6 Nanyang Hutong, Dongcheng District (Former Beijing Ballet Theater)</p><p>Ranked among the world''s Top 50 specialty coffee shops — the only entry from Asia on the list. Housed in a converted ballet theater, the industrial-retro space spans three floors, with a signature "time tunnel" copper corridor connecting the coffee and dining areas. The standout order is the <strong>Happy Ghost Dirty</strong> — the rim is coated in crushed pistachios and the espresso is rich and full-bodied. The pour-over single-origin menu is extensive, featuring primarily Panama and Ethiopia beans. Sitting at the bar counter is recommended for a close-up view of the baristas at work.</p><h2>2. Soloist Coffee</h2><p>📍 39 Yangmeizhu Xiejie, Xicheng District</p><p>A pioneer of specialty coffee in Beijing, founded in this hutong back in 2014. The American vintage-industrial interior is filled with old lamps, globes, and typewriters. The second-floor terrace overlooks the grey-tiled rooftops of old Beijing, with a view toward the former site of Qingyun Pavilion — where the legendary meeting between Cai E and Xiao Fengxian is said to have taken place. The specialty here is <strong>pour-over single-origin coffee</strong>, brewed by baristas who are almost obsessive about water temperature, grind size, and extraction. Perfect for slowing down and savoring a cup amid a room full of vintage objects.</p><h2>3. Voyage Coffee</h2><p>📍 22 Yangmeizhu Xiejie, Xicheng District (also at Nanluoguxiang, Sanlihe, and 798)</p><p>A benchmark of minimalist design — grey-tiled roofs, floor-to-ceiling glass walls, an old courtyard tree. The menu is intentionally spare: just a few classic coffees paired with three house-roasted single-origin beans — <strong>Black Forest</strong> (deep roast, full-bodied), <strong>Red Cherry</strong> (bright, fruity acidity), and <strong>Zero</strong> (balanced and smooth). The Yangmeizhu branch transforms a hutong residence into an open courtyard space, which turns golden with ginkgo leaves in autumn. Great for a rest stop during a city walk — order a pour-over and settle in under the tree.</p><h2>4. CABO Coffee / Polonio</h2><p>📍 CABO: Inside the DE&amp;E Creative Park, 13 Beijing Street, Dongcheng District / Polonio: 81 Gongmenkou Dongcha, Xicheng District</p><p>The owner studied in Australia, and the brand name comes from Cabo Polonio, a coastal headland in Uruguay. The philosophy is "Australian craft, Latin soul" — flat white foam is precisely controlled between 3 and 5 millimetres. Signature drinks include the Sydney Dirty (with ice cream) and creative specials like the Hong Kong Garden (coconut water, tamarind juice, espresso) and the Sunshine Coast (tonic water, espresso, black tea). The Polonio branch has a second-floor terrace with a direct view of the White Dagoba at Miaoying Temple. Pet-friendly.</p><h2>5. Me and Ditan · THE CORNER</h2><p>📍 Hepingli South Street, Dongcheng District (100 metres east of Ditan Park''s east gate, inside the B+ Automobile Service Experience Center)</p><p>Named after the celebrated essay "Me and Ditan" by Chinese writer Shi Tiesheng. Designed by Neri &amp; Hu Design and Research Office, the three-story industrial space features a tall-ceilinged lounge with a bar on the ground floor, a floating communal table on the second, and a silent study room on the third. The exterior vermilion red wall has become a popular photography spot. Handmade pastries and specialty coffee are served — the most authentic experience is to take your coffee to go and read under the ancient cypress trees inside Ditan Park.</p><h2>6. Tangfang Coffee</h2><p>📍 22 Qianhai East Bank, Shichahai, Xicheng District (Floors 3 and 4, Qingyun Lou Restaurant)</p><p>A four-story rooftop cafe beside the Silver Ingot Bridge at Shichahai, offering one of Beijing''s most recognisable skyline views: rowboats on Houhai lake and hutong rooftops to the left, the Drum Tower straight ahead, and the CBD skyline of Guomao to the right. The best time to visit is <strong>around sunset</strong>, when the light spills gold across the water. Standard espresso drinks and pastries are reliably good. Visiting on a weekday afternoon is recommended to avoid the crowds.</p><h2>7. il gatto coffee</h2><p>📍 1 Xiushui East Street, Chaoyang District (across from the Embassy of Guyana)</p><p>A minimalist white space tucked inside the Ritan embassy district. The owner, known as "Lao Zhao," is a legend in Beijing''s coffee scene with more than a decade dedicated to specialty coffee. The signature drink is the <strong>White Night</strong> — silky-smooth iced milk combined with espresso; the <strong>Bloodhound</strong> is a bolder, more adventurous special. The shop is small, but the atmosphere is quiet and understated. Embassy staff and expats are regulars, and the team is English-friendly.</p><h2>8. Wolfing Coffee Museum</h2><p>📍 Slow Life Park, Wanhong Road, Chaoyang District (near 798 Art District)</p><p>Covering 2,850 square metres, this complex combines a coffee museum, roasting factory, and experience workshop under one roof. Drinks are served at the front while roasting happens at the back. Highlights include a <strong>robot barista</strong>, a world coffee-origin map wall, and an antique coffee machine exhibition tracing a century of history. A DIY dessert area and pour-over workshops are also on offer (88 to 139 RMB per person). You could easily spend half a day here — ideal for rainy days or dedicated coffee enthusiasts.</p><h2>9. Fusan Coffee</h2><p>📍 22 Art Museum East Street, Dongcheng District (next to the National Art Museum of China)</p><p>The brand traces its roots to a 1959 Faema E59 lever espresso machine, which still stands on display inside the shop. The red-brick industrial space is blanketed in wall-to-wall greenery — a striking visual combination. The signature <strong>coconut milk Dirty</strong> is layered and complex in flavour. The Art Museum branch is close to Longfusi Temple and Nanluoguxiang, with a dedicated study area. The Xixinglong Street branch near Qianmen carries more of that old Beijing neighbourhood energy.</p><h2>10. Hong''en Temple Cafe</h2><p>📍 21 Doufuchi Hutong, Dongcheng District (inside Hong''en Temple, 200 metres north of the Bell Tower)</p><p>Hidden inside Hong''en Temple, a Taoist sanctuary with 700 years of history dating to the Yuan dynasty — said to be the "tail of the dragon" along Beijing''s central axis. The space has soaring ceilings and an ancient courtyard that is wonderful for sitting in the sun. The signature offering is the <strong>"One Bean, Three Ways" tasting set</strong> — the same coffee bean presented as a pour-over, cold drip, and milk coffee, so you can compare the flavour profile across all three methods. The owner personally explains the bean variety and brewing process, making this an immersive coffee culture experience.</p><h2>Quick Reference by District</h2><p>| District | Cafes | |------|--------| | <strong>Qianmen / Yangmeizhu Xiejie</strong> | Soloist Coffee, Voyage Coffee | | <strong>Drum Tower / Shichahai</strong> | Tangfang Coffee, Hong''en Temple Cafe | | <strong>Art Museum / Dongsi</strong> | Fusan Coffee, Metal Hands | | <strong>Ditan / Hepingli</strong> | Me and Ditan THE CORNER | | <strong>Ritan / Embassy District</strong> | il gatto coffee | | <strong>White Dagoba / Fuchengmen</strong> | CABO Polonio | | <strong>Temple of Heaven / South City</strong> | CABO Coffee, Temple of Heaven Branch | | <strong>798 / Wangjing</strong> | Wolfing Coffee |</p><h2>Itinerary Map</h2><p>``` Beijing Independent Coffee Tour ├── Hutong Cultural Route: Yangmeizhu Xiejie │   ├── Soloist Coffee → Pour-Over + Vintage Rooftop Terrace │   └── Voyage Coffee → Minimalist Courtyard + House-Roasted Beans ├── Central Axis Heritage Route: Drum Tower – Shichahai – Bell Tower │   ├── Tangfang Coffee → Four-Story Rooftop Overlooking Houhai Lake │   └── Hong''en Temple Cafe → 700-Year-Old Taoist Temple Tasting Experience ├── Cultural Arts Route: Art Museum – Dongsi – Ditan │   ├── Fusan Coffee → 1959 Vintage Machine + Red-Brick Space │   ├── Metal Hands → Converted Ballet Theater + Global Top 50 │   └── Me and Ditan → Neri &amp; Hu Design + Red Wall Courtyard ├── Embassy District / White Dagoba │   ├── il gatto → Minimalist White Space + Legendary Owner │   └── CABO Polonio → Rooftop Terrace Facing the White Dagoba └── 798 Art District ├── CABO Coffee 798 Branch → Beach-Themed Space └── Wolfing Coffee → 2,850-sqm Coffee Museum ```</p><h2>Travel Tips</h2><ul><li><strong>Reservations</strong>: Hong''en Temple requires advance booking through the official "Beijing Hong''en Temple" WeChat public account. Pour-over workshops at Wolfing Coffee are also best reserved ahead of time.</li><li><strong>Timing</strong>: Hutong cafes typically open after 10:00 AM. Popular spots fill up on weekend afternoons — mornings or weekdays are quieter.</li><li><strong>Payment</strong>: Most independent cafes accept WeChat Pay and Alipay. Some accept international credit cards. Having a small amount of cash on hand is a good idea.</li><li><strong>Getting There</strong>: In hutong areas, take the subway and walk or rent a bike. For 798, a taxi or rideshare is more practical. Yangmeizhu Xiejie is a short walk from Qianmen subway station.</li><li><strong>Language</strong>: Metal Hands, CABO, and il gatto are all English-friendly. Most hutong cafes have menus with English labels.</li></ul><p>*All information is based on publicly available sources from 2024 to 2026. Actual prices, menus, and opening hours are subject to each cafe''s official announcements.*</p>',
  '[]'::jsonb,
  2,
  TRUE
) ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
  city_id = EXCLUDED.city_id,
  title_en = EXCLUDED.title_en,
  title_zh = EXCLUDED.title_zh,
  subtitle = EXCLUDED.subtitle,
  icon = EXCLUDED.icon,
  badge = EXCLUDED.badge,
  cover_images = EXCLUDED.cover_images,
  body = EXCLUDED.body,
  meta_items = EXCLUDED.meta_items,
  audio_url = NULL,
  audio_title = NULL,
  audio_duration_seconds = 0,
  audio_quote = NULL,
  audio_transcript = NULL,
  display_order = EXCLUDED.display_order,
  is_published = EXCLUDED.is_published,
  updated_at = NOW();

INSERT INTO city_guides (
  id, city_id, title_en, title_zh, subtitle, icon, badge,
  cover_images, body, meta_items, display_order, is_published
) VALUES (
  'beijing_hutong_citywalk',
  'beijing',
  'Beijing Hutong Citywalk Guide',
  '北京胡同Citywalk旅行指南',
  NULL,
  '🚶',
  'Citywalk',
  ARRAY[]::TEXT[],
  '<p>Beijing''s hutongs are the living fossils of the city''s history and a museum of everyday life. This guide presents three classic Citywalk routes to take you into the heart of Beijing''s hutong culture.</p><h2>Route One: Yonghe Temple — Wudaoying Hutong</h2><p><strong>Route overview</strong>: Yonghe Temple → Wudaoying Hutong → Guozijian Hutong → Beiluoguxiang → Bell and Drum Towers → Yandai Xiejie → Shichahai</p><p><strong>Total distance</strong>: About 1.2 kilometres</p><p><strong>Recommended duration</strong>: 2 to 3 hours</p><p><strong>Best season</strong>: Good year-round; early winter mornings or spring evenings are especially fine</p><p><strong>How to get around</strong>: Walking and shared bikes</p><h2>Yonghe Temple (Lama Temple)</h2><h3>Introduction<strong>: Yonghe Temple is one of Beijing''s most historically significant Tibetan Buddhist temples, built in 1723 as the private residence of the Yongzheng Emperor before being converted into a Tibetan Buddhist monastery. The temple preserves a wealth of Buddhist cultural objects, including exquisite mandalas and thangka paintings. </strong>Its architecture blends Han Chinese and Tibetan styles, and the red walls with golden rooftops create a striking visual impact.</h3><h2>Highlights:</h2><ul><li><strong>Main Hall</strong>: The principal hall enshrines a Maitreya Buddha statue carved from a single piece of sandalwood, standing about 26 metres tall — one of the largest Buddhist statues in Beijing</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Dharma Objects Shop</strong>: A place to purchase prayer beads and amulets with religious significance</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Red Walls and White Stupa</strong>: The temple''s crimson perimeter wall and white Buddhist stupa together form one of Beijing''s classic landmark silhouettes</li></ul><h2>Practical information:</h2><ul><li>Opening hours: 8 a.m. to 5 p.m. (closed Mondays)</li></ul><ul><li>Admission: 25 yuan per person</li></ul><ul><li>Getting there: Take Line 2 to Andingmen Station, Exit A, then walk about 5 minutes</li></ul><ul><li>Suggested visit time: 45 to 60 minutes</li></ul><p><strong>Cultural context</strong>: Yonghe Temple has witnessed the political transitions of the early Qing dynasty. In 1722, when the Yongzheng Emperor ascended the throne and moved to the Forbidden City, the palace was eventually transformed into a Buddhist temple — an expression of the traditional Chinese concept of biding one''s time before the moment is right. <strong>The Tibetan Buddhist elements inside — mandalas and thangka paintings — stand as important testimony to the cultural exchange between Han and Tibetan peoples.</strong> When visiting, follow the traditional Tibetan practice of walking through the temple in a clockwise direction.</p><h2>Wudaoying Hutong</h2><p><strong>Introduction</strong>: Wudaoying Hutong blends tradition and modernity in a quieter, more artistic atmosphere than its more commercial neighbour Nanluoguxiang. While Nanluoguxiang has been heavily commercialised, Wudaoying preserves much of its original hutong character while welcoming a cluster of distinctive independent shops, cafes, and design studios, many run by expatriates or Chinese who have lived abroad.</p><h2>Highlights:</h2><ul><li><strong>CHOOCHOO COFFEE</strong>: A popular cafe styled after a train carriage</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Sanyuan Meiyuan</strong>: A traditional dessert shop offering rich, creamy double-steamed milk pudding and other classic sweets</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Hutong streetscape</strong>: Strolling along the stone-paved lane with its grey-tiled rooftops and traditional courtyard houses on either side</li></ul><h2>Practical information:</h2><ul><li>Opening hours: Open at all times</li></ul><ul><li>Admission: Free</li></ul><ul><li>Getting there: About a 10-minute walk from Yonghe Temple</li></ul><ul><li>Suggested visit time: 30 to 45 minutes</li></ul><p><strong>Cultural context</strong>: Wudaoying Hutong traces its origins to the Yuan dynasty, when it served as a site for imperial stables. <strong>Today the hutong retains its traditional herringbone grid layout — a reflection of ancient Chinese city planning wisdom.</strong> The shops here tend to be small, independent brands, reflecting Beijing''s identity as a cosmopolitan city where cultures mix and mingle. On a winter afternoon, settle into a floor-to-ceiling window seat at one of the cafes with a hot drink and watch the snow settle on the grey rooftiles outside — the ideal way to experience the quiet, contemplative mood of a Beijing hutong.</p><h2>Beiluoguxiang (North Luogu Lane)</h2><p><strong>Introduction</strong>: Beiluoguxiang sits just one street away from Nanluoguxiang yet offers a completely different experience. <strong>It retains far more of the genuine texture of old Beijing life, in sharp contrast to the heavier commercialisation next door.</strong> The lane includes several distinctive spaces, such as Yi Xi Zhi Di — a cultural venue converted from a traditional courtyard house.</p><h2>Highlights:</h2><ul><li><strong>Yi Xi Zhi Di</strong>: A cultural space adapted from a courtyard, offering a tea-by-the-fire experience</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Rooftop terrace</strong>: From the rooftop of Yi Xi Zhi Di, you can look out over a continuous sea of grey-tiled rooftops in every direction</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Hutong streetscape</strong>: In autumn and winter, the white ash trees lining the lane turn golden, and their yellow leaves play off the red window frames and grey tiles — a scene that could be lifted straight from a painting of old Beiping</li></ul><h2>Practical information:</h2><ul><li>Opening hours: Open at all times</li></ul><ul><li>Admission: Free (a minimum spend applies at Yi Xi Zhi Di)</li></ul><ul><li>Getting there: About a 15-minute walk from Wudaoying Hutong</li></ul><ul><li>Suggested visit time: 45 to 60 minutes</li></ul><p><strong>Cultural context</strong>: Beiluoguxiang''s origins reach back to the Yuan dynasty, when it formed part of the drainage system of the Yuan capital Dadu. <strong>The lane takes its name from the "north drum" — an ancient timekeeping instrument of the Ming dynasty — reflecting China''s traditional relationship with time and sound.</strong> Today Beiluoguxiang is one of the best places to find the authentic spirit of old Beijing, with many of its shops converted from residents'' own courtyard homes, preserving traditional ways of living. Here you can feel the essence of Beijing''s unhurried pace, engage with local residents, and see hutong culture up close.</p><h2>Bell and Drum Towers</h2><h3>Introduction<strong>: The Bell and Drum Towers mark the northern high point of Beijing''s Central Axis, a pair of buildings that together formed the ancient city''s timekeeping centre. </strong>Both structures once rang out the hours across the city — drum performances still take place on the hour today, making these a wonderful place to experience ancient time culture.</h3><h2>Highlights:</h2><ul><li><strong>Bell Tower</strong>: Climb to the top for a panoramic view of the surrounding hutong courtyard rooftops</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Drum Tower</strong>: On-the-hour drumming performances to experience the ancient ritual of marking time</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Red Walls under Snow</strong>: In winter, the vermilion walls and snow-capped heavy eaves create a scene of austere, timeless beauty</li></ul><h2>Practical information:</h2><ul><li>Opening hours: 8:30 a.m. to 5 p.m. (closed Mondays)</li></ul><ul><li>Admission: Drum Tower 20 yuan; Bell Tower 10 yuan</li></ul><ul><li>Getting there: About a 15-minute walk from Beiluoguxiang</li></ul><ul><li>Suggested visit time: 30 to 45 minutes</li></ul><h3>Cultural context<strong>: The Bell and Drum Towers were first built in the Yuan dynasty and rebuilt during the Ming and Qing dynasties. </strong>The Drum Tower was used to beat out the hours; the Bell Tower rang the bell — together they formed the timekeeping system of ancient Beijing.<strong> This method of marking time remained in use until 1924, when modern clocks took over. The Bell Tower houses a bronze bell weighing 46.5 tonnes — the heaviest surviving ancient bell in Beijing. </strong>Visiting the Bell and Drum Towers offers a window into ancient Chinese astronomical calendar-keeping and the way cities were managed and ordered.</h3><h2>Yandai Xiejie (Tobacco Pipe Alley)</h2><h3>Introduction<strong>: Yandai Xiejie is a century-old oblique alley connecting the Drum Tower to Shichahai, just 232 metres long. </strong>Its shape resembles a tobacco pipe — the alley itself is the stem, the eastern entrance is the mouthpiece, and the western end opens onto Yinding Bridge like the bowl — making it one of the most distinctive lanes in Beijing.</h3><h2>Highlights:</h2><ul><li><strong>Qing Dynasty Postal Cabinet shop</strong>: A shop with a bright orange frontage where you can stamp hutong-themed postcards and keepsakes</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Litong Store</strong>: A century-old antique shop displaying tobacco pipes, copper locks, and other objects from the late Qing and Republican eras</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Eight Beijing Delicacies gift box</strong>: Traditional pastries from Daoxiangcun, with vintage packaging that makes an ideal old-Beijing souvenir</li></ul><h2>Practical information:</h2><ul><li>Opening hours: Open at all times</li></ul><ul><li>Admission: Free</li></ul><ul><li>Getting there: About a 5-minute walk from the Bell and Drum Towers</li></ul><ul><li>Suggested visit time: 30 to 45 minutes</li></ul><p><strong>Cultural context</strong>: Yandai Xiejie dates from the Yuan dynasty and was once an upscale commercial street serving the nobility. <strong>The name "Yandai" (tobacco pipe) comes from the Qing dynasty, when a fine tobacco pipe was a status symbol among the aristocracy, and the street became famous for its concentration of tobacco craftsmen.</strong> Today the alley no longer specialises in pipes, but it retains the atmosphere of a traditional commercial street, with shops ranging from generations-old established names to contemporary creative studios. Stop and talk with the shopkeepers to hear 600 years of history in the stories of a single lane.</p><h2>Shichahai (the Three Back Lakes)</h2><h3>Introduction<strong>: Shichahai is Beijing''s largest urban lake complex, made up of the Front Lake, the Back Lake, and the West Lake — collectively known as the "back three lakes." </strong>As the planning baseline for the Yuan dynasty capital Dadu, Shichahai laid the foundations for Beijing''s Central Axis and the layout of its inner-city streets and lanes during the Ming and Qing dynasties. Its historical and cultural significance is profound.</h3><h2>Highlights:</h2><ul><li><strong>Ice rink</strong>: In winter, Shichahai freezes into a vast natural ice rink for skating and ice activities</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Lotus market</strong>: In summer, the lotus flowers bloom across the water — one of the city''s most beautiful sights</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Lakeside views</strong>: In all four seasons, the views across Shichahai are beautiful in their own distinct way</li></ul><h2>Practical information:</h2><ul><li>Opening hours: Open at all times (ice rink hours depend on weather conditions)</li></ul><ul><li>Admission: Free (ice rink requires a separate ticket, approximately 50 yuan per person)</li></ul><ul><li>Getting there: About a 10-minute walk from Yandai Xiejie</li></ul><ul><li>Suggested visit time: 60 to 90 minutes</li></ul><h3>Cultural context<strong>: Shichahai holds a unique place in the story of Beijing''s development. As the planning baseline for the Yuan capital, it shaped the Central Axis and street grid that define the old city to this day. </strong>Once the terminus of the ancient Grand Canal where thousands of boats converged, Shichahai carries the rich heritage of canal culture and is the defining jewel of old Beijing''s waterfront life.<strong> Today it is a beloved gathering place for residents — a natural ice rink in winter, pleasure boats in summer, and its own character in every season. </strong>A visit to Shichahai traces the arc of Beijing''s urban history while giving you a direct experience of old Beijing''s relationship with its waterways.</h3><h2>Route Two: Nanluoguxiang</h2><p><strong>Route overview</strong>: Nanluoguxiang → Beiluoguxiang → Drum Tower → Shichahai</p><p><strong>Total distance</strong>: About 3 kilometres</p><p><strong>Recommended duration</strong>: 3 to 4 hours</p><p><strong>Best season</strong>: Good year-round; summer evenings or autumn afternoons are especially fine</p><p><strong>How to get around</strong>: Walking</p><h2>Nanluoguxiang</h2><h3>Introduction<strong>: Nanluoguxiang is one of Beijing''s oldest neighbourhoods, running north to south with 16 hutong lanes arranged symmetrically on its east and west sides. </strong>As Beijing''s best-preserved Yuan dynasty hutong, Nanluoguxiang has been called the "first hutong of the capital city" and is an ideal place to experience old Beijing''s commercial street culture.</h3><h2>Highlights:</h2><ul><li><strong>Hutong panoramic map</strong>: A large map is posted on the wall at the entrance — good for photos and planning your route</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Distinctive shops</strong>: Including the Blue and White Store, a panda-themed shop, and many other eclectic independent retailers</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Street food</strong>: Try zhajiang noodles, lüdagun (sticky rice rolls coated in soybean powder), and baofu (tripe) — classic Beijing street snacks</li></ul><h2>Practical information:</h2><ul><li>Opening hours: Open at all times</li></ul><ul><li>Admission: Free</li></ul><ul><li>Getting there: Take Line 6 or Line 8 to Nanluoguxiang Station, Exit E</li></ul><ul><li>Suggested visit time: 60 to 90 minutes</li></ul><h3>Cultural context<strong>: Nanluoguxiang''s history reaches back to the Yuan dynasty — the name "South Luo" referred to one of the ancient timekeeping instruments. </strong>This hutong has witnessed the full arc of Beijing''s development: from a military defensive function in the Yuan dynasty, to a residential neighbourhood in the Ming and Qing periods, to a tourist commercial street in the modern era.<strong> While heavily commercialised today, it still preserves the traditional hutong grid and architectural character. </strong>A walk through Nanluoguxiang is a walk through the layers of Beijing''s urban history.</h3><h2>Cat Yard</h2><h3>Introduction<strong>: Cat Yard is a cat-themed restaurant set inside a traditional courtyard house near Nanluoguxiang, home to 38 cats and other pets. </strong>It brings together the old Beijing siheyuan courtyard and a modern feline-themed cafe, giving visitors a relaxed urban retreat where they can unwind and spend time with cats.</h3><h2>Highlights:</h2><ul><li><strong>Cat interaction</strong>: Spend time with a variety of resident cats, including Ragdoll, Golden Chinchilla, and Persian breeds</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Signature food</strong>: Signature dishes include Galaxy Roast Chicken Rice and Curry Brisket Rice</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Atmosphere</strong>: A warm courtyard interior with a tea room, outdoor terrace, and relaxed leisure spaces</li></ul><h2>Practical information:</h2><ul><li>Opening hours: 11 a.m. to 9 p.m.</li></ul><ul><li>Admission: Minimum spend applies (approximately 40 to 68 yuan per hour)</li></ul><ul><li>Getting there: At 20 Ju''er Hutong, off Nanluoguxiang — walkable from the main street</li></ul><ul><li>Suggested visit time: 30 to 60 minutes</li></ul><h3>Cultural context<strong>: Cat Yard represents the meeting of Beijing''s hutong culture and the modern world of pets and lifestyle. </strong>Beijingers have long had a tradition of keeping cats, and the "hutong cat" is a part of Beijing''s urban identity.<strong> Cat Yard has breathed new life into this tradition and become a distinctive way to experience old Beijing neighbourhoods. The variety of cat breeds inside reflects the cosmopolitan character of modern city life. </strong>Here, visitors can get a feel for how Beijingers live day to day and experience the warmth and inclusivity of hutong culture.</h3><h2>Drum Tower</h2><h3>Introduction<strong>: The Drum Tower is one of the key buildings on Beijing''s Central Axis, first built in the Yuan dynasty and rebuilt in the Ming dynasty. </strong>It was the timekeeping centre of ancient Beijing, where drums were beaten on the hour — an important place for understanding China''s ancient relationship with time.</h3><h2>Highlights:</h2><ul><li><strong>Red exterior walls</strong>: The Drum Tower''s vermilion outer walls make an immediate visual impression</li></ul><ul><li><strong>On-the-hour drum performances</strong>: Hourly drumming shows to experience the ancient time-marking ritual</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Views of the hutongs</strong>: From the Drum Tower you can look down over a panorama of surrounding courtyard rooftops</li></ul><h2>Practical information:</h2><ul><li>Opening hours: 8:30 a.m. to 5 p.m. (closed Mondays)</li></ul><ul><li>Admission: 20 yuan per person</li></ul><ul><li>Getting there: About a 15-minute walk from Nanluoguxiang</li></ul><ul><li>Suggested visit time: 30 to 45 minutes</li></ul><p><strong>Cultural context</strong>: The Drum Tower was first built in 1276, during the Yuan dynasty, under the name "Sishi Tai" (Time Platform). <strong>It and the Bell Tower together formed Beijing''s ancient timekeeping system, embodying the traditional Chinese understanding of astronomy, the calendar, and the rhythm of daily life.</strong> The massive drum inside the Drum Tower weighs 46.5 tonnes and requires several people to strike together. <strong>The on-the-hour performance is a vivid window into ancient Chinese city management and daily life.</strong> The hutongs surrounding the Drum Tower preserve a strong sense of traditional neighbourhood character — one of the best places to feel old Beijing''s street-level energy.</p><h2>Route Three: Shichahai</h2><p><strong>Route overview</strong>: Yandai Xiejie → Yinding Bridge → Back Lake North Shore → Prince Gong''s Mansion → Desheng Gate</p><p><strong>Total distance</strong>: About 3.5 kilometres</p><p><strong>Recommended duration</strong>: 4 to 5 hours</p><p><strong>Best season</strong>: Good year-round; summer evenings or winter mornings are especially fine</p><p><strong>How to get around</strong>: Walking</p><h2>Yinding Bridge (Silver Ingot Bridge)</h2><h3>Introduction<strong>: Yinding Bridge spans the channel between the Front Lake and the Back Lake of Shichahai and is one of the area''s most iconic landmarks. </strong>Its arched form resembles a silver ingot, and it is the best vantage point for "Viewing Mountains from Silver Ingot Bridge" — one of the Eight Great Sights of old Beijing — making it a favourite destination for photographers.</h3><h2>Highlights:</h2><ul><li><strong>View from the bridge</strong>: Stand at the centre of the bridge to take in the shimmering lake surface, the weeping willows along both banks, and the Bell and Drum Towers in the distance</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Guanghua Temple red wall</strong>: The crimson wall of Guanghua Temple on the west side of the bridge is a popular photography spot</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Hutong walk</strong>: Stroll along the lanes on either side of the bridge and feel the everyday rhythm of old Beijing</li></ul><h2>Practical information:</h2><ul><li>Opening hours: Open at all times</li></ul><ul><li>Admission: Free</li></ul><ul><li>Getting there: About a 5-minute walk from Yandai Xiejie</li></ul><ul><li>Suggested visit time: 30 to 45 minutes</li></ul><h3>Cultural context<strong>: Yinding Bridge was first built during the Zhengtong era of the Ming dynasty (1436 to 1449); the current structure was rebuilt in 1990. </strong>"Viewing Mountains from Silver Ingot Bridge" — the distant prospect of the Western Hills seen from the bridge — is one of the Eight Great Sights of Beijing and an expression of the ancient Chinese ideal of living in harmony with the natural world.<strong> Pedicab drivers near the bridge often offer hutong commentary tours, which are a good way to learn about Shichahai''s long history. </strong>A visit to Yinding Bridge offers a window into Beijing''s water system and hutong culture.</h3><h2>Wild Duck Island</h2><h3>Introduction<strong>: Wild Duck Island sits in the Back Lake section of Shichahai and is a small natural island. </strong>While the name suggests an abundance of wild ducks, the island is actually a pleasant resting and photography spot, adding a gentle finishing touch to the Shichahai landscape.</h3><h2>Highlights:</h2><ul><li><strong>Lake views</strong>: A peaceful vantage point for looking out across Shichahai</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Ducks in winter</strong>: When the lake freezes in winter, wild ducks can be seen moving across the ice</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Leisure space</strong>: Benches and pavilions on the island for a quiet rest</li></ul><h2>Practical information:</h2><ul><li>Opening hours: Open at all times</li></ul><ul><li>Admission: Free</li></ul><ul><li>Getting there: Reachable on foot or by boat from the Back Lake North Shore</li></ul><ul><li>Suggested visit time: 30 to 45 minutes</li></ul><h3>Cultural context<strong>: Wild Duck Island takes its name from the sight of wild ducks gathering on the frozen lake in winter. </strong>While the island itself has no particular historical significance, its name reflects the seasonal ecology of Beijing in winter and gives you a sense of how the natural world changes with the city''s seasons.<strong> The island is ringed with greenery and reeds, complementing the broader Shichahai landscape and creating a rare pocket of natural beauty inside the city. </strong>A visit here is a reminder of the natural world coexisting quietly within the urban fabric of Beijing.</h3><h2>Desheng Gate</h2><h3>Introduction<strong>: Desheng Gate is one of the nine inner gates of Beijing''s old city wall, first built in the second year of the Zhengtong reign of the Ming dynasty (1437). </strong>Originally known as Jiande Gate and used as the departure point for military campaigns, it was later renamed Desheng Gate — meaning "victory through virtue" — embodying traditional Chinese military philosophy and ethics.</h3><h2>Highlights:</h2><ul><li><strong>Arrow tower</strong>: The Ming dynasty-style arrow tower, a fine example of defensive military architecture</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Gate tower</strong>: While the gate tower interior is not currently open to visitors, the exterior is powerfully evocative of the city''s military past</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Desheng Gate Square</strong>: The surrounding hutong streetscape</li></ul><h2>Practical information:</h2><ul><li>Opening hours: Open at all times</li></ul><ul><li>Admission: Free</li></ul><ul><li>Getting there: About a 10-minute walk from Shichahai Station</li></ul><ul><li>Suggested visit time: 30 to 45 minutes</li></ul><h3>Cultural context<strong>: Desheng Gate was first built in 1437. </strong>Originally Jiande Gate, used as the march-out gate for military expeditions, it was renamed Desheng Gate — "winning through virtue" — embodying the ancient Chinese military philosophy of conquering through moral authority.<strong> The gate''s arrow tower was a key component of Beijing''s Ming dynasty defensive system and a witness to the campaigns fought against northern nomadic peoples. </strong>A visit to Desheng Gate is an encounter with China''s ancient military planning and the intelligence of traditional city-building.</h3><h2>Prince Gong''s Mansion</h2><h3>Introduction<strong>: Prince Gong''s Mansion is one of the best-preserved Qing dynasty royal residences in Beijing. Originally the home of the powerful minister Heshen, it was later granted to Prince Gong. </strong>The mansion is celebrated for its exceptional scale and refined architectural artistry, and has been described as "half a dynasty of Qing history brought to life."</h3><h2>Highlights:</h2><ul><li><strong>Yin''an Hall</strong>: The mansion''s main ceremonial hall, commanding in its scale and presence</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Hou Zhao Lou (Back Multi-storey Building)</strong>: Climb to the roof for a panoramic view of the garden below</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Fu Pond</strong>: A decorative pond in the courtyard, its stone base inlaid with bat motifs — bats being a symbol of good fortune in Chinese culture</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Longevity Character Stone</strong>: A calligraphy piece by the Kangxi Emperor, said to embody "the greatest fortune under heaven" — touching it is thought to bring good luck</li></ul><h2>Practical information:</h2><ul><li>Opening hours: 8:30 a.m. to 5 p.m. (closed Mondays)</li></ul><ul><li>Admission: 40 yuan per person</li></ul><ul><li>Getting there: About a 15-minute walk from Shichahai Station</li></ul><ul><li>Suggested visit time: 60 to 90 minutes</li></ul><h3>Cultural context<strong>: Prince Gong''s Mansion was built during the Qianlong reign of the Qing dynasty, originally as the home of Heshen before being granted to Prince Gong. </strong>The layout of the mansion reflects the traditional Confucian hierarchy — front halls for formal affairs, rear courtyards for private life — ordered and purposeful in every detail.<strong> The pervasive "fortune" symbolism throughout — from the Fortune Gateway to the Longevity Character Stone — reflects Chinese culture''s deep and enduring fascination with blessings and good fortune. </strong>A visit to Prince Gong''s Mansion takes you into the architectural world of a Qing dynasty royal household and the rich symbolic culture that surrounds the pursuit of happiness in China.</h3><h2>Shichahai Ice Rink</h2><h3>Introduction<strong>: The Shichahai Ice Rink is one of Beijing''s most popular natural winter ice rinks. </strong>When the lake freezes solid, it becomes a vast natural ice surface where you can ride ice sledges and ice bicycles — the most authentically old-Beijing of all winter experiences, available only in the cold months.</h3><h2>Highlights:</h2><ul><li><strong>Ice activities</strong>: Rent ice sledges and ice bikes for a taste of old-fashioned Beijing winter fun</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Training areas</strong>: Dedicated zones for ice hockey, speed skating, and figure skating lessons</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Winter festival</strong>: Joint events with the nearby lotus market create a festive ice-and-snow carnival atmosphere</li></ul><h2>Practical information:</h2><ul><li>Opening hours: Approximately December through February (depending on weather conditions)</li></ul><ul><li>Admission: Approximately 50 yuan per person (including skates)</li></ul><ul><li>Getting there: About a 10-minute walk from Shichahai Station</li></ul><ul><li>Suggested visit time: 60 to 90 minutes</li></ul><h3>Cultural context<strong>: The Shichahai Ice Rink is an important part of Beijing''s winter cultural tradition, reflecting the northern Chinese love of and adaptation to snow and ice. </strong>Ice activities have a long history in northern China, traceable to the Tang and Song dynasties, and the Shichahai Ice Rink continues that tradition for modern visitors.<strong> Professional skating instructors are available on site. </strong>A visit to Shichahai Ice Rink gives you a real taste of northern Chinese ice culture and old Beijing''s winter pleasures — where tradition and the present day come together on the ice.</h3>',
  '[{"icon":"📏","label":"Distance","value":"About 1.2 kilometres"},{"icon":"⏱","label":"Duration","value":"2 to 3 hours"}]'::jsonb,
  3,
  TRUE
) ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
