INSERT INTO city_guides (
  id, city_id, title_en, title_zh, subtitle, icon, badge,
  cover_images, body, meta_items, display_order, is_published
) VALUES (
  'beijing_celebrity_residences',
  'beijing',
  'Beijing Celebrity Former Residences · Attraction Listings',
  '北京名人故居 · 景点列表页文案',
  'Compiled from the official recommended routes of the Beijing Municipal Bureau of Culture and Tourism, organized into two itineraries: the West District Heritage Trail and the East District Cultural Trail.',
  '🏠',
  NULL,
  ARRAY[]::TEXT[],
  '<h2>Route One: West District Heritage Trail</h2><h3>1. Beijing Lu Xun Museum (Lu Xun''s Former Residence)</h3><p>Address: 19 Gongmenkou Second Alley, Fuchengmen Inner Street, Xicheng District</p><p>Lu Xun purchased this small courtyard house in 1924 and wrote major works here including "Wild Grass" and "Dawn Blossoms Plucked at Dusk." Two jujube trees that he wrote about in his essays still stand in the courtyard. The highlight is his restored study-bedroom — a plain wooden desk, a rattan chair, and yellowed manuscripts evoke the writer bent over his work. The adjoining museum displays personal documents, original manuscripts, and his collection of woodblock prints, tracing the full arc of this founding figure of modern Chinese literature.</p><p>![Lu Xun Museum](real-photos/01_LuXun_Museum.jpg)</p><h3>2. Li Dazhao''s Former Residence</h3><p>Address: 24 Wenhua Hutong, Xicheng District</p><p>This is where Li Dazhao lived longest during his years in Beijing (1920–1924). The small three-sided courtyard has been preserved to reflect life as it was when he was a professor at Peking University. The main hall hosted early meetings of the Society for the Study of Marxism; his bedroom-study still holds a simple bookshelf and an English typewriter. The exhibition focuses on his theoretical writings and revolutionary activities as one of the principal founders of the Communist Party of China — essential context for understanding a turning point in modern Chinese history.</p><h3>3. Xu Beihong Memorial Museum</h3><p>Address: 53 Xinjiekou North Street, Xicheng District</p><p>The site was originally Xu Beihong''s residence; it was relocated here during subway construction, but his studio has been faithfully restored — the large painting table, palette, and unfinished works remain as he left them. Core holdings include his landmark paintings "Foolish Old Man Removes the Mountains" and his celebrated series of galloping horses, as well as a prized collection of classical Chinese painting and calligraphy spanning the Tang through Qing dynasties. The museum traces the full journey of this master who bridged Chinese and Western art, from his student years in Paris to his leadership of the Central Academy of Fine Arts.</p><p>![Xu Beihong Memorial Museum](real-photos/03_XuBeihong_Museum.jpg)</p><h3>4. Mei Lanfang Memorial Museum</h3><p>Address: 9 Huguo Temple Street, Xicheng District</p><p>Mei Lanfang spent the last decade of his life in this two-courtyard residence (1951–1961). The main hall displays costumes, headdresses, and props associated with his iconic female roles. In the sitting room, photographs of him alongside international figures including Charlie Chaplin document his role in bringing Jingju to the world stage. Crabapple and persimmon trees still fill the courtyard; the bedroom has been preserved as it was — a court robe encrusted with pearls and embroidery hangs on a rack, the most visually arresting exhibit in the museum.</p><p>![Mei Lanfang Memorial Museum](real-photos/04_MeiLanfang_Courtyard.jpg)</p><h3>5. Guo Moruo Memorial Museum</h3><p>Address: 18 Qianhai West Street, Xicheng District</p><p>Known informally as the "Peony Courtyard" for the peonies planted throughout the grounds, this large compound was originally a stable belonging to Prince Gong''s Estate. Guo Moruo spent his final fifteen years here (1963–1978). The exhibition covers his multiple identities: poet (manuscripts of "Goddess"), historian (oracle bone inscription research materials), and playwright (source materials for his historical dramas). The garden''s rockeries, waterways, and covered walkways frame a view of Shichahai Lake, making this as much a garden visit as a museum tour.</p><p>![Guo Moruo Memorial Museum](real-photos/05_GuoMoruo_Courtyard.jpg)</p><h3>6. Soong Ching-ling''s Former Residence</h3><p>Address: 46 Beiyan, Houhai, Xicheng District</p><p>This estate was originally the western garden of the mansion belonging to Nalan Mingzhu, a grand secretary under the Kangxi Emperor, where the Qing-dynasty lyric poet Nalan Xingde grew up. Soong Ching-ling lived here from 1963 until her death in 1981. The main building is a charming East-meets-West two-story villa; the ground-floor reception room once hosted multiple foreign heads of state, and the upstairs bedroom remains unchanged. The lakeside garden is shaded by ancient scholar trees and dotted with rockeries. The small museum inside tells the story of her life — from revolutionary companion to honorary president of the People''s Republic of China.</p><p>![Soong Ching-ling''s Former Residence](real-photos/06_SoongChingling_Gate.jpg)</p><h2>Route Two: East District Cultural Trail</h2><h3>7. Lao She Memorial Museum</h3><p>Address: 19 Fengfu Hutong, Dengshikou West Street, Dongcheng District</p><p>Named "Red Persimmon Courtyard" for the two persimmon trees growing in the yard, this is where Lao She lived for sixteen years (1950–1966) and wrote his most celebrated works, including "Dragon Beard Ditch" and "Teahouse." The compact, carefully tended courtyard preserves a main-room study where his writing desk, teaware, and collection of Jingju face masks can still be seen. Fishponds, flowering plants, and rattan chairs recreate the atmosphere of a Beijing literary household — the perfect starting point for understanding the hutong world he depicted in his writing.</p><p>![Lao She Memorial Museum](real-photos/07_LaoShe_Memorial.jpg)</p><h3>8. Mao Dun''s Former Residence</h3><p>Address: 13 Houyuanen Temple Hutong, Dongcheng District</p><p>Mao Dun spent his last seven years here (1974–1981), completing his memoir "The Road I Have Traveled." The front courtyard of this two-courtyard compound houses a biographical exhibition; the rear courtyard is preserved as it was in his lifetime — bedroom, sitting room, and study all unchanged. The most moving scene is his study: neatly arranged Chinese and foreign literary titles line the shelves beside the desk at which he wrote. Crabapple trees bloom in the courtyard each spring, adding a quiet grace to the late residence of the author of "Midnight."</p><p>![Mao Dun''s Former Residence](real-photos/08_MaoDun_Courtyard.jpg)</p><h3>9. Qi Baishi Former Residence Memorial Museum</h3><p>Address: 13 Yu''er Hutong, Dongcheng District</p><p>Qi Baishi spent his final two years here (1955–1957). The courtyard is modest; the studio preserves the long worktable, brush-washers, and seal boxes the old master used. The exhibition traces his extraordinary journey from village carpenter to globally celebrated artist, and several late-career paintings embody his signature aesthetic — beauty found in the space between likeness and unlikeness. A pomegranate tree in the courtyard still bears fruit each year, echoing the vegetables, fruits, and insects he so often painted.</p><h3>10. Cao Xueqin Former Residence Memorial Museum</h3><p>Address: 123 Guangqumen Inner Street, Dongcheng District (northeast corner of Ciqikou)</p><p>This is the only residence in Beijing with documented historical evidence connecting it to Cao Xueqin. Official records from the seventh year of the Yongzheng Emperor''s reign describe it as "Seventeen-and-a-Half Rooms at Suan Market Street." Reconstructed on the original site and opened in 2022, the three-courtyard complex recreates the residential layout of middle and lower-ranking Bannermen households in Qing-dynasty Beijing. The permanent exhibition includes facsimiles of early hand-copied manuscripts of "Dream of the Red Chamber," related artifacts, and materials on the Cao family history — an essential starting point for exploring this landmark of world literature.</p><h3>11. Ji Xiaolan''s Former Residence (Yuewei Cottage)</h3><p>Address: 241 Zhushikou West Street, Xicheng District</p><p>The Qing-dynasty grand secretary Ji Xiaolan lived here for roughly sixty years and presided over the compilation of the Siku Quanshu — the largest imperial anthology in Chinese history. A wisteria vine he planted himself, now over 200 years old, drapes the entrance trellis in cascades of purple each spring. The "Yuewei Cottage" study holds a remarkable collection of rare ancient books and scholarly objects. The exhibition recounts his reputation as the foremost literary talent at the court of Emperor Qianlong — both his scholarly achievements and the popular legends that grew up around him.</p>',
  '[]'::jsonb,
  8,
  TRUE
) ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
  city_id = EXCLUDED.city_id,
  title_en = EXCLUDED.title_en,
  title_zh = EXCLUDED.title_zh,
  subtitle = EXCLUDED.subtitle,
  icon = EXCLUDED.icon,
  badge = EXCLUDED.badge,
  cover_images = EXCLUDED.cover_images,
  body = EXCLUDED.body,
  meta_items = EXCLUDED.meta_items,
  audio_url = NULL,
  audio_title = NULL,
  audio_duration_seconds = 0,
  audio_quote = NULL,
  audio_transcript = NULL,
  display_order = EXCLUDED.display_order,
  is_published = EXCLUDED.is_published,
  updated_at = NOW();

INSERT INTO city_guides (
  id, city_id, title_en, title_zh, subtitle, icon, badge,
  cover_images, body, meta_items, display_order, is_published
) VALUES (
  'beijing_best_season',
  'beijing',
  'Best Season to Visit Beijing',
  '一、最佳旅行季节：9月至10月的秋高气爽',
  NULL,
  '☀',
  NULL,
  ARRAY[]::TEXT[],
  '<p>Beijing has over 3,000 years of urban history and more than 800 years as an imperial capital. Today it stands as an international metropolis where ancient heritage and modern energy go hand in hand. As China''s capital, Beijing has four distinct seasons, each with its own character and appeal — but for most visitors, <strong>the finest time to visit is undoubtedly autumn, especially the golden weeks of September and October.</strong> The climate is at its most comfortable, the scenery is spectacular, crowds are manageable, and travel costs are relatively low, making it an ideal window for a relaxed and affordable trip.</p><h2>Part One: The Best Season — September and October</h2><p><strong>Autumn (September and October) is Beijing''s golden travel window.</strong> Deep-blue skies, crisp air, and mild temperatures create perfect conditions for exploring the city.</p><h3>1. Comfortable Climate</h3><p>Beijing''s autumn climate is close to ideal. <strong>Average temperatures range from 15°C to 25°C</strong> — warm enough to enjoy but without the sweltering heat of summer or the bitter cold of winter. Days are pleasantly sunny without being harsh; evenings turn refreshingly cool and are perfect for outdoor activities. Compared with summer averages of 28°C to 35°C and winter temperatures that regularly drop below zero, the autumn climate lets visitors explore comfortably from morning to night without worrying about the weather.</p><p><strong>Air quality and visibility also reach their annual best.</strong> The summer rainstorms and dust events that affect other seasons are largely absent in autumn. The Air Quality Index typically stays at excellent levels, visibility is high, city views are crystal clear, and every photograph comes out beautifully. October in particular offers cool mornings, sunny afternoons, and evenings requiring nothing more than a light jacket — ideal for long days outdoors.</p><h3>2. Stunning Natural Scenery — a Photographer''s Paradise</h3><p>Beijing''s autumn is famously described as a season where "skies stretch high and forests blaze with colour." <strong>Natural scenery across the city reaches its most beautiful state of the year.</strong> A kind of magic transforms the whole city into a vivid, sweeping painting:</p><ul><li><strong>Fiery Red Foliage</strong>: At Xiangshan Park (Fragrant Hills), Badaling Great Wall, and Pofengling, maple leaves and smoke-tree foliage pile up in layer after layer, cascading like a river of red. Xiangshan Park in particular — regarded by Beijingers as the very emblem of autumn — sets the entire hillside ablaze in orange-red from top to bottom.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Golden Ginkgo Avenues</strong>: The ginkgo boulevard in Beihai Park, a roughly 200-metre-long ginkgo-lined path in front of the Five Pagoda Temple, and the ginkgo avenue in Ditan Park all glow bright gold, as if you have walked into a fairy tale. Ditan Park''s avenue has become one of autumn Beijing''s defining landmarks — the ground blanketed in golden leaves, walking through feels like drifting through a sea of gold.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Ancient Architecture Meets Autumn Colour</strong>: Inside the Forbidden City, golden roof tiles catch the blue sky above while fallen leaves pave the ground below in gold. In that moment, you feel transported back to an imperial age. Nearby, Jingshan Park''s Wanchun Pavilion offers the best panoramic view of the Forbidden City — for just 2 yuan you can climb to the summit and look down over the palace in all its autumn glory.</li></ul><p>This perfect union of natural beauty and historic architecture makes autumn Beijing a paradise for photographers, where every frame captures the interplay of nature and history.</p><h3>3. Manageable Crowds — a Better Experience</h3><p>Compared with the summer peak (especially July and August) and the Chinese New Year holiday, <strong>autumn visitor numbers are at their most comfortable level.</strong> Crowds are far below those seen during the May Day and National Day holidays, and nowhere near as overwhelming as summer.</p><p>According to Beijing''s Bureau of Culture and Tourism, <strong>weekday visitor density runs roughly 57 percent lower than on weekends</strong>, and visitor numbers in September and October are about 38 percent lower than during the summer break. Avoiding the National Day holiday in early October improves the experience further. At the Palace Museum, for example, weekday autumn crowds are noticeably smaller than peak-season weekends, giving visitors far more space and time to appreciate every detail of this magnificent palace complex.</p><p><strong>The off-peak advantage</strong> is especially clear in autumn. Visitor numbers start to drop in early September. After a brief uptick around the National Day holiday in early October, they fall again quickly. From late October through early November, numbers drop to one of their lowest points of the year — exploring popular sites during this window is a quiet and deeply satisfying experience.</p><h3>4. Lower Travel Costs — Excellent Value</h3><p>Autumn is also Beijing''s <strong>economic sweet spot for travellers.</strong> Accommodation and flights cost significantly less than during the May Day and National Day holidays. Based on current market data, <strong>budget hotels in Beijing during autumn typically run 180 to 350 yuan per night</strong> — far below the 800-yuan-and-above prices seen during the May Day holiday (some hotels charge over 3,000 yuan per night at that time, roughly four times the autumn rate).</p><p>Chain hotels near subway stations — such as those near Gongyixiqiao Station — <strong>hold steady at around 300 yuan per night</strong> and are an ideal choice for budget-conscious travellers. Beijing''s "Jingcai" residents'' benefit package, which covers subway and bike-share discounts among other perks, also applies during the autumn period.</p><p><strong>For admission</strong>, the Palace Museum charges 60 yuan per person during peak season (April 1 through October 31), compared with 40 yuan in the off-season. While slightly higher, this still represents excellent value compared with summer crowds or the potential price increases around Chinese New Year.</p><h2>Part Two: The Other Seasons — Pros and Cons</h2><p>Autumn is Beijing''s best season for most visitors, but every season has its own distinct appeal.</p><h3>1. Spring (March to May): Blossoms and New Life</h3><p><strong>Spring temperatures in Beijing range from 8°C to 22°C</strong>, making it a wonderful season for flower-viewing. Yuyuantan Park''s cherry blossoms billow like clouds of snow; the peach trees along the Summer Palace''s western embankment burst into bloom; Fayuan Temple fills with the perfume of lilac. The city comes alive with colour.</p><h2>Advantages:</h2><ul><li>All manner of flowers bloom in succession — cherry blossom, crabapple, magnolia — ideal for blossom enthusiasts</li></ul><ul><li>Mild temperatures perfect for outdoor activities</li></ul><ul><li>Some sites hold spring events, including Qingming (Tomb-Sweeping Festival) programs and traditional spring temple fairs</li></ul><h2>Disadvantages:</h2><ul><li><strong>Spring can be windy and sand-dust haze occasionally arrives</strong>, potentially disrupting outdoor plans</li></ul><ul><li>Bloom windows are short and timing needs to be precise</li></ul><ul><li>From late March to early April, the tourist season begins to pick up and visitor numbers climb steadily</li></ul><h3>2. Summer (June to August): Lush Green and High Energy</h3><p><strong>Summer temperatures are high — averaging 25°C to 35°C — with July often pushing well above 35°C.</strong> The heat is real, but summer Beijing has its own character:</p><h2>Advantages:</h2><ul><li><strong>Lush greenery everywhere and clear, shimmering lakes</strong> — Kunming Lake at the Summer Palace gleams a brilliant blue, and lotus flowers cover Beihai Park</li></ul><ul><li>A rich evening scene, including night visits to Mutianyu Great Wall and Shichahai night market</li></ul><ul><li>Some sites run summer-season events and light shows</li></ul><h2>Disadvantages:</h2><ul><li><strong>High heat and heavy rainfall</strong> — humidity makes temperatures feel even higher; sun protection and cooling precautions are essential</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Visitor numbers peak sharply</strong>, especially in July and August during school holidays, with every major site packed to capacity</li></ul><ul><li>Accommodation and transport costs rise significantly, with hotel prices potentially doubling</li></ul><ul><li>Some sites impose visitor caps due to overcrowding, reducing the quality of the experience</li></ul><h3>3. Winter (December to February): Ice, Snow, and Festive Charm</h3><p><strong>Winter temperatures in Beijing regularly drop below zero</strong>, sometimes reaching minus seven degrees Celsius, and the air is cold and dry. But occasional light snowfall transforms the city into something wonderfully magical.</p><h2>Advantages:</h2><ul><li><strong>Unique snow scenery</strong>: the Forbidden City blanketed in snow and frost-covered trees along the Great Wall are among Beijing''s most unforgettable winter sights</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Plenty of winter activities</strong>: ice skating at Shichahai, ice lantern festivals at Longqing Gorge, and more</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Fewer visitors at some sites</strong>, allowing for a quieter, more peaceful experience</li></ul><h2>Disadvantages:</h2><ul><li><strong>Bitter cold and dry air</strong> — layered, warm clothing is essential for any outdoor activity</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Visitor numbers and hotel prices surge around Chinese New Year</strong>, with some hotels charging more than three times their usual rate</li></ul><ul><li><strong>More time naturally spent indoors</strong>, with outdoor touring hours limited by the cold</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Some sites, particularly in mountain areas, may close due to weather conditions</strong></li></ul><h2>Part Three: Must-See Autumn Experiences in Beijing</h2><h3>1. Red Leaves and Ginkgo Avenues</h3><p>Autumn''s most unmissable sights are the blazing red foliage and golden ginkgo avenues:</p><ul><li><strong>Xiangshan Park (Fragrant Hills)</strong>: Synonymous with Beijing''s autumn foliage, with hillsides that blaze orange-red from top to bottom. Take the cable car for a panoramic view. Best viewing: mid-October to early November.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Pofengling</strong>: Dubbed the most dramatic mountain foliage landscape in northern China, Pofengling is home to around 200,000 wild smoke trees — the densest red-leaf concentration in the region. Climb to the Eagle Beak viewpoint for a sweeping 360-degree view of a swirling red sea.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Ditan Park</strong>: The golden ginkgo avenue here has become one of Beijing''s defining autumn landmarks. By late autumn, the path is blanketed in golden leaves — walking through feels like drifting in a golden sea.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Beihai Park</strong>: Ginkgo trees alongside ancient architecture create a stunning tableau, with the lake''s surface mirroring the golden leaves overhead.</li></ul><p>Beijing''s Bureau of Landscape and Forestry has curated a three-tier autumn colour corridor — city parks, suburban areas, and mountain forests — covering 100 designated viewing spots, so visitors can choose the route that suits them best.</p><h3>2. Historical Sites — Imperial Grandeur in Autumn Light</h3><ul><li><strong>The Palace Museum (Forbidden City)</strong>: Its red walls and golden rooftops are breathtaking in every season, but <strong>autumn is the finest time to visit.</strong> Mild temperatures and manageable crowds give you the space to truly feel the grandeur and solemnity of this 600-year-old Ming and Qing dynasty palace. Book afternoon tickets (entry from 3 p.m.) when crowds drop by more than half. Don''t miss a stroll along the ginkgo avenue on either side of the Gate of Divine Might — the golden leaves playing off the red walls and yellow tiles make for spectacular photographs.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Temple of Heaven</strong>: The ceremonial ground where Ming and Qing emperors performed rituals of heaven worship and prayed for good harvests. <strong>Enter from the north gate, where crowds are typically lighter.</strong> In autumn, ancient trees soar overhead and fallen leaves cover the ground, making the ancient ideal of harmony between humanity and heaven feel genuinely present.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Summer Palace</strong>: China''s largest imperial garden, where Kunming Lake and Longevity Hill complement each other in perfect harmony. In autumn the lake is clear, the surrounding hillsides glow with colour, and a boat ride across the water (40 yuan per person) is an experience not to miss. The Seventeen-Arch Bridge at sunset, with autumn wind sending gentle ripples across the lake, makes time itself feel softer.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Jingshan Park</strong>: Climb Wanchun Pavilion for 2 yuan and look down over the full sweep of the Forbidden City. <strong>Arrive when the park opens at 7 a.m. — crowds are sparse and the golden glazed rooftiles in the morning light are extraordinary.</strong></li></ul><h3>3. Nature and Sport — Energy and Serenity</h3><ul><li><strong>Huairou National Trend Cultural Festival</strong>: Running from May through October, hosting nearly 20 special events including intangible heritage markets and traditional costume competitions, drawing visitors from around the world.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Huairou Triathlon World Cup</strong>: Held in October, combining athletic excitement with Beijing''s autumn landscape at its most beautiful.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Great Wall in Autumn</strong>: The autumn colours at Badaling stretch across the mountain ridges for miles, bringing a sense of life and dynamism to the ancient stones. Tower Fourteen is a favourite spot for sunset-watching; Tower Twenty offers a sweeping panoramic view of the surrounding hills. The interplay of red and gold against the ancient wall is unlike anything else.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Olympic Forest Park</strong>: In autumn, drifts of pink muhly grass, rounded kochia shrubs, and waving cosmos flowers weave a romantic seasonal tapestry — a wonderful spot for a relaxed afternoon stroll.</li></ul><h3>4. Hutong Strolls and Food — Old Beijing''s Everyday Warmth</h3><ul><li><strong>Nanluoguxiang</strong>: Busy and commercial, but worth visiting for the quieter hutongs nearby. In autumn the street canopy is full and lush — a pleasant wander through genuine neighbourhood life.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Shichahai</strong>: The perfect combination of bar street, traditional pedicab hutong tours, and lakeside evenings. <strong>On an autumn evening, sit by the water and enjoy the breeze with a bowl of almond tofu (15 yuan) and lamb skewers (20 yuan for three)</strong> — a thoroughly authentic taste of old Beijing''s nightlife.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Yangmeizhu Xiejie (Yangmeizhu Oblique Street)</strong>: A hutong full of seasonal charm, where cafes offer limited-time autumn menus — a cherry blossom latte and pea cake combo for 38 yuan, enjoyed on a courtyard rooftop terrace with views of the hutong rooflines and the CBD skyline in the distance.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Huguo Temple Snack Street</strong>: Start a morning the old Beijing way — a filling traditional breakfast for around 10 yuan per person, paired with doujir (fermented mung bean juice) and jiaoquan (fried dough rings), for a genuine taste of the city''s street food heritage.</li></ul><h2>Part Four: Practical Guide for Autumn</h2><p>To make the most of your autumn visit, here are some practical tips:</p><h3>1. Where to Stay</h3><p><strong>Budget hotels</strong>: Typically 180 to 350 yuan per night in autumn. Recommended: chain hotels close to subway stations, such as those near Gongyixiqiao Station — convenient, well-equipped, and consistently priced.</p><p><strong>Characterful guesthouses</strong>: Hutong guesthouses near Nanluoguxiang run around 200 to 400 yuan per night and give you a genuinely authentic Beijing experience. <strong>Sharing with a group brings costs down significantly — four people sharing can pay as little as 50 yuan each</strong>, which is outstanding value.</p><p><strong>Higher-end options</strong>: Resorts such as those at Gubei Water Town run approximately 1,200 to 1,800 yuan per night during the autumn off-peak period — ideal for those looking for more comfort and space.</p><h3>2. Getting Around</h3><ul><li><strong>Subway</strong>: Beijing''s metro network covers all major tourist sites. Use the Yitongxing app to scan and board. Avoid rush hours (7 to 9 a.m. and 5 to 7 p.m.) — outside those windows, the subway is the best way to get around.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Shared bikes</strong>: Great for short trips and hutong exploration. <strong>Stick to designated parking areas to avoid fines.</strong></li></ul><ul><li><strong>Bus</strong>: Some sites require a bus connection — Bus Route 877 runs directly to the Great Wall; buses also serve the Summer Palace and other sites further out.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Taxi and ride-hailing</strong>: Useful outside rush hours. Note that hailing a ride near Tiananmen Square and nearby core areas can be difficult.</li></ul><h3>3. Booking and Tickets</h3><ul><li><strong>Palace Museum (Forbidden City)</strong>: Tickets must be reserved seven days in advance. Peak season: 60 yuan per person; off-season: 40 yuan. <strong>Avoid the 9 to 11 a.m. rush — it accounts for about 40 percent of the day''s visitor footfall.</strong> Afternoon entry from 3 p.m. typically sees crowds fall by more than half.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>National Museum of China</strong>: Free admission, but booking three days in advance is required.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>"Beijing Culture and Tourism" WeChat official account</strong>: Sells tickets to various sites, with discounts of up to ten percent at selected venues.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>"Go Beijing" platform</strong>: A one-stop service designed for international visitors, available in 16 languages, with real-time crowd data, site booking, and payment services.</li></ul><h3>4. Food</h3><ul><li><strong>Peking Duck</strong>: Try established restaurants such as Quanjude, Da Dong, and Siji Minfu. <strong>With autumn crowds lower than in summer, you can book ahead and skip the usual wait.</strong></li></ul><ul><li><strong>Old Beijing street food</strong>: Huguo Temple Snack Street and Yin San Douzhi are the go-to spots for authentic local flavours. <strong>In autumn, look out for roasted chestnuts and tanghulu (candied hawthorn skewers) — both seasonal treats you will find on almost every corner.</strong></li></ul><ul><li><strong>Halal cuisine</strong>: Niujie is the heart of Beijing''s halal food scene. Hand-cut mutton at Jubaoyuan is a must-try. <strong>Arrive around 4 p.m. to beat the dinner crowd — around 80 yuan per person, and well worth the trip.</strong></li></ul><h2>Part Five: Autumn in Beijing — the City at Its Finest</h2><p>Beijing''s autumn is this city at its most enchanting. <strong>Clear skies, crisp air, blazing foliage, ancient architecture glowing in warm afternoon light.</strong> At this time of year, Beijing has both the weight of history and the grace of natural beauty; both cultural depth and the warmth of everyday life.</p><p>Whether you are a history and culture enthusiast, a lover of the outdoors, or someone who travels for food and local atmosphere, <strong>Beijing''s autumn has something for you.</strong> Visit the Forbidden City and take your time with every courtyard and carved detail. Climb Xiangshan and let the sea of red leaves fill your vision. Sit down to Peking Duck without the rush and savour every slice.</p><p><strong>Choose Beijing in autumn and you will get a comfortable, affordable, and genuinely surprising trip.</strong> Avoid the crowds, skip the extremes of heat and cold, and give yourself the space and energy to discover what makes this city so extraordinary.</p><p>We look forward to welcoming you to Beijing this golden season — where an ancient, ever-renewing city is ready to leave a lasting impression.</p>',
  '[]'::jsonb,
  9,
  TRUE
) ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
  city_id = EXCLUDED.city_id,
  title_en = EXCLUDED.title_en,
  title_zh = EXCLUDED.title_zh,
  subtitle = EXCLUDED.subtitle,
  icon = EXCLUDED.icon,
  badge = EXCLUDED.badge,
  cover_images = EXCLUDED.cover_images,
  body = EXCLUDED.body,
  meta_items = EXCLUDED.meta_items,
  audio_url = NULL,
  audio_title = NULL,
  audio_duration_seconds = 0,
  audio_quote = NULL,
  audio_transcript = NULL,
  display_order = EXCLUDED.display_order,
  is_published = EXCLUDED.is_published,
  updated_at = NOW();

INSERT INTO city_guides (
  id, city_id, title_en, title_zh, subtitle, icon, badge,
  cover_images, body, meta_items, display_order, is_published
) VALUES (
  'chengdu_museum_routes',
  'chengdu',
  'Chengdu Museum: Official Visitor Routes and Attraction Guide',
  '成都博物馆官方旅行线路与景点介绍',
  NULL,
  '🏛',
  'Museum',
  ARRAY[]::TEXT[],
  '<p>Chengdu Museum is located at <strong>1 Xiaohe Street, Qingyang District, Chengdu</strong>, on the west side of Tianfu Square and easy to reach by public transport. Visitors can take Metro Line 1 or Line 2 to Tianfu Square Station and walk approximately 3 minutes from Exit West 1 North or Exit West 1 South. Alternatively, buses on routes 13, 30, 43, 47, 64, and 78 stop at West Imperial Street Station, from which the museum is about 20 meters away on foot.</p><p>Visitor Notes (Responsible Travel):</p><p>Opening Hours:</p><ul><li>Tuesday through Thursday and Sunday: 9:00 AM to 5:00 PM (last entry at 4:30 PM)</li><li>Friday and Saturday: 9:00 AM to 8:30 PM (last entry at 8:00 PM)</li><li>Closed on Mondays (except public holidays)</li></ul><p><strong>Admission</strong>: Free, but advance reservation with ID verification is required. Foreign visitors may book using their passport via the museum''s official website or WeChat account, or register in person at the entrance.</p><ul><li><strong>Reservations</strong>: Foreign visitors can make reservations through the Chengdu Museum official website or WeChat public account ("Chengdu Museum"), or register with their passport at the entrance.</li><li><strong>Guided Tours</strong>: Free scheduled guided tours are available — groups form at 10:30 AM and 2:30 PM on the second floor. Bilingual Chinese-English audio guides are also available for rent at 40 yuan per unit.</li><li><strong>Interactive Experiences</strong>: The shadow puppet and marionette exhibition on the fifth floor features interactive performances. It is recommended to check performance times in advance and plan your visit accordingly.</li><li><strong>Rest Areas</strong>: Rest areas are available throughout the museum for visitors to take a break at any time.</li><li><strong>Dining</strong>: No food or drinks are sold inside the museum apart from water. Visitors are encouraged to eat beforehand at the Tianfu Square food court or at nearby restaurants.</li></ul><p>Based on the official recommended route, visitors are advised to tour the museum in the following floor order for the best experience:</p><h3>Basement Level → First Floor → Second Floor → Third Floor → Fourth Floor → Fifth Floor → Sixth Floor</h3><h3>Detailed Guide to Each Gallery</h3><p>#### Basement Level: Humanity and Nature — The Bering Donation Exhibition <strong>Location</strong>: Basement Level <strong>Theme</strong>: Exploring global biodiversity and natural ecosystems <strong>Highlights</strong>: Chengdu Museum''s first nature-themed exhibition, featuring <strong>more than 300 animal specimens</strong> representing species from all five continents. The exhibition is divided into three sections — "A Journey Through the World''s Nature," "Nature and Us," and "Respect and Conservation" — using vivid specimen displays to help visitors understand the ecological characteristics of different continents and the importance of biodiversity.</p><p>This exhibition is particularly well suited to families with children. Through hands-on specimen displays, foreign visitors can gain insight into China''s wildlife conservation efforts and the global importance of protecting biodiversity. Interactive Q&amp;A elements help visitors better understand the concept of living in harmony with nature.</p><p>#### First Floor: Special Exhibition Hall (Temporary Exhibitions) The special exhibition hall on the first floor hosts a variety of high-caliber temporary exhibitions, such as international art shows and historical artifact displays. <strong>Exhibition content rotates regularly according to season and theme</strong>, so there is always something new to discover at Chengdu Museum.</p><p>Temporary exhibitions typically carry significant international prestige and academic value, with many produced in partnership with leading museums abroad. Through these exhibitions, visitors can explore Chengdu''s history and culture from fresh perspectives and trace its connections to civilizations around the world.</p><p>#### Second Floor: Splendor of the Brocade City — Chengdu History and Culture (Ancient Period) Chengdu''s historical development from pre-Qin times through the Northern and Southern Dynasties</p><p>This exhibition is divided into two sections — <strong>"Nine Heavens Open One Chengdu: Chengdu in the Pre-Qin Era"</strong> and <strong>"West Shu, Land of Abundance: Chengdu from the Qin-Han Era through the Northern and Southern Dynasties"</strong> — presenting more than 240 selected artifacts that reveal the deep historical roots of ancient Shu civilization.</p><p>This gallery is the ideal starting point for understanding Chengdu''s history and culture. Through these precious artifacts, visitors can appreciate the splendor of ancient Shu civilization and the prosperity of Chengdu during the Han dynasty as the "Land of Abundance." The stone rhinoceros and the lacquered acupuncture figure are among the museum''s most treasured masterpieces and should not be missed.</p><p>#### Third Floor: Splendor of the Brocade City — Chengdu History and Culture (Sui-Tang through Ming-Qing Period) Chengdu''s historical transformation from the Sui-Tang era through the Ming and Qing dynasties</p><p>This exhibition is divided into two sections — "A Renowned Metropolis: Chengdu during the Sui, Tang, Five Dynasties, Song, and Yuan Periods" and "Evening Glow on Red Towers: Chengdu during the Ming and Qing Dynasties" — displaying <strong>more than 600 artifacts and sets</strong> that illustrate the thriving prosperity of Chengdu as a great southwestern city.</p><p>This gallery uses a wealth of artifacts and reconstructed scenes to present Chengdu''s glorious history from the Sui-Tang era through the Ming and Qing dynasties. The model of a Sichuan jacquard loom in particular gives visitors a vivid sense of the extraordinary craftsmanship behind ancient Shu brocade, and the enduring appeal of China''s silk culture.</p><p>#### Fourth Floor: Splendor of the Brocade City — Chengdu History and Culture (Modern and Folk Culture Period) Chengdu''s modern history and its distinctive folk culture</p><p>This gallery is divided into two sections. The <strong>"Modern Period"</strong> section covers Chengdu''s historical transformations from the First Opium War of 1840 through to liberation in 1949, while the <strong>"Folk Culture"</strong> section showcases Chengdu''s unique cultural character and community spirit.</p><p>The Modern Period section helps visitors understand Chengdu''s important role in China''s recent history, particularly its contributions during the Railway Protection Movement and the War of Resistance. The Folk Culture section uses richly reconstructed scenes and authentic objects to immerse visitors in Chengdu''s distinctive street life and daily rhythms, capturing the magic of "old Chengdu."</p><p>#### Fifth Floor: Shadows in Motion, Puppets Through the Ages — Chinese Shadow Puppet and Marionette Exhibition Traditional Chinese shadow puppet and marionette art, with interactive experiences</p><p><strong>Highlights</strong>: Chengdu Museum also operates under the designation of the Chengdu Chinese Shadow Puppet Museum, making it <strong>Sichuan''s first and Chengdu''s only nationally designated museum of its kind</strong>, and currently the museum with the world''s largest collection of shadow puppets in terms of quantity, variety, and quality. The exhibition is divided into two sections — "Shadows in Motion: Chinese Shadow Puppet Exhibition" and "Puppets Through the Ages: Chinese Marionette Exhibition" — featuring close to 2,000 selected artifacts and sets that <strong>chart the full development of Chinese shadow puppet and marionette art</strong>.</p><p>Chinese shadow puppetry was inscribed on UNESCO''s Representative List of the Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity in 2011. This exhibition not only showcases a rich collection of shadow puppets and marionettes, but also <strong>offers interactive experiences</strong> where visitors can try operating the puppets themselves or take part in weekend shadow puppet performances and experience this traditional Chinese art form firsthand.</p><p>#### Sixth Floor: Museum Shop and Viewing Terrace Chengdu Museum gift shop and panoramic views of Tianfu Square</p><p>The sixth floor is home to the museum''s gift shop and viewing terrace. The shop offers a wide range of <strong>creative products inspired by the museum''s prized collections</strong>, such as stone rhinoceros blind-box figures, glazed rhinoceros ornaments, and glazed entertainer figurines. There is also a viewing terrace with a panoramic view of Tianfu Square.</p><p>The gift shop is the ideal place to take a piece of Chengdu Museum''s cultural heritage home with you. The products are beautifully designed, combining practical appeal with cultural meaning. The viewing terrace gives visitors the chance to admire the sweeping scenery of Tianfu Square from above, bringing the entire museum visit to a satisfying close.</p>',
  '[]'::jsonb,
  0,
  TRUE
) ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
  city_id = EXCLUDED.city_id,
  title_en = EXCLUDED.title_en,
  title_zh = EXCLUDED.title_zh,
  subtitle = EXCLUDED.subtitle,
  icon = EXCLUDED.icon,
  badge = EXCLUDED.badge,
  cover_images = EXCLUDED.cover_images,
  body = EXCLUDED.body,
  meta_items = EXCLUDED.meta_items,
  audio_url = NULL,
  audio_title = NULL,
  audio_duration_seconds = 0,
  audio_quote = NULL,
  audio_transcript = NULL,
  display_order = EXCLUDED.display_order,
  is_published = EXCLUDED.is_published,
  updated_at = NOW();

INSERT INTO city_guides (
  id, city_id, title_en, title_zh, subtitle, icon, badge,
  cover_images, body, meta_items, display_order, is_published
) VALUES (
  'chengdu_coffee',
  'chengdu',
  '☕ Chengdu Independent Coffee Guide · Top 10 Picks for Foreign Visitors',
  '☕ 成都独立咖啡体验指南 · 外国游客必访 TOP 10',
  NULL,
  '☕',
  NULL,
  ARRAY[]::TEXT[],
  '<h2>1. Goût &amp; Co</h2><ul><li><strong>What makes it special</strong>: Chengdu''s calling card in the world of specialty coffee. The owner placed third at a French coffee brewing competition and comes with a background in robotics engineering — he returned from Paris to open this shop. The focus is on single-origin pour-over and in-house roasting, with an open roasting area where you can watch the whole process from raw bean to finished roast.</li><li><strong>Signature coffee</strong>: Single-origin pour-over (light-roasted Ethiopian beans with citrus and jasmine notes; Colombian beans with caramel sweetness and a nutty, full-bodied finish).</li><li><strong>Address</strong>: 11 Zhuyuan Lane, Wuhou District, Chengdu (Zongbei branch)</li><li><strong>Why visit</strong>: Unanimously recognized by the English-speaking coffee community as the essential first stop in Chengdu. Consistently high quality and precise flavor expression — the benchmark for understanding what Chengdu specialty coffee can do.</li></ul><h2>2. Pick Coffee</h2><ul><li><strong>What makes it special</strong>: A minimalist café within easy walking distance of Kuanzhai Alley. Grey tones and wooden interiors with thoughtful details throughout. Famous for its numbered "Pick Series" coffees, each with a distinct flavor profile. Staff remain warm and attentive even when busy.</li><li><strong>Signature coffee</strong>: Pick Number 2 or Pick Number 3 (clean, refreshing signature blends with layered flavors).</li><li><strong>Address</strong>: 9 Paotong Tree Street, Qingyang District, Chengdu</li><li><strong>Why visit</strong>: The most convenient high-quality coffee stop when exploring Kuanzhai Alley — professional-grade drinks in a tourist area, which is rare. The seats out front are perfect for a photo break.</li></ul><h2>3. UM! Coffee Brewer</h2><ul><li><strong>What makes it special</strong>: Less of a traditional café, more of a dedicated coffee bar. Located in the heart of Kuanzhai Alley, the space is tiny and stripped of all excess — no sprawling seating, no sofas. You come here for the coffee alone.</li><li><strong>Signature coffee</strong>: Pour-over, espresso.</li><li><strong>Address</strong>: 26-2 Kuan Alley, Qingyang District, Chengdu</li><li><strong>Why visit</strong>: A special recommendation from FLTR Magazine — "tourist areas usually don''t have good coffee; UM! is the exception." Shatters the cliché that nothing worth drinking exists near the attractions.</li></ul><h2>4. Raindrops Coffee</h2><ul><li><strong>What makes it special</strong>: Founded by a former head barista at Five Elephant, the acclaimed Berlin roastery. The focus is on internationally sourced light-roast beans. The name is inspired by the image of pour-over coffee dripping slowly into the cup. Across from Mengzhuiwan Swimming Pool, the setting is fresh and quiet — a hidden gem among local coffee enthusiasts.</li><li><strong>Signature coffee</strong>: Single-origin pour-over (light-roasted, highlighting floral aromas and bright fruit acidity).</li><li><strong>Address</strong>: Unit 16, Building 2, 10 Huaxing Road, Chenghua District, Chengdu</li><li><strong>Why visit</strong>: Rated by FLTR Magazine as "the place recommended by coffee people." If you care about what''s in the cup more than what''s on your social media feed, this is the place.</li></ul><h2>5. UID Cafe</h2><ul><li><strong>What makes it special</strong>: A legendary café on Tangba Street, open for more than 13 years. European vintage black-and-gold décor, with a wooden bar worn smooth by years of use. An original coffee-by-day, cocktails-by-night concept — specialty coffee through the afternoon, then the lights dim and it transforms into a serious cocktail bar after dark.</li><li><strong>Signature drinks</strong>: Pistachio Dirty, Espresso Martini (made with espresso); pairs well with a croissant.</li><li><strong>Address</strong>: 66 Tangba Street, Jinjiang District, Chengdu</li><li><strong>Why visit</strong>: The full Chengdu café experience, from afternoon clarity to evening ease — stay from mid-afternoon into the night and you''ll understand why Chengdu people are so good at slowing down.</li></ul><h2>6. Serendipity Blend</h2><ul><li><strong>What makes it special</strong>: A roughly 20-square-metre "stand-up café" — not a single chair inside, yet it regularly moves over 14,000 yuan worth of coffee in just 5 hours. Famous for blending local Sichuan ingredients into coffee, most notably folding the tingly, aromatic kick of Sichuan peppercorn into each cup.</li><li><strong>Signature coffee</strong>: Sichuan Peppercorn Dirty (a collision of espresso and cold milk, with the subtle numbing tingle of peppercorn quietly blooming in the sweet, milky finish — a landmark example of locally rooted Sichuan coffee innovation).</li><li><strong>Address</strong>: Yulin-Fangcao Street area, Wuhou District, Chengdu (confirm the exact address before visiting)</li><li><strong>Why visit</strong>: The Chengdu phenomenon that the entire Chinese coffee world is talking about. A truly one-of-a-kind "Sichuan-flavored coffee" experience you simply cannot find anywhere else.</li></ul><h2>7. Chuanna Wanhai</h2><ul><li><strong>What makes it special</strong>: Sources light-roasted beans exclusively from Glitch, a celebrated specialty roastery in Tokyo, Japan, delivered directly to the shop each month. Bean packaging notes the roasting date and flavor description. Famous for serving Dirty coffee in cups frozen to minus 86 degrees Celsius. The original location carries a dark art aesthetic; the Liangzijie branch features a serene koi pond.</li><li><strong>Signature coffee</strong>: Minus-86-degree frozen-cup vanilla Dirty (40 yuan; a striking contrast of ice and heat).</li><li><strong>Address</strong>: 153 Zhongdao Street, Jinjiang District, Chengdu</li><li><strong>Why visit</strong>: A rare chance in Chengdu to experience world-class Japanese light-roasting craft — Glitch is globally known for its precision in preserving a bean''s original fruit aromas. A must-visit for the serious coffee enthusiast.</li></ul><h2>8. Ginko</h2><ul><li><strong>What makes it special</strong>: The defining Japanese-inspired, calming café experience in Chengdu. Natural wood tones, soft light filtered through white voile curtains, fiddle-leaf figs and monstera plants adding touches of green — every corner feels gently softening. Hand-written menus and understated ceramic cups and saucers with cherry blossom patterns: the healing atmosphere is in every detail.</li><li><strong>Signature pairing</strong>: Japanese light-roast pour-over coffee with a matcha chiffon cake (the gentle bitterness of the matcha and the toasty warmth of the coffee are a perfect match; the cake is made in limited quantities daily and may sell out after 2:00 PM).</li><li><strong>Address</strong>: 21-17 Qinglong Lane, Qingyang District, Chengdu</li><li><strong>Why visit</strong>: The ideal place for foreign visitors to experience where Japanese café culture and Chengdu''s unhurried pace of life meet. Perfect for quiet reading, journaling, or an afternoon catch-up with friends. The message wall is filled with handwritten notes from guests.</li></ul><h2>9. Dopamina+</h2><ul><li><strong>What makes it special</strong>: A neighborhood café built around pour-over coffee as its core strength. The bean menu changes constantly — there is always something at the bar you haven''t seen before, whether an unusual processing method, a lesser-known origin, or a roaster you''ve never heard of. The vibe is relaxed and easygoing; the bar is close enough to watch every step of the brewing process.</li><li><strong>Signature coffee</strong>: Seasonal single-origin pour-over (tell the barista your flavor preferences and they will recommend the right bean for you).</li><li><strong>Address</strong>: Unit 13, 151 Shuangqiao Road, Chenghua District, Chengdu</li><li><strong>Why visit</strong>: FLTR Magazine''s pick for a dedicated pour-over café — "there is always something interesting to try." Perfect for anyone who wants to explore the full range of coffee flavors; every visit may turn up something new.</li></ul><h2>10. Agua Café</h2><ul><li><strong>What makes it special</strong>: Chengdu''s first café to bring the Japanese omakase concept into coffee. There is no fixed menu — the owner selects 2 to 3 self-roasted beans based on the day''s conditions and your personal flavor preferences, brewing each one in sequence while explaining the origin story and the reasoning behind each brewing parameter.</li><li><strong>Signature experience</strong>: Omakase pour-over tasting session (a comparative tasting of 2 to 3 beans, finishing with a handwritten card noting the brewing parameters for each cup).</li><li><strong>Address</strong>: Dianjiangtai area, Jinjiang District, Chengdu (near Chunxi Road and Taikoo Li)</li><li><strong>Why visit</strong>: An immersive experience that feels like a private coffee masterclass — a maximum of 6 guests per session, advance reservation required, quiet and intimate atmosphere. Ideal for anyone who wants a deeper understanding of how pour-over coffee works.</li></ul><h2>📋 Quick Reference: Locations by District</h2><p>| Area | Cafés | |------|-------| | <strong>Near Kuanzhai Alley</strong> | Pick Coffee, UM! Coffee Brewer | | <strong>Tangba Street / Taikoo Li</strong> | UID Cafe, Agua Café | | <strong>Keghua North Road / Zhuyuan Lane</strong> | Goût &amp; Co | | <strong>Mengzhuiwan / Huaxing Road</strong> | Raindrops Coffee | | <strong>Yulin / Fangcao Street</strong> | Serendipity Blend | | <strong>Zhongdao Street</strong> | Chuanna Wanhai | | <strong>Qinglong Street / Wenshu Monastery</strong> | Ginko | | <strong>Shuangqiao Road</strong> | Dopamina+ |</p><h2>⚠️ Important Notes</h2><p>1. <strong>Opening hours</strong>: Most independent cafés in Chengdu close between 6 and 7 PM, and some take days off on weekends. Check current operating status via Dianping or Xiaohongshu before heading out. 2. <strong>Reservations</strong>: Agua Café (the omakase experience requires advance booking; maximum 6 guests per session); Ginko (the matcha chiffon cake is made in limited quantities daily — arrive before 2:00 PM to be safe). 3. <strong>Language</strong>: All of the above are independently owned and run, and English proficiency varies. A translation app on your phone will help with ordering. 4. <strong>Payment</strong>: WeChat Pay and Alipay are accepted everywhere; some locations also take international credit cards. Having a mobile payment option set up is recommended. 5. <strong>Getting there</strong>: Chengdu''s metro network covers most of the areas above. For older neighborhoods like Yulin and Tangba Street, a shared bike or a walk is the best way to soak up the local atmosphere.</p>',
  '[]'::jsonb,
  1,
  TRUE
) ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
  city_id = EXCLUDED.city_id,
  title_en = EXCLUDED.title_en,
  title_zh = EXCLUDED.title_zh,
  subtitle = EXCLUDED.subtitle,
  icon = EXCLUDED.icon,
  badge = EXCLUDED.badge,
  cover_images = EXCLUDED.cover_images,
  body = EXCLUDED.body,
  meta_items = EXCLUDED.meta_items,
  audio_url = NULL,
  audio_title = NULL,
  audio_duration_seconds = 0,
  audio_quote = NULL,
  audio_transcript = NULL,
  display_order = EXCLUDED.display_order,
  is_published = EXCLUDED.is_published,
  updated_at = NOW();

INSERT INTO city_guides (
  id, city_id, title_en, title_zh, subtitle, icon, badge,
  cover_images, body, meta_items, display_order, is_published
) VALUES (
  'chengdu_sichuan_museum',
  'chengdu',
  'Sichuan Museum: Visitor Routes and Attraction Guide',
  '四川博物院参观路线与景点介绍',
  NULL,
  '🏛',
  'Museum',
  ARRAY[]::TEXT[],
  '<p>Sichuan Museum is located at 251 South Huanhua Road, Qingyang District, Chengdu, within the scenic Huanhua Creek Historic Cultural Area, adjacent to Du Fu Thatched Cottage. As the largest comprehensive museum in southwest China and a National First-Class Museum, Sichuan Museum holds a collection of more than 350,000 cultural relics, of which over 70,000 are classified as precious, presenting a complete historical panorama of Sichuan from prehistoric times through the Ming and Qing dynasties. <strong>The museum''s architecture draws on the design elements of west Sichuan vernacular buildings, featuring steeply pitched roofs, timber-frame construction, and dark grey roof tiles</strong>, creating a presence that is dignified and commanding while remaining warmly rooted in local tradition.</p><p>Visitor Notes (Responsible Travel):</p><p><strong>Recommended Route</strong>: <strong>The museum''s exhibition area spans three floors. The recommended visiting order is Second Floor → Third Floor → First Floor</strong>, following the chronological sequence of Sichuan history for a clear sense of how the region''s culture evolved.</p><h2>Open Tuesday through Sunday, 9:00 AM to 5:00 PM (last entry at 4:00 PM)</h2><p><strong>Recommended visit duration</strong>: 3 to 5 hours</p><p>Foreign-language ticketing enquiries: +86-28-65521888 | +86-28-65521569 | +86-28-65521555</p><h3>Second Floor: Ancient Sichuan — Prehistoric Gallery</h3><p>The <strong>Prehistoric Gallery</strong> on the second floor is the first section of Sichuan''s comprehensive history exhibition. Through more than 340 artifacts, it traces the story of early human settlement and cultural exchange in the Sichuan Basin.</p><p>This gallery follows the arc of archaeological discovery from the Paleolithic through the Neolithic, showing how early humans in Sichuan moved from basic survival to the dawn of civilization. <strong>Key exhibits include a Neolithic painted pottery bottle and a jade pendant in the shape of a human face</strong>. The pottery bottle resembles a bamboo tube, slightly narrowed at the waist with a rolled rim and a flat base, its surface decorated with black parallel lines and rope patterns — an expression of early Yangtze River painted pottery culture. The human-face jade pendant reflects prehistoric Sichuan''s jade-working skills and spiritual beliefs.</p><p>The gallery also displays other representative artifacts from early Sichuan civilization, including stone tools, pottery, and jade objects, showing how the ancient inhabitants adapted to Sichuan''s complex geography and created a rich and distinctive prehistoric culture. <strong>Through these precious relics, you can touch the very first threads of Sichuan''s civilization and feel the ingenuity and creativity of the people who once lived in this land of Ba and Shu.</strong></p><h3>Second Floor: Ancient Sichuan — Pre-Qin Period Gallery</h3><p>The <strong>Pre-Qin Period Gallery</strong> on the second floor is the second section of Sichuan''s comprehensive history exhibition. Through nearly 200 precious artifacts, it presents the development of the Ba-Shu region during the pre-Qin era.</p><p>This gallery focuses on the Ba-Shu civilization of the Shang, Zhou, and Warring States periods, showcasing the region''s distinctive bronze culture, ritual systems, and social life. <strong>Key exhibits include a Western Zhou dynasty bronze lei vessel with elephant-trunk handles and kui dragon patterns, a Warring States period bronze hu vessel with water and land battle scenes, and Sanxingdui bronze artifacts</strong>. The bronze lei vessel features three layers of relief — elephant heads at the shoulders and animal masks on the belly — serving as compelling evidence of cultural exchange between ancient Shu and the Central Plains ritual tradition. The battle-scene bronze hu vessel has been called a "Warring States version of the Along the River During the Qingming Festival scroll," its surface inlaid with red copper wire forming four bands of imagery depicting warfare, daily life, and production in the Ba-Shu region.</p><p>The gallery also displays weapons, ritual vessels, and everyday objects from the Ba-Shu area, including bronze swords, spears, and halberds, as well as the distinctive writing and symbols of Ba-Shu culture. <strong>These exhibits not only reveal the unique character of Ba-Shu civilization, but also shed light on its cultural exchanges and interactions with the Central Plains, Chu, and other surrounding regions.</strong></p><h3>Second Floor: Zhang Daqian Painting and Calligraphy Gallery</h3><p>The <strong>Zhang Daqian Painting and Calligraphy Gallery</strong> on the second floor is a dedicated showcase of the artist''s achievements. Sichuan Museum holds a large collection of works by Zhang Daqian, most notably 183 copies he made of Dunhuang murals — a holding that has earned the museum its reputation as the world''s richest repository of Zhang Daqian''s work.</p><p>This gallery is divided into three sections: Zhang Daqian''s copies of Dunhuang murals, his freehand paintings, and his personal seal collection. <strong>Must-see works include "Copy of an Early Tang Bodhisattva with Necklace" and "Copy of the Donor Portrait of the Governor''s Wife, Lady Wang of Taiyuan."</strong> The former reveals Zhang Daqian''s deep study and transmission of Dunhuang mural art, employing the "Cao style" technique — in which drapery appears to cling to the body as if wet — an approach associated with the Northern Qi painter Cao Zhongda, in which the folds press close to the figure as if floating in water.</p><p>The gallery also features Zhang Daqian''s early works, including figure paintings of court ladies, flower-and-bird paintings, and landscape paintings, as well as the various seals he used. <strong>Through these works, you can trace Zhang Daqian''s artistic journey from tradition to innovation, and see how he wove together Ba-Shu culture and Dunhuang art to create a style entirely his own.</strong></p><h3>Third Floor: Ancient Sichuan — Jin through Five Dynasties Period Gallery</h3><p>The <strong>Jin through Five Dynasties Period Gallery</strong> on the third floor is the fourth section of Sichuan''s comprehensive history exhibition. Through more than 280 artifacts, it highlights the "cultural sparks" that flew when different peoples and dynasties collided during an era of shifting power.</p><p>This gallery is divided into two units — the Jin and Northern-Southern Dynasties period, and the Sui-Tang through Five Dynasties period. <strong>Key exhibits include a Southern Qi Yongming-era stone stele of Amitayus Buddha, a Tang dynasty seven-string qin named "Ice-Breaking at the Rocky Stream," and a Five Dynasties period jade belt belonging to Former Shu King Wang Jian.</strong> The Amitayus stone stele is one of the earliest surviving Southern Dynasties Buddhist sculpture steles in Sichuan with a confirmed date, showcasing the "slender figure with delicate folds" aesthetic of Southern Dynasties Buddhist art. The qin named "Ice-Breaking at the Rocky Stream" is one of fewer than 20 surviving Tang dynasty instruments of its kind; it has been exhibited in Singapore and stands as testimony to the glory of Tang dynasty music.</p><p>The gallery also displays ceramics, gold and silverwork, and paintings and calligraphy from the Tang and Song periods, including Tang sancai ware and fragmentary stone classics from the Later Shu of the Five Dynasties, reflecting the economic prosperity and cultural flowering of Sichuan during this era. <strong>Through these exhibits, you can trace the spread and development of Buddhism in Sichuan, and the rich historical blending of different peoples and cultures across the region.</strong></p><h3>Third Floor: Sichuan Ethnic Minority Artifacts Gallery</h3><p>The <strong>Sichuan Ethnic Minority Artifacts Gallery</strong> on the third floor showcases the cultures and lives of the 14 indigenous ethnic minority groups of Sichuan. Sichuan Museum has selected more than 200 exhibits for this gallery, organized into four sections: Yi People of the Mountains, Qiang Village Life, Tibetan Plateau Culture, and Colorful Miao Country.</p><p><strong>Key exhibits include Yi ethnic costumes, a Tibetan gilded bronze mask, and a Qiang sheepskin drum.</strong> The Yi costumes are represented by those from the Liangshan Yi Autonomous Prefecture: both men and women wear right-lapel robes, and men traditionally grow a single tuft of hair on the front of the crown — known as the "Hero''s Knot" — while women''s dress varies between unmarried and married styles. The Tibetan gilded bronze mask reflects the characteristics of Tibetan religious belief and ritual ceremony.</p><p>The gallery also displays Miao silver jewelry, Tujia brocade, and other ethnic craft objects, along with daily utensils and production tools from various ethnic groups. <strong>These exhibits not only express the distinctive artistic styles and practical wisdom of Sichuan''s ethnic peoples, but also embody the unity-in-diversity that defines Chinese culture as a whole.</strong></p><h3>Third Floor: Arts and Crafts Gallery</h3><p>The <strong>Arts and Crafts Gallery</strong> on the third floor presents the finest works from Sichuan Museum''s collection of decorative arts and crafts, spanning a period from as early as the Shang dynasty to the late Qing dynasty and early Republic of China period.</p><p><strong>Key exhibits include a Qing dynasty thangka depicting King Gesar, a Tang dynasty celadon-glazed warrior figurine, and a Qing dynasty ivory-carved screen illustrating scenes from Dream of the Red Chamber.</strong> The King Gesar thangka is an artistic rendering of the Tibetan epic "The Epic of King Gesar." The Tang Bodhisattva head, celebrated as the "Eastern Goddess of Beauty," represents the perfect union of Buddhist art and Tang dynasty craftsmanship. The gallery also displays jade objects, gold and silver work, items carved from bamboo, wood, ivory, and horn, lacquerware, shadow puppets, snuff bottles, and embroidery spanning the Shang dynasty through the early Republican era — including jade belt hooks and a double-sided Shu embroidery vase featuring cats and dogs.</p><p><strong>These objects are not only distinctive in form, vibrant in color, and exquisite in carving — most were also practical items for daily use, reflecting the ancient craftsman''s gift for weaving art and life seamlessly together.</strong> The Arts and Crafts Gallery offers a vivid encounter with the deep craft traditions and consummate skill of the Ba-Shu region.</p><h3>First Floor: Sichuan Han Dynasty Ceramic and Stone Art Gallery</h3><p>The <strong>Sichuan Han Dynasty Ceramic and Stone Art Gallery</strong> on the first floor is one of the museum''s principal permanent galleries. The Han dynasty ceramic and stone art represented here — through pictorial stones, pictorial bricks, and ceramic sculpture — arose from the era''s custom of lavish burial, and carries a strong sense of ethnic character and its historical moment.</p><p><strong>Must-see exhibits include an Eastern Han dynasty ceramic storytelling and singing figurine and the pictorial brick "Salt Well."</strong> The storytelling figurine has been called the "forefather of comic performance": exquisitely preserved, it shows a figure with a topknot, half-closed eyes, a lopsided grin with tongue poking out, both arms raised high, the left hand cradling a small drum and the right gripping a mallet — a vivid portrait of the cheerful, free-spirited attitude of Han dynasty Sichuanese. The pictorial brick "Salt Well" depicts the production of Sichuan well-salt from a bird''s-eye view and has been called the world''s earliest "industrial process diagram," reflecting the advanced handicraft technology of Han dynasty Sichuan.</p><p>The gallery also displays Han dynasty ceramic figurines, pictorial stones, and bronze objects, including an exorcism figurine and a bronze money tree. <strong>These exhibits illuminate both the social life and artistic achievements of Han dynasty Sichuan, and the spiritual beliefs and views on life and death held by the people of that era.</strong></p><h3>First Floor: Wanfo Temple Stone Carving Gallery</h3><p>The <strong>Wanfo Temple Stone Carving Gallery</strong> on the first floor is one of the museum''s permanent galleries. It displays Buddhist stone sculpture unearthed from the site of Wanfo Temple in Chengdu — pieces that have been excavated continuously since the eighth year of the Guangxu reign (1882) — amounting to more than 200 figures, the majority of which are now held at Sichuan Museum.</p><p>The Wanfo Temple stone carvings are a significant body of evidence for Buddhist sculpture of the Southern Dynasties and of the Sichuan region. <strong>Key exhibits include a standing figure of Shakyamuni from the fourth year of the Putong era of the Liang dynasty of the Southern Dynasties, and a Tang dynasty Bodhisattva head.</strong> The Liang-dynasty Shakyamuni figure bears a precisely dated inscription and reflects the artistic style and devotional spirit of Southern Dynasties Buddhist art. The Tang dynasty Bodhisattva head has been celebrated as the "Eastern Goddess of Beauty," representing the peak of Tang Buddhist sculpture.</p><p>The sculptures in this gallery cover a wide range of subjects, including Buddhas, Bodhisattvas, inscription steles, and niche carvings, and are characterized by the Southern Dynasties aesthetic of slender elegance and flowing, ample robes. <strong>These works hold exceptional artistic value and serve as an important historical record of the spread and development of Buddhism throughout Sichuan.</strong></p>',
  '[]'::jsonb,
  2,
  TRUE
) ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
