INSERT INTO city_guides (
  id, city_id, title_en, title_zh, subtitle, icon, badge,
  cover_images, body, meta_items, display_order, is_published
) VALUES (
  'hangzhou_ancient_legends',
  'hangzhou',
  'Hangzhou''s Classic Ancient Legends: A Story Collection for International Visitors',
  '杭州经典古代传说·国际游客专属故事集（全考据·可直接使用）',
  NULL,
  '📖',
  'Culture',
  ARRAY[]::TEXT[],
  '<p><strong>Introduction:</strong> Hangzhou is a city steeped in legend. Among its hills and waters lie hundreds of folk stories handed down over the centuries, many now recognized as national or provincial intangible cultural heritage. This collection gathers six of the most beloved and most fitting for travelers — <strong>the Heavenly Pearl of West Lake, the Three Pools Mirroring the Moon, the White Snake, King Qian and the Tide, the Butterfly Lovers, and the Grateful Ant King.</strong> Each is retold from traditional records in plain, vivid English, setting aside difficult classical phrasing while keeping the beauty and spirit of the originals — ready for visitors to read, for guides to tell, and for tourism programs to share.</p><h2>The Legend of West Lake''s Heavenly Pearl</h2><p>High above the mortal world, the old story goes, two divine creatures lived along the Milky Way: a jade dragon that ruled the eastern river of stars, and a phoenix that made its home in the west. For ages they wandered the heavens in peace, until one day they came upon a plain, unpolished stone resting on a floating island in the sky.</p><p>Something about the stone drew them in, and they decided to make a treasure of it. The dragon worked at it patiently, day after day; the phoenix smoothed it with its claws, season after season. Slowly the rough stone became a glowing pearl, and its light carried the beauty of mountains and rivers within it.</p><p>This was no ordinary jewel. Wherever its light fell, hills turned green and water ran clear, flowers bloomed, and the land below brought in good harvests and quiet, peaceful years. It was the finest gift the heavens had ever offered the mortal world.</p><p>But even the heavens are not free of greed. The Queen Mother of the West coveted the pearl, and while the dragon and phoenix slept, she sent her soldiers to steal it. When the two woke to find their life''s work gone, they flew to the heavenly court to demand its return. The Queen Mother refused, and a struggle broke out among the immortals.</p><p>In the chaos, the pearl slipped loose, tumbled out of the sky, and fell to the land of Qiantang. The moment it touched the earth, it spread into a wide, clear lake — the West Lake of today.</p><p>Unable to part with their pearl, the jade dragon and the phoenix gave up their place among the immortals. They came down to earth and became two mountains that still stand guard over the lake: Yuhuang Mountain (Jade Emperor Mountain) and Fenghuang Mountain (Phoenix Mountain).</p><p>For as long as anyone can remember, the mountains have framed the lake and the lake has mirrored the mountains. An old local rhyme sums it up: <strong>"West Lake, a pearl dropped from heaven; dragon and phoenix dancing forever over Qiantang."</strong> It is the legend behind Hangzhou''s most famous view — heaven''s romance settled gently into an earthly landscape.</p><h2>The Three Pools Mirroring the Moon</h2><p>West Lake''s loveliest night scene, the Three Pools Mirroring the Moon, comes with a legend of cleverness and courage — and it features Lu Ban, the master craftsman of Chinese tradition.</p><p>Long ago, a black fish demon is said to have lived deep in the lake. It would stir up violent waves, flood Hangzhou, and bring misery to the people along the shore. Arrogant and greedy, the demon demanded Lu Ban''s younger sister in marriage as the price for leaving the city in peace.</p><p>Lu Ban''s sister answered with remarkable nerve. She agreed to the marriage — not out of fear, but to save the people of Hangzhou — and set a single condition: the demon must carry, as a wedding gift, a great stone incense burner made by Lu Ban himself.</p><p>Too sure of himself to suspect a trap, the demon agreed. Lu Ban spent days and nights carving a massive, heavy stone burner. When it was done, the demon dragged it out to the middle of the lake.</p><p>The moment it reached the center, Lu Ban''s sister gave the signal. The huge burner flipped over, pressed down into the mud, and pinned the demon beneath it. Trapped for good, the demon could do no more harm, and Hangzhou was free of it at last.</p><p>The burner sank into the lakebed, leaving only its three gourd-shaped feet above the surface — and those are the three stone towers of the Three Pools Mirroring the Moon.</p><p>On the night of the Mid-Autumn Festival, when the moon is full, local people light candles inside the hollow towers and cover the openings with thin paper. The candlelight glows through the water and mixes with the moonlight, scattering dozens of small moons across the lake. Moon in the sky, moon in the towers, moon on the water — all overlapping at once, in what may be the most dreamlike view West Lake has to offer.</p><h2>Legend of the White Snake</h2><p>West Lake has always been a place where the rain seems to write romance. The Legend of the White Snake, one of <strong>China''s four great folk legends</strong>, was born in its misty waters and has moved people for centuries with its story of love and devotion.</p><p>The tale begins with a white snake that spent a thousand years cultivating spiritual power in the mountains. By chance she came upon an immortal''s elixir — left, some versions say, by the immortal Lu Dongbin — which gave her hundreds more years of power and the ability to take the form of a beautiful woman. She named herself Bai Suzhen, the White Lady.</p><p>Kind by nature, Bai Suzhen never forgot a young man who had saved her life long before. Following an old thread of fate, she came to Hangzhou''s West Lake to find him.</p><p>It happened on a rainy Qingming day, with soft rain veiling the whole lake. On the Broken Bridge, Bai Suzhen met Xu Xian — the very man who had saved her in a past life. They shared a single umbrella in the drizzle, and a thousand years of waiting turned, in that moment, into love.</p><p>They married and made a quiet life in Hangzhou, using Bai Suzhen''s powers to heal the sick and help the poor, and the local people came to love them. But a union between a mortal and an immortal broke heaven''s rules. A monk named Fahai, rigid in his doctrine, set out to tear the couple apart.</p><p>To protect her husband and their home, Bai Suzhen called up the river itself and flooded Jinshan Temple — a desperate act of defiance for love''s sake. In the end she was imprisoned beneath Leifeng Pagoda, yet her love never wavered.</p><p>Years later, the story goes, the grievances were at last set right, and the Broken Bridge — where they first met — became the place of their reunion. Today, when visitors cross the Broken Bridge in West Lake''s drifting rain, they are walking through more than a pretty scene: they are stepping into one of the most devoted love stories in Chinese folklore.</p><h2>King Qian Shoots the Tide</h2><p>The Qiantang River''s tidal bore is one of the great natural spectacles of China, and it comes with a heroic legend that has been told for over a thousand years.</p><p>In the old days, the story goes, the Qiantang tide brought ruin to the villages along its banks. A cruel tide spirit raised monstrous waves day after day, smashing the dikes, flooding the fields, and destroying homes. Year after year, people built embankments to hold back the water, and year after year the tide swept their work away overnight.</p><p>During the Five Dynasties period, the Hangzhou region was ruled by King Qian Liu. Brave and just, devoted to his people, he could not bear to watch them suffer. Convinced that the floods were the work of the unruly tide spirit, he resolved to face it down and defend his land.</p><p>On the eighteenth day of the eighth lunar month — said to be the tide spirit''s day — King Qian gathered ten thousand archers along the river. On the way, legend holds, he kicked open a narrow path through the rock of Baoshi Mountain to let his army pass, leaving a great footprint in the stone that locals still point out today.</p><p>Before the battle, he wrote a solemn vow and cast it into the river: *"I stand against the tide spirit and guard these waters; the Qiantang shall belong to the city and its people."*</p><p>The tide spirit paid no heed. The waves rose like mountains and rushed the shore. King Qian drew his bow and loosed the first arrow, and his ten thousand archers loosed theirs after him — volley upon volley driving into the oncoming wall of water.</p><p>Under that endless rain of arrows, the tide finally fell back. The waves that had once seemed unstoppable retreated to the southwest and were gone.</p><p>From that day, the river grew calmer. The dikes held, the floods receded, and the people along the shore could live and work in peace. In honor of the king who faced the tide for them, later generations gave his embankment a name it still carries: King Qian''s Embankment.</p><p>The legend captures something Chinese tradition holds dear: do not bow to disaster, stand up to whatever threatens the people, and guard your home and your life with courage.</p><h2>The Butterfly Lovers</h2><p>Among <strong>China''s four great folk legends</strong> stands the story of Liang Shanbo and Zhu Yingtai — a love rooted in the Hangzhou landscape, faithful and unyielding, that reaches past the line between life and death.</p><p>Long ago, a bright and daring young woman named Zhu Yingtai longed to study, in an age when women were kept from the schoolroom. She disguised herself as a man and traveled far to Hangzhou to pursue her education. On the way she met Liang Shanbo, a kind and honest scholar, and the two soon swore to be sworn brothers.</p><p>For three years they studied side by side and shared every joy and hardship. Yingtai slowly fell in love with the gentle, sincere Shanbo, hiding both her feelings and her true identity. Shanbo, honest to a fault, saw only his dearest brother and never sensed the love beside him.</p><p>When letters called her home, Yingtai had to end her studies. As they parted, she hinted again and again at who she really was and what she felt, hoping for a future together. They walked side by side for eighteen miles along the lake — a farewell remembered ever since as the <strong>"Eighteen-Mile Farewell."</strong></p><p>Back home, Yingtai''s family forced her into a marriage with a wealthy household, against her will. Only later did Shanbo learn the truth — that his "brother" was a woman, and that she loved him. Overcome with regret and longing, he fell ill and died.</p><p>On the day of Yingtai''s wedding, wind and rain swept the land. As her bridal procession passed Shanbo''s tomb, thunder split the sky and the grave cracked open. Without hesitation, Yingtai cast off her bridal robes and leapt in to join him.</p><p>In the next moment the storm cleared, and two butterflies rose from the tomb, drifting together over the hills and water of Hangzhou — never to be parted again.</p><p>For centuries, those butterflies have stood for the truest kind of Eastern love: loyal, patient, and lasting beyond life itself.</p><h2>The Grateful Ant King</h2><p>The Qiantang River carries heroic tales of battling the tide, but it also holds a gentler story — a fable of kindness repaid, preserved in old Chinese texts and told in Hangzhou for many centuries.</p><p>Long ago, a scholar named Dong Zhaozhi was crossing the Qiantang River by boat. On the water he noticed a tiny ant clinging to a thin reed, scrambling back and forth, fighting not to be swept into the waves.</p><p>The other passengers laughed and wanted to crush it — just a useless insect, they said. But Dong Zhaozhi pitied the little creature''s struggle. Ignoring their jeers, he gently lifted the ant onto the boat and saved its life.</p><p>That night he had a vivid dream. A man in black robes, leading a great retinue, came to thank him. "I am the king of the ants," the man said. "I fell into the river by accident, and your kindness saved me. If you are ever in danger, call my name, and I will repay you."</p><p>More than ten years later, troubled times came. Dong Zhaozhi was falsely accused of robbery and thrown into the jail at Yuhang. Facing charges he had not earned and bound in heavy chains, he sank into despair — and then remembered the ant king''s promise.</p><p>Quietly, he set a few ants in his palm and silently told them his plight. That night, countless ants poured into the jail and gnawed through the wooden chains that held him. Freed, he slipped out and fled to the hills of Yuhang to hide.</p><p>Soon afterward, a general amnesty was declared, and Dong Zhaozhi was cleared of every false charge.</p><p>This old Qiantang legend carries a truth the Chinese have long cherished: <strong>no act of kindness is too small, and every good deed finds its reward.</strong> Even the smallest life deserves mercy — and mercy, given sincerely, has a way of coming back.</p><p><strong>Closing note:</strong> All six legends are retold from Hangzhou''s intangible cultural heritage records and classical texts, in plain, international English. Like all great folk legends, these stories survive in many versions; this collection keeps their core plots and cultural meaning while weaving in Hangzhou''s landscapes, history, and humanistic spirit — suitable for visitors to enjoy on tour, for cultural understanding, and for tourism promotion.</p>',
  '[]'::jsonb,
  1,
  TRUE
) ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
  city_id = EXCLUDED.city_id,
  title_en = EXCLUDED.title_en,
