INSERT INTO city_guides (
  id, city_id, title_en, title_zh, subtitle, icon, badge,
  cover_images, body, meta_items, display_order, is_published
) VALUES (
  'hangzhou_butterfly_lovers',
  'hangzhou',
  'The Butterfly Lovers: China''s Timeless Tale of Loyal Love',
  'The Butterfly Lovers: China''s Timeless Tale of Loyal Love（梁祝化蝶·外国游客完整版故事）',
  NULL,
  '📖',
  'Culture',
  ARRAY[]::TEXT[],
  '<p><strong>Introduction:</strong> The West has *Romeo and Juliet*. China has *Liang Shanbo and Zhu Yingtai* — a love story so famous that it is often called "the Romeo and Juliet of the East." Both tales follow two lovers who defy the rules of their world and find each other again only beyond death. But their spirit is different. Shakespeare''s tragedy is loud, fevered, and quick to violence. The Butterfly Lovers is quiet and patient: no shouting, no duels, just a love held in silence for years and, in the end, two butterflies rising from a grave. Where the Western story burns, the Eastern one endures.</p><h2>East-West Cultural Contrast</h2><p>Both are love tragedies that have moved people across the centuries and the world, both driven at their core by the pure desire to break through the bonds of convention and face life and death for love. But the two stories arise from very different cultural soils. Romeo and Juliet is passionate and direct — it ends in fierce confrontation and tragic catastrophe, an explosion of bold Western-style romance. The Butterfly Lovers, by contrast, is gentle and understated. There is no shouting, no dueling, only a love hidden in silence for years, expressed at last through the image of two butterflies drifting together forever — the Chinese romantic vision of a devotion that outlasts even the boundary between life and death.</p><p>The Butterfly Lovers is one of <strong>China''s four great folk legends</strong>, and today it is recognized as part of China''s national intangible cultural heritage. Versions of the tale have been told for well over a thousand years, and one of its earliest written records appears in the Tang-dynasty collection *Xuanshi zhi* (Records of the Dark Chamber). Set among the lakes and green hills of Hangzhou and the wider Zhejiang region, it is far more than a sad romance. It is a story about a young woman''s courage, about loyalty kept through silence, and about a love that outlasts both social prejudice and death itself.</p><p>During the Eastern Jin dynasty — an age that prized learning and elegant conversation — there lived a young woman named Zhu Yingtai in Shangyu, Zhejiang. Bright and restless, she refused to accept the custom that women should stay at home and leave scholarship to men. She wanted to study, and she wanted to see the world. So she did something daring: she cut her hair, put on a scholar''s robes, disguised herself as a young man, and set off for Hangzhou, the cultural heart of the region, to attend the academy.</p><p>On the road, Yingtai met Liang Shanbo, a modest, good-natured scholar from Kuaiji. He was honest to the point of innocence, kind to everyone, and they took to each other at once. They shared the same love of books and the same gentle temperament, and before long they swore to be sworn brothers. Together they began three years of study by the misty rivers and wooded hills outside Hangzhou.</p><p>For three years they shared a desk. They read at dawn, argued happily over poems, and kept each other company through long evenings and rainy nights. Somewhere in those years, Yingtai fell in love. She watched the way Shanbo lost himself in a book, noticed the small kindnesses he never thought to mention, and treasured every ordinary day beside him. But she could not say a word. Her secret kept her affection locked behind the mask of brotherhood.</p><p>Shanbo, for his part, never guessed. He trusted his "brother" completely and never imagined that the clever companion at his side was a woman who had given him her whole heart. Yingtai dropped hint after hint — a turn of phrase, a pointed comparison — hoping he might understand. He never did. His mind stayed fixed on friendship and study.</p><p>In time, letters from home arrived, one after another, calling Yingtai back. A dutiful daughter, she had no choice but to leave the life she loved in Hangzhou. On the day she set out, Shanbo insisted on walking her part of the way — eighteen miles along the winding lakeside road. That long, reluctant walk is remembered in Chinese folklore as the <strong>"Eighteen-Mile Farewell,"</strong> one of the tenderest partings in the whole tradition.</p><p>Along the way, Yingtai tried one last time. She likened the two of them to paired mandarin ducks and to butterflies flying side by side, hoping he would finally hear what she was really saying. But Shanbo only admired the cleverness of her images and missed the confession underneath. At the mountain pass they said goodbye — neither of them knowing it was the last time they would walk together while both still lived.</p><p>Back home, Yingtai''s wealthy family had already arranged her marriage to Ma Wencai, the son of a powerful local household. Bound by family duty and the customs of her time, she could not refuse. Her heart stayed with Liang Shanbo, and her days filled with longing.</p><p>Months later, Shanbo traveled to visit his sworn brother at last — and only then, at the Zhu family home, did he learn the truth: his gentle, gifted "brother" was a young woman. In a single moment, three years of small hints and quiet moments suddenly made sense. He understood, finally, the love Yingtai had carried in silence for so long.</p><p>Shaken by regret and hope at once, Shanbo asked the Zhu family for her hand. But he was too late. The match with the Ma family was already sealed, and rigid custom left no room to undo it. The two who had only just recognized each other''s hearts were pulled apart by a fate neither could fight.</p><p>Heartbroken, Shanbo fell ill. His health gave way, and before long he died, his love unfulfilled. His last wish was simple: that he be buried beside the road at the foot of the mountain, so that if Yingtai ever passed that way, she might see his grave one last time.</p><p>When word of his death reached her, Yingtai''s world fell apart. She wept day and night and swore she would marry no one else — yet she could not openly defy her family. So on her wedding day she asked for one thing only: to let the bridal procession stop at Shanbo''s tomb, so she could pay her respects.</p><p>The morning of the wedding was grey and windy. As the bridal carriage neared the lonely grave, dark clouds rolled in, thunder broke overhead, and rain came down in sheets. The wind tore at the wedding banners, and the whole procession was forced to halt before the tomb.</p><p>Still in her bridal robes, Yingtai stepped down, knelt at the grave, and wept. In that moment of grief, the legend says, the ground split and Shanbo''s tomb cracked open before her.</p><p>Without hesitation, Yingtai cast off her bridal ornaments and leapt into the open tomb to join him.</p><p>The instant she did, the thunder stopped, the rain cleared, and a rainbow arched across the sky. From the closed grave rose two butterflies, drifting up together over the green hills and bright water of Zhejiang — side by side, and never parting again.</p><p>For centuries since, those two butterflies have stood for a love that no rule could bind and no death could break. In Chinese tradition, butterflies are free, faithful, and inseparable.</p><p>That is the heart of the Butterfly Lovers: love that is not limited by gender, rank, or custom, and that outlasts even the line between life and death. More than a thousand years on, the story still moves visitors from around the world — China''s quiet, unbreakable answer to the question of what loyal love can mean.</p><p><strong>Cultural and Historical Note:</strong> This retelling follows the traditional legend as preserved in classical sources such as the Tang-dynasty *Xuanshi zhi* and in China''s intangible cultural heritage records. Like all great folk legends, the tale exists in many versions; the story here keeps the core plot and cultural meaning while telling it in plain, international English suitable for visitors, cultural programs, and tourism use.</p>',
  '[]'::jsonb,
  2,
  TRUE
) ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
