INSERT INTO city_guides (
  id, city_id, title_en, title_zh, subtitle, icon, badge,
  cover_images, body, meta_items, display_order, is_published
) VALUES (
  'nanjing_local_culture',
  'nanjing',
  'Nanjing: A Complete Guide to Local Cultural Activities for Foreign Visitors',
  '🏯 南京适合外国人体验的本地文化活动 · 完整指南',
  'All information in this guide is cross-referenced from public sources dated 2025–2026.',
  '🎭',
  'Culture',
  ARRAY[]::TEXT[],
  '<h2>Part One: Hands-on Intangible Heritage Crafts</h2><h3>1. Jinling Sutra-Engraving Workshop — Woodblock Printing Experience</h3><p>The Jinling Sutra-Engraving Workshop was founded in 1866 by Buddhist scholar Yang Renshan. It is a living heritage site for the UNESCO-recognised art of Chinese woodblock printing and houses more than 120,000 carved scripture blocks. Visitors can try every step of the traditional process — tracing, carving, inking, and rubbing — and take home a hand-printed copy of a Buddhist scripture or devotional image. With only two master carvers on site, spots are extremely rare.</p><ul><li><strong>Address:</strong> 35 Huaihai Road, Qinhuai District, Nanjing</li><li><strong>Opening hours:</strong> Tuesday to Sunday, 9:00–16:30 (closed Monday)</li><li><strong>Booking:</strong> Via the official WeChat account "Jinling Kejing Chu"; daily capacity is 80 visitors, so book at least three days ahead. Free rubbing workshops run on Wednesday and Saturday mornings, limited to 15 participants each.</li><li><strong>Price:</strong> Approximately 50 yuan per print, including materials</li></ul><p><strong>Why visit:</strong> This is a living workshop for a world-class intangible heritage craft. The idea that printing was invented in China is easy enough to grasp in the abstract — but the real cultural revelation comes the moment you brush ink onto a pear-wood block and press out crisp lines of text with a bamboo brush. With only two carvers still practising, an experience here is genuinely rare — the kind of hidden gem that defines a deep-travel itinerary.</p><h3>2. Qinhuai Intangible Heritage Hall — One-Stop Craft Workshop</h3><p>The Qinhuai Intangible Heritage Hall is the largest intangible heritage experience space in Jiangsu Province, covering 7,400 square metres and bringing together 135 heritage projects from various levels of the national list. Inside, visitors will find workshops for paper cutting, silk lanterns, velvet flower-making, shadow puppetry, and woodblock printing, as well as a Yuhua tea tasting area and an immersive digital exhibition. Heritage practitioners are in residence year-round to teach, and both Chinese and English guided tours are available.</p><ul><li><strong>Address:</strong> 21 Chaoku Street, Qinhuai District, Nanjing (within the core Confucius Temple area)</li><li><strong>Opening hours:</strong> 10:00–21:00, free admission</li><li><strong>Annual visitors:</strong> Over 500,000</li></ul><p><strong>Why visit:</strong> For foreign visitors, this is the single best starting point for understanding Nanjing''s intangible heritage. In one venue you can try paper cutting, silk lanterns, velvet flowers, shadow puppetry, and Baju folk singing — dozens of traditions under one roof, with English-language guidance. Nanjing University and other institutions have co-developed practice programmes here, and the hall has hosted groups of international students from more than 12 countries for immersive experience events.</p><h3>3. Nanjing Paper Cutting Experience</h3><p>Nanjing paper cutting is a national-level intangible heritage art and part of the UNESCO-recognised tradition of Chinese paper cutting, with roots tracing back to the early Ming dynasty. Its foremost practitioner, Zhang Lindi, holds provincial representative-inheritor status. Workshops are held at the paper-cutting studio inside the Qinhuai Intangible Heritage Hall and at the Nanjing Folk Museum (Gan Xi Former Residence), where an inheritor guides participants through the distinctive Nanjing style — described as "flowers within flowers, themes within themes" — and visitors complete a piece to take home.</p><ul><li><strong>Workshop venues:</strong> Paper-cutting studio, Qinhuai Intangible Heritage Hall; Nanjing Folk Museum (Gan Xi Former Residence)</li><li><strong>Suitable for:</strong> No prior experience needed; ideal for families and groups</li></ul><p><strong>Why visit:</strong> Nanjing paper cutting differs from its northern Chinese counterparts in its refined aesthetic — an intricate play of layered motifs and hidden imagery. A single pair of scissors and a sheet of red paper cuts through every language barrier, making this one of the most immediately satisfying cultural experiences available to any visitor. China Daily ran a feature on how Nanjing paper cutting draws large numbers of foreign visitors during the Lantern Festival.</p><h3>4. Qinhuai Silk Lantern Making</h3><p>Qinhuai silk lanterns are a national-level intangible heritage art. Workshops are held at the Qinhuai Intangible Heritage Hall and at lantern-maker studios in Laomendong. Under the guidance of a heritage practitioner, participants build a complete lantern from scratch — framing the structure, covering it in silk, painting the surface, and adding decorative details. During the "World Mayors Look at Nanjing" event in November 2025, mayors from multiple countries took part in an immersive lantern-making session.</p><ul><li><strong>Workshop venues:</strong> Qinhuai Intangible Heritage Hall; lantern-maker studios in Laomendong</li><li><strong>International visibility:</strong> Featured at the "World Mayors Look at Nanjing" event, November 2025</li></ul><p><strong>Why visit:</strong> Qinhuai silk lanterns are one of Nanjing''s most iconic cultural symbols. The 2025 Qinhuai Lantern Festival was designated the first celebration under China''s new "Intangible Heritage Spring Festival" initiative, drawing visitors from around the world with more than 350 lantern displays across five themed zones. Making a lantern by hand is not just a craft activity — it is a way of taking a piece of Nanjing''s legendary lantern glow home with you.</p><h3>5. Nanjing Cloud Brocade Museum — Weaving Experience</h3><p>Nanjing Cloud Brocade is inscribed on the UNESCO Representative List of the Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity, with a reputation that can be summed up as "an inch of brocade, an inch of gold." At the museum, visitors can watch two weavers work in perfect coordination on a grand loom standing 5.6 metres tall, and explore digital immersive installations that animate the making of imperial dragon robes and offer three-dimensional analysis of the loom''s mechanics. Hands-on workshops let visitors create a Cloud Brocade decorative piece using gold leaf with a purity of 98 percent. Admission is free with ID.</p><ul><li><strong>Address:</strong> 240 Chating East Street, Jianye District, Nanjing</li><li><strong>Opening hours:</strong> Daily, 9:30–17:00</li></ul><p><strong>Why visit:</strong> Cloud Brocade is Nanjing''s signature cultural product — the city''s calling card. The museum goes well beyond a typical "look but don''t touch" display, with VR weaving experiences and immersive digital installations. For foreign visitors, the simple sight of a 5.6-metre grand loom being operated simultaneously by two weavers is already a profound cultural jolt.</p><h3>6. Jinling Gold Leaf Forging Experience</h3><p>Jinling gold leaf forging is a national-level intangible heritage craft that originated in the Longtan Garden area of Qixia District — the site of an imperial Ming-dynasty workshop. The defining feat of the craft: one gram of gold can be beaten into roughly half a square metre of pure gold leaf, just 0.12 micrometres thick. Over 2.47 million sheets of Nanjing gold leaf were used in the restoration of the Forbidden City, and the craft continues to supply gilding for major heritage sites including the Forbidden City and the Potala Palace. Experience activities include gold leaf application and hands-on decorative piece-making.</p><ul><li><strong>Workshop venues:</strong> Nanjing Gold Leaf Museum; selected heritage workshops</li><li><strong>Historical impact:</strong> Over 2.47 million sheets used in the Forbidden City restoration; supplies gilding for heritage sites including the Forbidden City and the Potala Palace</li></ul><p><strong>Why visit:</strong> This craft, born in Ming-era imperial workshops, once left foreign journalists speechless — during the 2018 "Foreigners Learn Intangible Heritage" event, international media watched live as one gram of gold was beaten into half a square metre of shimmering leaf. Pressing a layer of genuine gold leaf — thin as a cicada''s wing — onto an object is an experience that combines luxury and artisan mastery in a way nothing else quite does.</p><h2>Part Two: Local Performing Arts</h2><h3>7. Nanjing Baju — The Ancient Ballad Art Unique to Jinling</h3><p>Nanjing Baju is a national-level intangible heritage art and the only folk ballad form native to Jinling. It is sung in the Nanjing dialect, accompanied by the percussive click of plates and castanets, with a melodic style that originated on the floors of Cloud Brocade weaving mills. Its leading practitioner, Huang Lingling, holds national representative-inheritor status. Performances are based at the old teahouse of the Nanjing Folk Museum (Gan Xi Former Residence). The experience includes watching a Baju performance, a tea ceremony session, learning to sing an unaccompanied verse, and trying out Baju percussion instruments.</p><ul><li><strong>Performance venue:</strong> Old teahouse, Nanjing Folk Museum (Gan Xi Former Residence)</li><li><strong>Foreign visitor events:</strong> September 2025 "Baju Speaks of Mid-Autumn" — co-organised by the Nanjing Municipal Bureau of Science and Technology and the Nanjing Museum Administration, with three programme segments: tea ceremony, Baju performance, and hands-on crafts (osmanthus sachets and woodblock rubbing)</li></ul><p><strong>Why visit:</strong> Nanjing Baju has been called "the golden song of Jinling, born on the weaving floor," with origins traced to the breaks that Ming-dynasty Cloud Brocade workers took between shifts. It is the one sound that belongs solely to Nanjing — sung in dialect, with topical verses that change with the times. The September 2025 "Baju Speaks of Mid-Autumn" foreign visitor event has already proven the concept: international guests joined master practitioner Huang Lingling in learning to sing a verse of "Nanjing Street Food," experiencing the rhythms of the Nanjing dialect through the act of singing — cultural exchange that needs no common language.</p><h3>8. "Impression of Zhonghua Gate" — Immersive Light and Shadow Night Show</h3><p>"Impression of Zhonghua Gate" is a large-scale live-action light and shadow performance staged within the barbican of Zhonghua Gate. Combining live actors with three-dimensional projection mapping, it brings the ancient military architecture and defensive genius of the gate to life. The show runs from 17:00 to 21:30, using light, technology, and history to create a dialogue across more than 650 years.</p><ul><li><strong>Location:</strong> Zhonghua Gate Barbican Scenic Area, Qinhuai District, Nanjing</li><li><strong>Show times:</strong> 17:00–21:30</li></ul><p><strong>Why visit:</strong> The Zhonghua Gate barbican is the largest and best-preserved ancient fortification of its kind surviving in the world. No language skills are needed for this show — the three-dimensional light display tells the story directly, with a visual impact that transcends cultural background. A previous production staged during the National Day holiday already demonstrated how well this format connects with international audiences. Standing on walls that are over 600 years old, watching light and colour pour across the stone surface, communicates more than any museum label ever could.</p><h2>Part Three: Immersive Technology and Heritage Experiences</h2><h3>9. Grand Bao''en Temple Heritage Museum — Metaverse Experience</h3><p>The Grand Bao''en Temple Heritage Museum is built over the excavated remains of a Ming imperial monastery. In April 2023, it became the first cultural institution in China to launch a full "true-connection metaverse museum" experience. Visitors scan a device to create a personal digital avatar and enter the "Sacred Realm of Bao''en Metaverse," using their phones to move between the physical and virtual spaces across eight interactive stages — including "A Thousand-Year Gaze" and "The Glazed Archway." The centrepiece is the digital resurrection of the Ming-dynasty glazed pagoda, which was destroyed during the Taiping Heavenly Kingdom conflict.</p><ul><li><strong>Address:</strong> 1 Yuhua Road (south of Zhonghua Gate), Qinhuai District, Nanjing</li><li><strong>Opening hours:</strong> 8:30–19:30</li><li><strong>Global recognition:</strong> The digital preservation project for the glazed pagoda was showcased at the 2025 World Internet Conference</li></ul><p><strong>Why visit:</strong> This is China''s flagship example of technology enhancing cultural heritage. For foreign visitors, the Bao''en Temple glazed pagoda already has deep historical resonance in the West — in the 17th century, Dutch traveller Johan Nieuhof depicted it in his account of the Dutch East India Company''s embassy to China, and replicas of the "Nanjing Porcelain Tower" appeared across Europe. Encountering this structure — once counted among the Seven Wonders of the Medieval World — rebuilt in the metaverse is a strange and wonderful collision of history and the future.</p><h3>10. Nanjing Museum — VR Experience: "A View of the World: Kunyu Wanguo Quantu"</h3><p>The Nanjing Museum is one of China''s three great national museums, with a collection of more than 430,000 artefacts. Its crown jewel is the Kunyu Wanguo Quantu — a world map completed in 1608 through the collaboration of Italian missionary Matteo Ricci and Ming-dynasty scholar Li Zhizao, and itself a testament to the history of Sino-Western cultural exchange. From 10 July 2025, the museum launched a VR large-space immersive exhibition of the same name, in which visitors wear headsets to step inside a 720-degree panoramic recreation of a world as it appeared 400 years ago.</p><ul><li><strong>Address:</strong> 321 Zhongshan East Road, Xuanwu District, Nanjing</li><li><strong>Opening hours:</strong> Tuesday to Sunday, 9:00–17:00 (closed Monday); advance booking required via the official website or mini-programme</li><li><strong>Exhibition opening:</strong> 10 July 2025</li></ul><p><strong>Why visit:</strong> The map itself is one of the great achievements of East-West cultural exchange — the product of a remarkable partnership between Matteo Ricci and Li Zhizao. For a foreign visitor, stepping inside a 400-year-old world map in VR and experiencing the entire globe as Ming-dynasty Chinese scholars saw it carries a double cultural meaning: you are both admiring a Chinese artefact and inhabiting a moment in the history of civilisational exchange.</p><h2>Part Four: Urban Space and Architecture</h2><h3>11. Nanjing Ming City Wall — Walking and Cycling</h3><p>The Nanjing Ming City Wall stretches for more than 25 kilometres, making it the largest and best-preserved ancient city wall surviving anywhere in the world. Construction began in 1366 under Emperor Zhu Yuanzhang and took 28 years to complete. Recommended sections: Zhonghua Gate to Wuding Gate to East Water Gate (about 3 kilometres, the most scenic stretch); or Xuanwu Gate to Jiefang Gate to Taiping Gate (with views of Xuanwu Lake and Purple Mountain). Both walking and cycling are options — bicycle hire is available near Zhonghua Gate. English-language cycling tours of the wall are offered through Cycle Tours Global and similar platforms.</p><ul><li><strong>Built:</strong> Begun in 1366 under the Ming Hongwu Emperor, completed over 28 years</li><li><strong>Museum:</strong> Nanjing City Wall Museum, located immediately adjacent to Zhonghua Gate, with a design inspired by the wall''s ramp structures</li><li><strong>Evening option:</strong> "Impression of Zhonghua Gate" light and shadow show at the barbican</li></ul><p><strong>Why visit:</strong> European medieval castles are mostly isolated fortresses. The Nanjing Ming City Wall is something fundamentally different — a complete defensive system that genuinely encircled an entire city, and a scale that can only be grasped by walking it. English-language blogs including Mandarin Vibes and Cycle Tours Global have produced dedicated cycling guides, reflecting strong international demand. Standing on the wall and looking out over the Qinhuai River toward Purple Mountain is the best way to understand Nanjing''s famous character as a city framed by mountains and water.</p><h3>12. Niushou Mountain — Buddha Summit Palace Buddhist Cultural Experience</h3><p>Niushou Mountain is one of the Four Great Scenic Sites of Jinling. The Buddha Summit Palace is a landmark of international Buddhist culture, enshrining a sacred relic believed to be part of Shakyamuni Buddha''s cranial bone. The building descends into a deep excavation, with three floors above ground and six below, encompassing the Chan Realm Grand Hall, the Sacred Relic Hall, and the Relic Treasury. The soaring dome and lotus-shaped forms make for a visually stunning fusion of contemporary architecture and a Buddhist tradition more than a thousand years old. The wider site includes the Buddha Summit Temple and the Buddha Summit Pagoda.</p><ul><li><strong>Address:</strong> 18 Ningdan Avenue, Jiangning District, Nanjing</li><li><strong>Opening hours:</strong> 8:30–17:30; Buddha Summit Palace opens 9:00–17:30 in spring and summer, 9:00–17:00 in autumn and winter</li><li><strong>Best seasons:</strong> Spring and autumn</li></ul><p><strong>Why visit:</strong> The Buddha Summit Palace is a peak expression of contemporary architecture in dialogue with an ancient Buddhist tradition. Its sunken design is visually arresting before you even step inside. For foreign visitors with an interest in religion, architecture, or cultural history, this is an exceptional window onto the Chinese Buddhist tradition of relic veneration and the extraordinary ambition of modern Chinese architectural design.</p><h2>Part Five: Attire and Culinary Experiences</h2><h3>13. Hanfu Experience + Photography in Laomendong and the Confucius Temple Area</h3><p>Laomendong is a Ming and Qing dynasty historic district east of Zhonghua Gate, with grey-brick walls, traditional roof tiles, and stone-paved lanes — the heart of Nanjing''s Hanfu experience scene. Dozens of shops in the area offer full-service packages: costume hire, hair and make-up styling, and accompanied photography. Visitors in Hanfu can pose in the lanes of Laomendong, on the Ming City Wall, at Zhan Garden, and along the Qinhuai riverfront. Costume hire runs approximately 80 to 200 yuan per day; hair and styling is an additional 100 to 300 yuan.</p><ul><li><strong>Recommended photography spots:</strong> Laomendong (grey-brick lanes), Zhan Garden (Jinling''s foremost classical garden), Chaotian Palace (red walls and glazed tile roofs), the Qinhuai riverfront at the Confucius Temple</li><li><strong>Shops:</strong> Concentrated around Laomendong and within the Confucius Temple scenic area</li></ul><p><strong>Why visit:</strong> Dressing in traditional Hanfu has become one of the most popular activities for foreign visitors to China over the past two years, with enormous exposure on TikTok and Instagram. Nanjing offers a richer backdrop of Ming, Qing, and Republican-era settings than most cities — posing in a 600-year-old section of city wall or a stone-flagged alley while wearing Hanfu produces striking photographs. For foreign visitors, this is more than wearing a costume — it is an immersive way of entering Chinese classical aesthetics in person.</p><h3>14. Nanjing Deep-Dive Food Experience</h3><p>Nanjing is known as the "Duck Capital," and duck is the cornerstone of its culinary identity. The Confucius Temple area is home to the "Eight Qinhuai Delicacies": the sesame-oil plain tofu threads and duck-fat flaky pastry of Qifang Pavilion, the osmanthus-filled small rice dumplings of Lianhu Pastry Shop, the beef pot stickers of Jiangyouji, and five other classic street foods. The Michelin Guide published a dedicated Nanjing food feature in 2025, and English-language dining guides are available. Recommended heritage restaurants: Qifang Pavilion (halal dishes), Lianhu Pastry Shop (sweets), Han Fuxing (salted duck), and Jiangyouji (pot stickers).</p><ul><li><strong>Must-try dishes:</strong> Salted duck (Nanjing''s signature), duck blood and vermicelli soup, beef pot stickers, sweet taro shoots in osmanthus syrup, xiaolongbao, pork-skin noodle soup</li><li><strong>Food districts:</strong> Confucius Temple food street, Laomendong, Shizi Bridge, Kexiang Lane</li><li><strong>International recognition:</strong> Michelin Guide published a Nanjing food feature, "A Taste of Nanjing" (April 2025)</li></ul><p><strong>Why visit:</strong> Nanjing''s "Duck Capital" identity — a culture in which no feast is complete without duck — is unique in the world. The Michelin Guide''s 2025 Nanjing feature signals that the city has firmly entered the global culinary tourism conversation. Foreign visitors can work through all eight Qinhuai Delicacies in a single sitting, or join an English-language food tour to hear the stories behind the dishes — including why Nanjing''s obsession with duck is linked to the Ming dynasty''s imperial relocation.</p><h3>15. Yuhua Tea Tasting Experience</h3><p>Yuhua Tea is a Nanjing municipal intangible heritage art and one of China''s Ten Famous Teas, grown on the slopes of Yuhua Terrace and the area around Sun Yat-sen Mausoleum. The tea is distinctive for its needle-shaped leaves and deep emerald colour — a rare needle-form green tea. The name "Yuhua Tea" carries special historical weight, chosen to honour the martyrs of the Yuhua Terrace revolutionary memorial site. Tasting sessions are available at the Yuhua Tea area within the Qinhuai Intangible Heritage Hall, at the Sun Yat-sen Mausoleum Tea Factory, and at teahouses in Laomendong. The tea pairs perfectly with a Nanjing Baju performance at the old teahouse of Gan Xi Former Residence — a combined "Baju and Yuhua Tea" afternoon.</p><ul><li><strong>Tasting venues:</strong> Yuhua Tea experience area, Qinhuai Intangible Heritage Hall; Sun Yat-sen Mausoleum Tea Factory; teahouses in Laomendong</li><li><strong>Paired experience:</strong> Combined "watch Baju, taste Yuhua Tea" programme at the old teahouse of Gan Xi Former Residence</li></ul><p><strong>Why visit:</strong> Chinese tea culture has a natural appeal to Western visitors, and Yuhua Tea''s distinctive needle-shaped appearance — plus the historical resonance of its name — gives a tea tasting here an extra layer of depth. Sitting in the old teahouse of Gan Xi Former Residence, sipping Yuhua Tea while listening to Nanjing Baju, is a feast for the senses of sight, hearing, and taste all at once — quintessential Jinling in a single afternoon.</p><h2>Quick Reference</h2><h2>Hands-on Intangible Heritage Crafts</h2><ul><li>Jinling Sutra-Engraving · Woodblock Printing — Language barrier: Low | Hands-on: ⭐⭐⭐ | Year-round | Booking required</li><li>Qinhuai Intangible Heritage Hall · One-Stop — Language barrier: Low | Hands-on: ⭐⭐⭐ | Year-round | No booking needed</li><li>Nanjing Paper Cutting — Language barrier: Very low | Hands-on: ⭐⭐⭐ | Year-round | No booking needed</li><li>Qinhuai Silk Lantern Making — Language barrier: Low | Hands-on: ⭐⭐⭐ | Year-round | No booking needed</li><li>Cloud Brocade Museum Weaving Experience — Language barrier: Low | Hands-on: ⭐⭐ | Year-round | No booking needed</li><li>Jinling Gold Leaf Application — Language barrier: Very low | Hands-on: ⭐⭐⭐ | Year-round | No booking needed</li></ul><h2>Local Performing Arts</h2><ul><li>Nanjing Baju — Language barrier: Moderate | Hands-on: ⭐⭐ | Year-round | Booking required</li><li>"Impression of Zhonghua Gate" Light and Shadow Night Show — Language barrier: Very low | Hands-on: ⭐ | Year-round | Booking advised</li></ul><h2>Immersive Technology and Heritage Experiences</h2><ul><li>Grand Bao''en Temple Metaverse — Language barrier: Very low | Hands-on: ⭐⭐⭐ | Year-round | Online ticket purchase advised</li><li>Nanjing Museum VR Kunyu Wanguo Quantu — Language barrier: Very low | Hands-on: ⭐⭐⭐ | During exhibition run | Booking required</li></ul><h2>Urban Space and Architecture</h2><ul><li>Ming City Wall Walk / Cycle — Language barrier: Very low | Hands-on: ⭐⭐ | Best in spring and autumn | No booking needed</li><li>Niushou Mountain Buddha Summit Palace — Language barrier: Low | Hands-on: ⭐ | Best in spring and autumn | Online ticket purchase advised</li></ul><h2>Attire and Culinary Experiences</h2><ul><li>Hanfu + Laomendong Photography — Language barrier: Very low | Hands-on: ⭐⭐⭐ | Year-round (spring and autumn best) | No booking needed</li><li>Nanjing Deep-Dive Food Experience — Language barrier: Low | Hands-on: ⭐⭐ | Year-round | No booking needed</li><li>Yuhua Tea Tasting — Language barrier: Low | Hands-on: ⭐⭐ | Year-round | No booking needed</li></ul><h2>Important Notes</h2><p>1. <strong>Booking is essential</strong> for the Jinling Sutra-Engraving Workshop (80 visitors per day maximum), the Nanjing Museum (including the VR exhibition), and the Grand Bao''en Temple metaverse. Walk-ins are not accepted at these venues; all advance reservations must go through the official WeChat account or ticketing platform. 2. <strong>Practitioner schedules:</strong> For Baju, paper cutting, lantern-making, and similar experiences that involve teaching by a specific heritage practitioner, confirm availability in advance. The front desk at the Qinhuai Intangible Heritage Hall can advise. 3. <strong>Language support:</strong> The Qinhuai Intangible Heritage Hall provides Chinese and English guided tours. The Baju and tea ceremony events for foreign visitors at Gan Xi Former Residence are organised by official bodies including the Nanjing Municipal Bureau of Science and Technology; they are held irregularly. Follow the "Nanjing Folk Museum" WeChat account for updates. 4. <strong>Seasonal notes:</strong> The Qinhuai Lantern Festival runs only during the Spring Festival period (approximately mid-January to mid-February). Avoid the city wall in the heat of July and August. Niushou Mountain is at its best in spring and autumn. 5. <strong>Prices:</strong> All prices listed are reference figures gathered from public sources. Please verify current pricing directly with each venue or official channel.</p>',
  '[]'::jsonb,
  2,
  TRUE
) ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
