INSERT INTO city_guides (
  id, city_id, title_en, title_zh, subtitle, icon, badge,
  cover_images, body, meta_items, display_order, is_published
) VALUES (
  'shanghai_museum_furniture',
  'shanghai',
  'Chapter Five: The Soul of Wood — Ming and Qing Furniture Gallery, Shanghai Museum',
  '第五章：木韵天成——上海博物馆明清家具馆',
  'Know-how: Huanghuali (Dalbergia odorifera) grows mainly in Hainan province, growing slowly and requiring a hundred years to reach usable size.',
  '🏛',
  'Museum',
  ARRAY[]::TEXT[],
  '<h2>Introduction: Time Frozen, Elegance in Motion</h2><p>Step into the Ming and Qing Furniture Gallery on the fourth floor of the Shanghai Museum, and time seems to pause.</p><p>In this 700-square-meter gallery, more than a hundred masterworks of Ming and Qing furniture stand in quiet dignity — not cold display pieces, but living history. Every grain of wood records the aesthetic ideals of Ming literati; every mortise-and-tenon joint crystallizes the ingenuity of Qing craftsmen. This is a sanctuary of classical Chinese furniture, and one of the world''s finest windows onto China''s material culture.</p><p>The Shanghai Museum''s Ming and Qing Furniture Gallery was established in 1996, the first dedicated Ming and Qing furniture gallery in China. Its collection draws on two principal sources: the Ming furniture comes largely from the private collections of scholars Wang Shixiang and Chen Mengjia, while the Qing furniture belongs to the museum''s original holdings. This unusual collecting history makes it possible to trace, within a single space, the full arc of Chinese classical furniture from the Ming style to the Qing.</p><h2>Section One: The Peak of Chinese Furniture — The Artistry of Ming and Qing</h2><h3>One: Ming-Style Furniture — The Literati Aesthetic of Radical Simplicity</h3><h2>What is Ming-style furniture?</h2><p>Ming-style furniture refers to furniture produced from the Ming dynasty through the early Qing (roughly the 15th to 17th centuries), made primarily from precious hardwoods such as huanghuali, zitan, hongmu, tieli, and qizi. It is not merely the furniture of a historical period — it represents the highest artistic achievement in the entire history of Chinese classical furniture.</p><h2>Five defining artistic qualities of Ming-style furniture:</h2><p>#### 1. Exceptional Material — Nature''s Gift</p><p>What first captivates in Ming furniture is the material itself. Huanghuali wood is warm and lustrous, its grain flowing like drifting clouds; zitan is deep and restrained, its luster quiet and profound. These woods spent hundreds of years forming their distinctive patterns and tones in nature, and the craftsmen who worked them chose to let the material speak for itself rather than overlay it with excessive decoration.</p><p>#### 2. Superb Construction — The Poetry of Mortise-and-Tenon</p><p>Ming-style furniture uses not a single nail; all joints are mortise-and-tenon. This technique, borrowed from traditional Chinese architecture, makes furniture both durable and embodies the philosophy of harmony between humanity and nature. Dovetail joints, clamp-head joints, inserted-shoulder joints, rice-dumpling corner joints — these ingenious structures are simultaneously engineering marvels and visual feasts.</p><p><strong>A case in point:</strong> The Shanghai Museum''s huanghuali small flat-top table with clamp-head joints (formerly in the Chen Mengjia collection) — its clamp-head joint serves both as structural support and decorative element, demonstrating the Ming ideal that "structure is decoration."</p><p>#### 3. Refined Form — The Spatial Art of Flowing Line</p><p>The aesthetic of Ming furniture can be summed up in two words: open and spare. It does not pile on ornament in the manner of Baroque furniture; instead, it uses the most economical line to describe the most elegant contour. The curved back of a round-back armchair cradles the human spine; the headrail of an official''s hat chair spreads like the wings of an ancient official''s cap; the legs of a flat-top desk taper inward with a stability that is also graceful.</p><p>This sense of formal beauty is deeply influenced by the Neo-Confucian idea of "investigating things to extend knowledge" — through rigorous proportion, achieving visual harmony and balance.</p><p>#### 4. Deep Resonance — The Literati Spirit Made Material</p><p>Ming-style furniture is the tangible result of literati aesthetics. Ming scholars participated directly in furniture design, infusing it with the aesthetic ideals of poetry, calligraphy, painting, and seal carving, so that Ming furniture carries not only functional but spiritual meaning. A huanghuali bookshelf is not merely storage for books; it is a symbol of the owner''s cultural ideal of passing learning down through generations.</p><p>#### 5. Restrained Decoration — The Art of Knowing When to Stop</p><p>The decoration of Ming furniture follows a principle of "better simple than complex." When carving does appear, it is typically confined to secondary surfaces — the edge beads, aprons, and spandrels — and takes the form of scrolling foliage, cloud patterns, or geometric meander motifs. This disciplined, precise decoration throws into relief the overall refinement of the piece rather than competing with it.</p><h3>Two: Qing-Style Furniture — The Palace Grandeur of a Different World</h3><h2>The transition from Ming to Qing</h2><p>After the reign of Emperor Kangxi of the Qing dynasty, as national power grew and aesthetic tastes shifted, furniture moved gradually from the refined simplicity of the Ming style toward the elaborate splendor of the Qing style. This change reflects both the spirit of the era and a broadening of the contexts in which furniture was used.</p><h2>Three defining qualities of Qing-style furniture:</h2><p>#### 1. Rich Carving — The Ultimate Display of Craft</p><p>Qing-style furniture makes extensive use of relief carving, openwork carving, and fully three-dimensional carving. Decorative motifs include dragons and phoenixes, auspicious animals, flowers, landscapes, and narrative scenes — transforming furniture into sculpture. The Shanghai Museum''s mid-Qing zitan throne, covered entirely with cloud patterns, bats, twin dragons playing with a pearl, and crashing waves, showcases the opulent grandeur of Qing imperial furniture.</p><p>#### 2. Inlaid Luxury — Rich Combinations of Material</p><p>Qing furniture frequently incorporates inlays of ivory, jade, mother-of-pearl, and enamel, producing vivid color contrasts and textural richness. This technique of "one hundred treasures inlay" exemplifies the Qing goal of achieving a synthesis of all craft traditions.</p><p>#### 3. Functional Innovation — New Forms for New Lives</p><p>Qing furniture expanded into specialized forms unknown in the Ming period, including multi-tiered display cabinets, zither tables, chess tables, and reclining chairs. These new categories reflect the diversification and refinement of Qing-dynasty daily life.</p><h2>Section Two: Wang Shixiang — The Man Who Gave Chinese Classical Furniture Its Scholarly Voice</h2><h3>One: A Life of Play That Became Scholarship</h3><p><strong>Wang Shixiang (1914–2009)</strong>, courtesy name Changan, born in Beijing of a Fujian family, led a life that is itself the finest illustration of the word "legendary."</p><p>As a young man, Wang was known in Beijing as a committed "player" — flying hawks, fighting crickets, keeping pigeons, growing gourds. These pursuits, dismissed by most as idle amusements, he transformed into fields of genuine knowledge. He later recalled: "From childhood to adulthood, from primary school to university, I was always more interested in play than study."</p><p>Yet it was precisely this spirit of play that allowed him to find an original path through the study of traditional Chinese culture. He researched Ming furniture, lacquerware, bamboo carving, and gourd vessels — and for each new pursuit, he produced a pioneering scholarly work.</p><h2>The scholarly turn: from play to research</h2><p>In the 1950s, Wang Shixiang began a systematic study of Ming furniture. During this period of enormous social upheaval in China, large quantities of Ming and Qing furniture were being destroyed as "feudal relics" or lost abroad. Pained by what he witnessed, Wang resolved to "write the history of Ming furniture while there was still time."</p><p>He cycled through Beijing''s streets and lanes, visiting antique dealers and second-hand markets, even turning up at demolition sites to salvage furniture. He not only collected pieces but also gathered the oral histories of craftsmen, recording their methods and techniques. This fieldwork approach gave his scholarship both theoretical depth and practical grounding.</p><h3>Two: "A Study of Ming Furniture" — A Landmark Scholarly Achievement</h3><p>In 1985, Wang Shixiang''s "Connoisseurship of Ming Furniture" was published in Hong Kong. The book filled a gap in the Chinese study of Ming furniture and was hailed by scholars as the third great milestone in Chinese cultural studies, after Guo Moruo''s research on bronzes and Shen Congwen''s history of costume.</p><p>In 1995, he published "A Study of Ming Furniture" — the culmination of more than forty years of research and the recognized founding text of Chinese classical furniture scholarship.</p><h2>Three major contributions of "A Study of Ming Furniture":</h2><p>1. <strong>Establishing a research framework for Ming furniture</strong> — Wang classified Ming furniture into five broad categories (chairs and stools, tables and desks, beds and couches, cabinets and shelves, and miscellaneous), developing a detailed research structure for each.</p><p>2. <strong>A systematic and objective account of Ming furniture''s artistic achievement</strong> — Drawing on history, aesthetics, craft, and culture, he illuminated the full value of Ming furniture, transforming "Ming-style furniture" from a vague concept into a rigorous discipline.</p><p>3. <strong>Providing a theoretical foundation for conservation and transmission</strong> — His research had not only academic but practical value, offering authoritative guidance for furniture restoration, reproduction, and collecting.</p><h3>Three: Wang Shixiang and the Shanghai Museum</h3><p>Wang Shixiang was not only a scholar of Ming furniture but an important collector. His Ming and Qing furniture holdings were comprehensive and of exceptional quality. In his later years, he donated his prized collection to the Shanghai Museum, and it became the core of the Ming and Qing Furniture Gallery.</p><h2>Wang Shixiang''s cultural conviction:</h2><p>This spirit of giving scholarly work to the public is a modern expression of the traditional Chinese intellectual ideal of "establishing meaning for heaven and earth, and securing life for the people."</p><h2>Section Three: A Forgotten Pioneer — Chen Mengjia and the Early Collecting of Ming and Qing Furniture</h2><h3>One: Chen Mengjia — A Polymath Undervalued by History</h3><p><strong>Chen Mengjia (1911–1966)</strong>, born in Nanjing of a Zhejiang family, was a poet, ancient script scholar, archaeologist, and collector — what we would today call a multi-disciplinary talent.</p><h2>Literary beginnings: poet of the Crescent Moon School</h2><p>Chen Mengjia made his name early as a poet, a leading figure of the Crescent Moon School. His verse was fresh and lyrical; he was called "the Shelley of China." In 1929, at the age of eighteen, he published his first collection, "Meng Jia''s Poems," to considerable acclaim.</p><h2>Scholarly transformation: from poet to academic</h2><p>In the 1930s, Chen Mengjia shifted to academic research, teaching at Yenching University, Tsinghua University, and the Southwest Associated University. His scholarly fields included ancient Chinese script, archaeology, and ancient religious history, with particular distinction in oracle-bone script and bronze vessel research.</p><h2>Key scholarly contributions:</h2><ul><li>Compiled the "Comprehensive Account of Oracle-Bone Divination Inscriptions from Yinxu," systematically organizing the oracle-bone inscriptions from the Shang dynasty site</li><li>Compiled "Chinese Bronze Vessels in American Collections," pioneering the systematic survey of Chinese cultural heritage held overseas</li><li>Proposed numerous original ideas on the dating, classification, and interpretation of bronze inscriptions</li></ul><h3>Two: Chen Mengjia and the Collecting of Ming and Qing Furniture</h3><p>In the 1940s, during a visiting scholarship in the United States, Chen Mengjia encountered large quantities of classical Chinese furniture that had made its way abroad. He recognized acutely that this furniture represented a vital dimension of Chinese material culture in urgent need of systematic collection and study.</p><p>On returning to China, he began buying Ming furniture on a large scale. What set his collecting apart:</p><p>#### 1. Systematic collecting</p><p>Chen Mengjia did not buy piecemeal — he assembled complete sets, room by room: everything from large banquet tables and painting desks down to jewelry boxes and brush pots, a full ensemble. This systematic approach was remarkably advanced for the time.</p><p>Wang Shixiang later recalled:</p><p>#### 2. An eye of exceptional discernment</p><p>Every piece Chen collected was of the highest quality. He valued not only material and workmanship but artistic merit and cultural depth. The huanghuali pieces he assembled were celebrated for their elegant form and perfect proportion; many later became treasures of the Shanghai Museum.</p><p>#### 3. A scholar''s approach to collecting</p><p>As a scholar, Chen Mengjia was not merely "buying furniture" — he was "studying furniture." He recorded the provenance, period, and distinctive craft features of each piece, leaving invaluable primary source material for later researchers.</p><h3>Three: The Friendship Between Chen Mengjia and Wang Shixiang</h3><p>Chen Mengjia and Wang Shixiang were the twin stars of Ming furniture collecting. The two became close friends through their shared passion, regularly browsing markets together, examining pieces, and discussing their research.</p><h2>An anecdote:</h2><p>In the preface to "Connoisseurship of Ming Furniture," Wang Shixiang recalled a moment when he spotted a piece he wanted but could not afford. He went to Chen Mengjia, who said: "Buy it — I''ll lend you the money." When Wang eventually gathered enough to repay him, Chen replied: "Forget it. I like that piece too. Let it stay with you a while longer, and we can swap when I find something even better."</p><p>This kind of refined, generous friendship is a vivid embodiment of the Chinese tradition of "meeting in friendship through art and advancing in virtue through friendship."</p><p>After Chen Mengjia''s death, his furniture collection passed through several hands. Eventually, through the efforts of Chen Mengjia''s wife Zhao Luorui''s brother Zhao Jingxin, select pieces from the collection were acquired by the Shanghai Museum, where they joined Wang Shixiang''s later donation to form the foundation of the Ming and Qing Furniture Gallery.</p><h2>Historical assessment:</h2><p>Chen Mengjia was a pioneer of classical Chinese furniture collecting. His contribution lay not only in the objects he gathered but in the scholarly vision he imparted to those who followed. Wang Shixiang said with deep feeling:</p><h2>Section Four: Key Works in the Shanghai Museum''s Ming and Qing Furniture Gallery</h2><h3>One: Ming Dynasty Masterworks (primarily huanghuali and zitan)</h3><p>#### 1. Huanghuali small flat-top table with clamp-head joint and drawer (formerly in the Chen Mengjia collection)</p><ul><li><strong>Dimensions:</strong> 112 cm long, 54 cm wide, 83 cm tall</li><li><strong>Character:</strong> A paradigmatic example of Ming furniture. The clamp-head joint is clean and powerful; the apron line flows with natural ease. A single drawer below the tabletop adds practical function. The proportions are harmonious throughout, the lines upright and lively — a perfect embodiment of the Ming aesthetic of "pare away the superfluous."</li><li><strong>Cultural significance:</strong> Originally in the Chen Mengjia collection, this table was featured as a key illustration in Wang Shixiang''s "Connoisseurship of Ming Furniture" and holds high scholarly and artistic value.</li></ul><p>#### 2. Huanghuali four-protruding-end official''s hat armchair (formerly in the Wang Shixiang collection)</p><ul><li><strong>Dimensions:</strong> Seat 58 cm long, 46 cm wide; overall height 117 cm</li><li><strong>Character:</strong> The chair takes its name from the way the tops of the back stiles and the front armrest ends extend outward, resembling an ancient official''s hat. The headrail sweeps in a graceful curve; the back splat bends in an S-curve that conforms naturally to the spine; the chair is entirely without carving, relying entirely on proportion and line.</li><li><strong>Cultural significance:</strong> The official''s hat armchair is the most representative chair form in Ming furniture, expressing the Ming literati ideal of "quiet refinement and restrained elegance."</li></ul><p>#### 3. Zitan painting desk with inserted-shoulder joint (formerly in the Wang Shixiang collection)</p><ul><li><strong>Dimensions:</strong> 192 cm long, 91 cm wide, 82 cm tall</li><li><strong>Character:</strong> Fashioned in zitan with generous proportions and commanding presence. The inserted-shoulder joint distributes structural forces between leg, shoulder, and apron in an especially rational way. The apron edges and leg faces carry full, rounded bead profiles; the feet are lightly carved. The overall surface detailing is spare but rhythmically rich.</li><li><strong>Cultural significance:</strong> Zitan was already extremely rare in the Ming period; large-scale zitan furniture was rarer still. Since the late Qing dynasty this desk has been revered as the "first zitan painting desk" — a major work in the canon of Ming furniture.</li></ul><h3>Two: Qing Dynasty Masterworks (primarily zitan and hongmu)</h3><p>#### 1. Zitan throne with carved cloud patterns</p><ul><li><strong>Dimensions:</strong> Seat 122 cm long, 85 cm wide; overall height 125 cm</li><li><strong>Character:</strong> The throne is the highest-ranking seat in the classical Chinese hierarchy, reserved for imperial use. This example is made of fine zitan and carved over every surface. The back takes the form of a three-panel screen with edges in flowing scrolling cloud shapes. The central back panel is carved with a dragon descending from heaven, below which two dragons play with a pearl, below which crashing waves meet a rocky shore — signifying "the true dragon Son of Heaven commanding all under heaven." Armrests and seat rail are carved throughout with clouds, bats, and other auspicious imagery.</li><li><strong>Cultural significance:</strong> Once used in the Qing imperial court, this throne is broad and imposing, its carving of the finest quality — a masterwork of Qing imperial furniture displaying the Qing craft ideal of precision and ingenuity.</li></ul><p>#### 2. Large zitan cabinet with carved dragon patterns</p><ul><li><strong>Dimensions:</strong> 210 cm wide, 65 cm deep, 280 cm tall</li><li><strong>Character:</strong> A monumental cabinet of considerable scale, made entirely of zitan. The cabinet doors bear high-relief cloud-and-dragon carving; the dragon is vigorous, the clouds fluid. The copper hinges and face plates are finely engraved, creating a sumptuous contrast with the deep tonality of the zitan.</li><li><strong>Cultural significance:</strong> The large cabinet was an important Qing furniture type, used in palaces and noble residences. This example, with its extravagant material and superb workmanship, is a material witness to the glory of the Qing dynasty at its height.</li></ul><p>#### 3. Hongmu wall panel inlaid with mother-of-pearl landscape</p><ul><li><strong>Dimensions:</strong> 150 cm long, 80 cm wide</li><li><strong>Character:</strong> A decorative panel type fashionable in the Qing period. The frame is hongmu; the central field is inlaid with mother-of-pearl depicting mountains, pavilions, and gardens. The iridescent quality of the shell inlay plays against the dignified warmth of the hongmu, creating a richly layered scene of considerable depth.</li><li><strong>Cultural significance:</strong> The technique of mother-of-pearl inlay reached its peak in the Qing period; this panel is a perfect illustration of the Qing craft ideal of "fine material, fine workmanship."</li></ul><h2>Section Five: The Cultural Meaning of Ming and Qing Furniture and Its Relevance Today</h2><h3>One: Ming and Qing Furniture — The Summit of Chinese Material Culture</h3><p>Ming and Qing furniture is not only the high point of Chinese furniture history but a significant expression of Chinese material culture as a whole. It embodies several core principles of traditional Chinese thought:</p><p>#### 1. The philosophy of harmony between humanity and nature</p><p>The materials, structure, and form of Ming and Qing furniture all reflect a deep respect for and attunement to nature. The natural grain of huanghuali and zitan is preserved and displayed rather than obscured; mortise-and-tenon joinery follows the natural behavior of wood; the forms of furniture tend toward rounded, yielding curves. All of this is the expression, in material terms, of the philosophy of harmony between humanity and the natural world.</p><p>#### 2. The aesthetic ideal of "conveying meaning through form"</p><p>Ming furniture in particular is a classic expression of literati aesthetics in material form. Through economy of shape, excellence of craft, and elevated refinement of spirit, it communicates the scholar''s aspiration toward clarity of purpose and tranquility of mind. A Ming-style round-back armchair is not merely a seat — it is a statement about the owner''s cultural sensibility.</p><p>#### 3. The craftsman''s spirit of "investigating things to extend knowledge"</p><p>The making of Ming and Qing furniture embodies the traditional Chinese craftsman''s ideal: through deep study of the properties of materials, the principles of structure, and the laws of form, to achieve mastery. A classic piece of Ming furniture, from the selection of wood to the final finishing, might take years or even decades to complete. This patient, unhurried ethos is the heart of the traditional Chinese craft spirit.</p><h3>Two: The Contemporary Relevance of Ming and Qing Furniture</h3><p>In the 21st century, Ming and Qing furniture continues to offer important lessons:</p><p>#### 1. Inspiration for modern design</p><p>The minimalist aesthetic of Ming furniture converges with the 20th-century modern design movement''s principle that "form follows function." Danish designer Hans Wegner''s "China Chair" series was directly inspired by the Ming round-back armchair. Today, a growing number of contemporary designers draw from Ming and Qing furniture to create new forms that carry traditional resonance while meeting modern life''s demands.</p><p>#### 2. A reflection on how we live</p><p>The way of life embodied by Ming and Qing furniture — unhurried, quality-focused, taste-driven — offers a counterweight to the "fast-consumption culture" of contemporary society. In an age of material abundance, is there still a case for the philosophy of "less but better"? Ming and Qing furniture offers its own quiet answer.</p><p>#### 3. A reminder about cultural heritage</p><p>The collecting stories of Wang Shixiang and Chen Mengjia show us the urgency of cultural heritage protection. Large quantities of Ming and Qing furniture remain scattered or have been lost abroad. How we protect these precious legacies is a question our generation must confront.</p><h2>Section Six: How to Look at Ming and Qing Furniture</h2><h3>One: Three Modes of Appreciation</h3><p>#### 1. Step back and read the overall form</p><p>Stand two to three metres in front of a piece and observe its form and proportions as a whole. Does the silhouette have beauty? Does the line flow? Is the overall character powerful or refined?</p><p>#### 2. Move close and examine the detail</p><p>Come in close to study the grain and color of the wood, the ingenuity of the joinery, the refinement of any carving. You may gently feel the surface of the furniture, sensing the warmth of the wood and the quality of the craft.</p><p>#### 3. Stand still and absorb the spirit</p><p>Finally, quiet your mind and try to sense the cultural meaning and character the piece conveys. A classic Ming or Qing piece is like a silent sage, speaking to you about the story of an era.</p><h3>Two: Practical Tips for the Shanghai Museum Ming and Qing Furniture Gallery</h3><p>1. <strong>Recommended time:</strong> Allow one to one and a half hours to savor each piece. 2. <strong>Suggested sequence:</strong> Begin with the Ming furniture section, then the Qing section — this allows you to feel the evolution of style clearly. 3. <strong>Must-see pieces:</strong> Do not miss the huanghuali small flat-top table with clamp-head joint, the zitan painting desk, and the zitan throne carved with cloud patterns. 4. <strong>Support facilities:</strong> The gallery has detailed text panels and multimedia interactive stations to deepen your understanding of Ming and Qing furniture. 5. <strong>Museum shop:</strong> The Shanghai Museum store carries Ming and Qing furniture-themed souvenirs worth browsing.</p><h2>Conclusion: The Resonance of Wood, the Continuity of Culture</h2><p>Leaving the Shanghai Museum''s Ming and Qing Furniture Gallery, those exquisite pieces seem to linger in the mind.</p><p>They say nothing, yet they say everything. They tell us the heights that the ancient Chinese reached in creating material culture; they remind us that traditional culture is not a sealed-off legacy but a living spring that can illuminate the present; they urge us, as inheritors of that tradition, to protect these precious legacies and let their stories continue.</p><p>Wang Shixiang and Chen Mengjia gave their lives to safeguarding this precious cultural memory. As we walk through the Shanghai Museum''s Ming and Qing Furniture Gallery, taking in those beautiful pieces, let us not forget the stories behind them — and what they cost to preserve.</p><h3>Let the resonance of wood carry on, and the thread of culture never be broken — perhaps that is the deepest reason this gallery exists.</h3>',
