INSERT INTO city_guides (
  id, city_id, title_en, title_zh, subtitle, icon, badge,
  cover_images, body, meta_items, display_order, is_published
) VALUES (
  'shanghai_museum_painting',
  'shanghai',
  'Ink and Color: Shanghai Museum''s Calligraphy and Painting Galleries',
  '翰墨丹青：上海博物馆书画馆',
  'About the images: The images in this article are AI-generated visual references, produced based on historical records, stylistic characteristics, dimensions, and materials of the individual works.',
  '🏛',
  'Museum',
  ARRAY[]::TEXT[],
  '<h2>Introduction: The Soul of Chinese Civilization in Brushstrokes</h2><p>Chinese calligraphy and painting represent the most distinctive and profound artistic expression of Chinese civilization — a cultural phenomenon unlike anything else in the history of world art. Unlike Western art, Chinese "shu hua" (calligraphy-and-painting) has never been purely a visual form. It is the vessel of the literati''s spirit, the materialization of philosophical thought, and the guardian of historical memory.</p><p>Calligraphy uses the written character as its medium, transforming abstract lines into a living artistic language. From the oracle bone inscriptions of the Shang dynasty onward, through more than three thousand years of evolution, the five major script types — seal, clerical, cursive, regular, and running — came into their own, forming the world''s only tradition in which the act of writing a script developed into a fully independent art form. As the Tang dynasty critic Zhang Huaiguan wrote: "Written words take several characters to convey a meaning; in calligraphy, a single character reveals the writer''s heart." In one character, one may read a calligrapher''s temperament, learning, cultivation, and the spirit of an age.</p><p>Painting, from the painted pottery of the Neolithic age to the silk paintings of the Warring States period, through the Wei-Jin ideal of "capturing spirit through form," the golden splendor of the Sui and Tang dynasties, the ink-centered aesthetics of the Five Dynasties and Song-Yuan era, and the multiplicity of styles in the Ming and Qing dynasties — this is the world''s longest-running and most richly varied tradition of visual art. Most distinctive of all, Chinese painting fused with calligraphy, poetry, and seal carving to produce the comprehensive art form known as "the four arts in one," in which poetry, calligraphy, painting, and seal impression unite in a single work — a uniquely Chinese contribution to world civilization.</p><p>Shanghai Museum, as one of China''s foremost centers of cultural heritage, is unmatched among museums at home and abroad for the richness, systematic completeness, and sheer number of masterworks in its calligraphy and painting collection — a collection sometimes described as "half of the nation''s finest works." Shanghai Museum is currently the only museum in the world with permanent historical survey exhibitions of both calligraphy and painting. Walking into these galleries is like reading a three-dimensional history of Chinese culture with your own eyes.</p><h2>I. Overview of the Collection</h2><p>Shanghai Museum''s calligraphy and painting collection is a civilization''s inheritance spanning a thousand years.</p><p>In the 1980s, China''s Ancient Calligraphy and Painting Appraisal Panel conducted a systematic review of the museum''s ancient holdings and catalogued <strong>4,780 works</strong>. Among those nearly five thousand pieces, the museum holds <strong>close to 300 works of calligraphy and painting from the Jin, Tang, Song, and Yuan dynasties</strong> — a number and quality surpassed among mainland museums only by the Palace Museum, while in certain categories and schools the collection holds a place that cannot be replicated.</p><p>The collection was built through the devotion of several generations of collectors, connoisseurs, and cultural guardians — from the private collections of the late Qing and early Republican era, to systematic acquisitions after the founding of the People''s Republic, to generous donations by overseas Chinese. Together, these contributions gathered fragments scattered across the river of history and reassembled them into a complete picture of Chinese culture.</p><h2>Core characteristics of the collection:</h2><ul><li><strong>Complete chronological span</strong>: From Shang dynasty oracle bone inscriptions, Western Zhou bronze inscriptions, and Warring States bamboo manuscripts, to Tang dynasty facsimile copies of works by Wang Xizhi, genuine works by the Tang monk Huaisu, brushwork by the "Four Masters of Song Calligraphy," Yuan dynasty masterpieces by Zhao Mengfu, and representative works of every major school of the Ming and Qing dynasties — almost nothing is missing.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Rich variety of forms</strong>: Calligraphy encompasses oracle bones, bronze inscriptions, bamboo slips, stone rubbings, model calligraphies, letters, and colophons; painting covers figure, landscape, and bird-and-flower genres in handscrolls, hanging scrolls, albums, and fan formats.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Documented provenance, rigorous authentication</strong>: Most of the works in the collection passed through the hands of renowned collectors and connoisseurs of successive dynasties, with seals, colophons, and catalogue entries all clearly verifiable. Combined with modern technical analysis, the standard of authentication is exceptionally high.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Numerous works prohibited from export</strong>: In the State Administration of Cultural Heritage''s second list of artefacts prohibited from going abroad for exhibition, published in 2012, Shanghai Museum''s holdings include Huaisu''s *Bitter Bamboo Shoots Letter* (Tang dynasty), Wang Anshi''s *Key Points of the Shurangama Sutra* (Northern Song dynasty), and Sun Wei''s *Lofty Scholars* (Tang dynasty) — national treasures that cannot be moved abroad.</li></ul><h2>II. Pre-Qin and Han Dynasties: The Birth of Writing and the Emergence of Aesthetics</h2><h3>2.1 The Origins of Writing: From Incising to Brushwork</h3><p>The origins of Chinese calligraphy can be traced to incised symbols of the late Neolithic period. But calligraphy in the true sense began with the oracle bone inscriptions of the Shang dynasty.</p><p>Shanghai Museum holds fine examples of Shang dynasty oracle bones — characters carved on turtle plastrons and animal bones that record the divination practices of the Shang royal court and stand as the earliest surviving witnesses to Chinese writing and calligraphy. The lines of oracle bone script are firm and forceful, the characters naturally varied in arrangement. Although the tool was a bronze blade rather than a brush, these inscriptions already reflect a conscious pursuit of the beauty of line.</p><p>In the Western Zhou period, writing was mainly cast onto bronze vessels and is known as "bronze script" or "vessel inscription." The <strong>Da Ke Ding</strong> (Great Ke Tripod, late Western Zhou period) in the museum''s collection bears a 290-character inscription on its inner wall, displaying the solemn beauty of bronze inscription through its "wave-and-flick" brushwork; it was praised by Kang Youwei as "the crown of bronze inscriptions." These inscriptions feature rounded, full strokes and a stately composure, embodying the order and dignity of Western Zhou ritual culture.</p><p>![Da Ke Ding inscription | AI visual reference](images/19-大克鼎-金文.png)</p><h3>2.2 Warring States Bamboo Manuscripts: The Earliest Face of Ink Brushwork</h3><p>Shanghai Museum holds Warring States bamboo manuscripts from the Chu state — among the earliest surviving examples of brush-written text. Unlike the carved marks of oracle bones and bronze inscriptions, the characters on these bamboo slips were written with a brush dipped in ink, allowing us a glimpse of authentic brush-writing from the pre-Qin era. The characters are freely composed, the strokes lively and dynamic, with the transitional features between seal and clerical scripts clearly visible — invaluable material for the study of the evolution of Chinese script forms.</p><p>![Warring States bamboo manuscripts | AI visual reference](images/20-战国楚简.png)</p><h3>2.3 From Seal to Clerical Script: The "Clerical Transformation"</h3><p>The Qin and Han dynasties were a pivotal period in the development of Chinese writing. After the First Emperor of Qin unified the six kingdoms, he standardized writing across the empire, establishing the small seal script as the official form and ending the regional diversity of scripts of the Warring States era. But the small seal script was complex to write and poorly suited to rapid record-keeping, and so a simpler script — clerical script — gradually matured during the Qin-Han transition.</p><p>Shanghai Museum holds the <strong>Eastern Han Clerical Script Stele of Yin Zhou</strong> (in hanging scroll format) and fragments of the <strong>Xiping Stone Classics of the Book of Changes</strong>, displaying the characteristic features of Han clerical script. The strokes of Han clerical script shifted from rounded to angular, establishing the fundamental square form of the Chinese character. Cai Yong invented the "flying white" calligraphic style; Zhang Zhi was honored as "Sage of Cursive Script." Calligraphy had begun its transformation from a purely practical tool into an art form for expressing emotion and conveying beauty.</p><h2>III. Wei-Jin and Northern and Southern Dynasties: The Age of Spirit and the Awakening of Art</h2><h3>3.1 Wang Xizhi: The Legend of the Sage of Calligraphy</h3><p>The Wei-Jin and Northern-Southern Dynasties period was the first great peak of Chinese calligraphy. The pursuit of "yun" — an elusive spirit or inner charm — rather than mere technical rules was the central aesthetic ideal of calligraphy in this era.</p><p>The defining figure of this period is, beyond any doubt, <strong>Wang Xizhi</strong> (303–361), revered by later generations as the "Sage of Calligraphy." Wang Xizhi drew from the full breadth of earlier traditions to create a new language in running script and cursive script; his most celebrated work, the *Preface to the Orchid Pavilion Poems*, has been called "the finest running-script work under heaven."</p><p>The works by Wang Xizhi in Shanghai Museum''s collection, while not originals, are Tang dynasty facsimile copies of great historical importance:</p><p><strong>The *Shangyou Letter</strong>* (Tang facsimile): Also known as the *Nocturnal Abdominal Pain Letter*, this is a cursive-script work by Wang Xizhi — paper, 23.5 cm by 26 cm, 7 lines and 58 characters. The brushwork is crisp and vigorous, the posture graceful and refined, retaining echoes of earlier "chapter cursive" style. It is one of Shanghai Museum''s signature treasures. Though not Wang Xizhi''s own hand, Tang facsimile copies of such precision and fidelity were regarded by generations of connoisseurs as the closest surviving approximation to Wang Xizhi''s originals.</p><p>![Wang Xizhi''s Shangyou Letter, Tang facsimile | AI visual reference](images/03-王羲之-上虞帖.png)</p><p><strong>The *Wang Family Letters</strong>* (Tang facsimile): Also known as the *Tang Facsimile of the Wang Clan Calligraphies*, this scroll was commissioned in 697 CE by Empress Wu Zetian, based on authentic works of Wang Xizhi and his descendants presented at court by the official Wang Fangqing; skilled craftsmen traced them to produce an imperial archive copy. The surviving scroll contains works by seven hands — Wang Xizhi, Wang Xianzhi, Wang Huizhi, Wang Sengjian, Wang Hui, Wang Ci, and Wang Zhi — in ten separate sections. Among these, Wang Xizhi''s *Letter to His Aunt* and *Early Spring Letter* are jewels within jewels — among the very few surviving physical examples of the Wang family''s calligraphic legacy, irreplaceable for the study of the "Two Wangs" tradition. In 2012, this scroll was added to the list of works prohibited from overseas exhibition.</p><h3>3.2 Wang Xianzhi: Breaking Convention and Forging a New Style</h3><p><strong>Wang Xianzhi</strong> (344–386), Wang Xizhi''s seventh son, earned equal fame with his father as the "Two Wangs" of calligraphy. Not content to merely inherit the family tradition, he boldly innovated and created "po ti" — dissolving the boundaries between regular, running, and cursive scripts to make the act of writing more fluid and free.</p><p>Shanghai Museum''s <strong>*Ya Tou Wan Letter</strong>* (Tang facsimile) is Wang Xianzhi''s masterpiece in cursive script. It is a short note to a friend complaining that a medicine called "Ya Tou Wan" (duck-head pills) had failed to work — an ancient equivalent of a pharmaceutical review. The brushwork flows in sweeping loops and arcs, the energy unbroken from start to finish. It is the definitive surviving work of Wang Xianzhi''s running-cursive achievement.</p><p>![Wang Xianzhi''s Ya Tou Wan Letter, Tang facsimile | AI visual reference](images/06-王献之-鸭头丸帖.png)</p><h3>3.3 From Writing to Art: The Emergence of Calligraphic Theory</h3><p>The Wei-Jin period saw not only the first great peak of calligraphic creation, but also the systematic beginnings of calligraphic theory. The concepts of "sinew," "bone," "flesh," and "qi" (breath-energy) developed in this era likened calligraphy to the living human body, elevating it into an art form of genuine philosophical depth.</p><h2>IV. Sui, Tang, and Five Dynasties: Rigorous Discipline and Grand Magnificence</h2><h3>4.1 Tang Dynasty Calligraphy: The Age of Rules and Norms</h3><p>The Tang dynasty was the age of "method-bound" calligraphy. Under the magnificent imperial order, calligraphy too pursued strictness of form and structural discipline. Regular script reached its highest development in the Tang, producing the three great systems of Ouyang Xun, Yan Zhenqing, and Liu Gongquan, each of which profoundly influenced all later generations.</p><p>Shanghai Museum holds an exceptionally rich array of Tang dynasty calligraphy:</p><p><strong>Li Yong''s *Fahua Temple Stele Album</strong>*: Li Yong (678–747), styled Taihe and known as "Li of the North Sea," was celebrated for his running script — vigorous in brush force, magnificent in presence. The album in the museum''s collection is a uniquely surviving Song dynasty rubbing, once examined and annotated by the Qing calligrapher He Shaoji. Its brushwork is restrained and naturally unforced — a defining example of Li Yong''s calligraphy.</p><p><strong>Tang dynasty copied sutras</strong>: The museum holds many fine Tang sutra manuscripts, including the *Clerical Script Recension of the Qishi Sutra, Scroll Six*. Though written for the most part by unnamed copyists, the extreme discipline required by the flourishing Tang Buddhist establishment meant that these works attain a high standard of formal precision, displaying the technical rigor of Tang calligraphy.</p><h3>4.2 The Pinnacle of Wild Cursive Script: Huaisu''s *Bitter Bamboo Shoots Letter*</h3><p>Among Tang cursive-script calligraphy, nothing is more breathtaking than the "wild cursive" of <strong>Huaisu</strong>.</p><p>Huaisu (737–799), a native of Changsha with the secular surname Qian and the Buddhist name Cangzhen, was the most celebrated wild-cursive calligrapher of the Tang dynasty. He took monastic vows in early life but was consumed by calligraphy — planting ten thousand banana plants to have leaves on which to practice, wearing through wooden writing trays with his brush. He and Zhang Xu were jointly known as "Crazy Zhang and Tipsy Su," pushing the expressive power of Chinese cursive script to its absolute limits.</p><p>Shanghai Museum''s <strong>*Bitter Bamboo Shoots Letter</strong>* is Huaisu''s <strong>only undisputed original work</strong>, and one of 195 artefacts prohibited from going abroad. The scroll is on paper, 25.1 cm by 12 cm, and contains just 14 characters: "The bitter bamboo shoots and tea here are unusually fine — do come over directly. Huaisu." The brushwork is fluid and circular, naturally unaffected, deeply resonant with the "Two Wangs" tradition. Fourteen characters, yet the presence they command is immeasurable — a supreme achievement of Chinese cursive-script art.</p><p>![Huaisu''s Bitter Bamboo Shoots Letter, original | AI visual reference](images/01-怀素-苦笋帖.png)</p><h3>4.3 Tang Dynasty Painting: A Turning Point from Figures to Landscape</h3><p>The Tang dynasty was a pivotal moment in the history of Chinese painting. In the early Tang, figure painting reached its zenith with masters such as Yan Liben and Wu Daozi; from the mid- and late Tang onward, landscape painting began to establish itself as an independent category, and the ideas of literati painting began to take root.</p><p><strong>Sun Wei''s *Lofty Scholars* scroll</strong>: This is one of the most precious national treasures in Shanghai Museum''s painting collection, and one of the 195 artefacts prohibited from going abroad.</p><p>Sun Wei, a late-Tang painter from Kuaiji (present-day Shaoxing, Zhejiang), was accomplished in figure painting, depictions of spirits and demons, and scenes of dragons and water. Scholarly analysis suggests this painting is likely a surviving fragment of a larger *Seven Sages of the Bamboo Grove* composition. Emperor Huizong of Song inscribed the title "Sun Wei''s Lofty Scholars" on the work. Reading from right to left, it depicts four celebrated Wei-Jin intellectuals — Shan Tao, Wang Rong, Liu Ling, and Ruan Ji — each accompanied by an attendant, with garden stones, banana plants, chrysanthemums, and similar elements creating an atmosphere of lofty, unworldly refinement.</p><p>*Lofty Scholars* is not only a masterpiece of ancient Chinese figure painting but an important visual record for the study of the Wei-Jin "Seven Sages of the Bamboo Grove" culture. Its status as one of the 195 artefacts prohibited from going abroad speaks to its irreplaceable historical and artistic value.</p><p>![Sun Wei''s Lofty Scholars scroll | AI visual reference](images/02-孙位-高逸图.png)</p><h2>Five Dynasties Calligraphy and Painting: The Bridge Between Tang and Song</h2><p>The Five Dynasties period (907–960), though politically turbulent, produced remarkable cultural and artistic achievements. Among the museum''s Five Dynasties holdings, <strong>Xu Xi''s *Snow Bamboo</strong>* and <strong>Dong Yuan''s *Summer Mountains</strong>* are the most celebrated.</p><p><strong>Xu Xi''s *Snow Bamboo</strong>*: Xu Xi was the most famous bird-and-flower painter of the Five Dynasties, rivaling Huang Quan of Western Shu; the saying ran: "Huang''s richness, Xu''s rusticity." The museum''s *Snow Bamboo*, though unsigned, has been attributed to Xu Xi through connoisseurship (some scholars date it to the Northern or Southern Song). The painting renders withered wood, bamboo, and rocks through washes of ink, with blank areas representing accumulated snow — a unique technique. The celebrated connoisseur Xie Zhiliu regarded it as the only surviving authentic work by Xu Xi.</p><p>![Xu Xi''s Snow Bamboo | AI visual reference](images/05-徐熙-雪竹图.png)</p><p><strong>Dong Yuan''s *Summer Mountains</strong>*: Dong Yuan was a landscape painter of the Southern Tang in the Five Dynasties era, celebrated for his paintings of the Jiangnan landscape; together with Juran, he was known as the "Dong-Ju" pairing and was one of the founders of the Southern School of landscape painting. The museum''s *Summer Mountains* scroll is unsigned, but a later colophon by Dong Qichang attributes it to Dong Yuan. The dense and varied texture strokes in the painting capture the moist, misty beauty of a Jiangnan landscape and had a lasting influence on later literati landscape painting.</p><p>![Dong Yuan''s Summer Mountains | AI visual reference](images/07-董源-夏山图.png)</p><h2>V. Song Dynasty: The Golden Age of Literati Art</h2><h3>5.1 Song Dynasty Calligraphy: Prioritizing Personal Expression</h3><p>The central characteristic of Song dynasty calligraphy was "yi" — the emphasis on individual expression and aesthetic meaning, breaking free of Tang formal discipline. This shift was closely connected to the rising status of the literati class in the Song, the growth of Neo-Confucianism, and the establishment of "literati painting" theory.</p><p>The most celebrated representatives of Song calligraphy are the "Four Masters of Song Calligraphy": <strong>Su Shi, Huang Tingjian, Mi Fu, and Cai Xiang</strong>.</p><p>Shanghai Museum''s Song dynasty calligraphy collection includes a number of remarkable treasures:</p><p><strong>Mi Fu''s *Nine-Section Cursive Script Album</strong>*: Mi Fu (1051–1107), styled Yuanzhang with the sobriquet "Wanderer of Xiangyang," was one of the most distinctive calligraphers of the Song dynasty. His work drew from many traditions, most deeply from Wang Xizhi and Wang Xianzhi, producing a style he himself described as "brushing the characters" — bold as a storm-driven mast, penetrating as a cavalry charge. The museum''s running-script album pages, though unsigned, bear a 1102 colophon by his court colleague He Zhizhong, attributing them to Mi Fu. As surviving brushwork by Mi Fu is rare, this album is of exceptional rarity and value.</p><p>![Mi Fu''s Nine-Section Cursive Script Album | AI visual reference](images/08-米芾-草书九帖册.png)</p><p><strong>The "Finest Surviving Edition" of the *Chunhua Pavilion Model Calligraphies</strong>*: In 992 CE, during the third year of the Chunhua reign of the Northern Song dynasty, Emperor Taizong ordered skilled craftsmen to engrave onto stone the genuine calligraphic works preserved in the imperial collection — producing the first comprehensive model calligraphy compilation in Chinese history. Because the original stones deteriorated over time, fine surviving rubbings are extremely rare. Shanghai Museum''s "finest surviving edition" includes Wang Xizhi''s *Autumn Moon Letter* among others — the closest existing approximation to the original engravings, of the utmost importance for the study of Chinese calligraphic history.</p><p><strong>Sima Guang''s *Regular Script: Letter on Ningzhou</strong>*: Sima Guang, famed as the historian behind the *Comprehensive Mirror in Aid of Governance*, was also a calligrapher of considerable accomplishment. This album page in regular script is poised and disciplined — a characteristic example of the calligraphic style of a Song dynasty official-scholar.</p><p><strong>Emperor Huizong of Song''s *Thousand Character Classic in Regular Script</strong>*: Emperor Huizong may have been an ineffectual ruler, but as an artist he was a genius. His invention, the "Slender Gold" style, features lean and vigorous strokes written with a fleet and agile brush. Though technically regular script, it has the fluency of running script — an utterly individual achievement in the history of Chinese calligraphy.</p><p>![Emperor Huizong''s Thousand Character Classic in Slender Gold Style | AI visual reference](images/09-宋徽宗-瘦金体千字文.png)</p><h3>5.2 Song Dynasty Painting: The Splendor of Landscape, Bird-and-Flower, and Genre Painting</h3><p>The Song dynasty was one of the most magnificent periods in the history of Chinese painting. The establishment of the court academy, the rise of literati painting, and the development of urban culture together produced the rich diversity of Song dynasty painting.</p><p>Shanghai Museum''s Song dynasty painting collection includes representative works across landscape, bird-and-flower, and figure genres:</p><p><strong>Emperor Huizong''s *Willows, Crows, Reeds, and Geese* scroll</strong>: A surviving work by Emperor Huizong (Zhao Ji), lightly colored on paper. The scroll is divided into two sections: the first depicts willows and crows; the second, reeds and geese. The first section, with its archaic brushwork and lofty style, is universally regarded as Huizong''s own hand; the second is generally attributed to other academy painters. The painting bears the imperial seal "Xuanhe Inner Treasure" and other marks from the Northern Song imperial collection, along with Huizong''s personal cipher "Unrivaled Under Heaven," testifying to an unbroken chain of provenance. Huizong''s paintings display not only technical mastery but also the pursuit of poetry and refinement that characterized Song court art.</p><p>![Emperor Huizong''s Willows, Crows, Reeds, and Geese | AI visual reference](images/04-宋徽宗-柳鸦芦雁图.png)</p><p><strong>Song dynasty landscape painting</strong>: The museum holds important works of Song dynasty landscape. In the Northern Song, landscape was represented by Li Cheng, Fan Kuan, and Guo Xi — monumental and majestic in spirit; in the Southern Song, by Li Tang, Liu Songnian, Ma Yuan, and Xia Gui — serene and evocative in feeling. While the specific works on view rotate with each exhibition, the collection consistently includes representative examples from both periods.</p><p><strong>Song dynasty genre painting</strong>: The economic growth of Song cities gave rise to "genre painting," depicting scenes of urban life. The museum holds fine examples of Song genre painting — works that serve not only as art but as valuable historical records of Song social life.</p><h2>VI. Yuan Dynasty: The Unity of Calligraphy and Painting, and the Height of Literati Art</h2><h3>6.1 Zhao Mengfu: Master of Both Revival and Innovation</h3><p>The central characteristic of Yuan dynasty calligraphy and painting was "archaism" — a return to the traditions of the Han and Wei dynasties. Under Mongol rule, Chinese literati expressed their commitment to Central Plains culture through practices oriented toward the ancient past. The central figure of this movement was <strong>Zhao Mengfu</strong> (1254–1322).</p><p>Zhao Mengfu, styled Ziang and known as the "Snow-Robed Daoist," was the greatest calligrapher, painter, and poet of the Yuan dynasty. In calligraphy, he mastered all five major script types; he was particularly celebrated for regular and running scripts, and his regular script was ranked alongside that of the Tang masters Ouyang Xun, Yan Zhenqing, and Liu Gongquan — one of the "Four Great Masters of Regular Script."</p><p>Shanghai Museum''s Zhao Mengfu holdings include both calligraphy and painting:</p><p><strong>The *Guangfu Temple Pagoda Restoration Record in Running Script</strong>*: This is Zhao Mengfu''s representative work in running script — the brushwork rounded and fluid, the structure disciplined and precise, fully expressing his artistic stance of "returning to the Two Wangs." Zhao Mengfu advanced the theory of "the shared roots of calligraphy and painting," arguing that calligraphy and painting share a common language of the brush — a theory that profoundly influenced the development of literati painting in later centuries.</p><p>![Zhao Mengfu''s Guangfu Temple Pagoda Restoration Record | AI visual reference](images/10-赵孟頫-行书光福重建塔记.png)</p><p><strong>Zhao Mengfu''s paintings</strong>: The museum holds paintings by Zhao Mengfu that embody his artistic ideal of infusing calligraphic brushwork into painting, opening a new direction in Yuan literati painting.</p><h3>6.2 The Four Yuan Masters: The Pinnacle of Literati Landscape</h3><p>Yuan dynasty landscape painting reached its highest peak with the "Four Yuan Masters" — <strong>Huang Gongwang, Ni Zan, Wu Zhen, and Wang Meng</strong> — who carried literati landscape painting to its culmination.</p><p>The paintings of the Four Yuan Masters no longer sought the monumental grandeur or precise realism of Song landscape, but instead emphasized "freehand expression" — conveying the painter''s character, emotion, and philosophical reflection through simplified brushwork. This attitude of "painting as a vehicle for the self" and "painting as a source of joy" established the fundamental character of literati painting for all later generations.</p><p>Shanghai Museum holds representative works by the Four Yuan Masters:</p><p><strong>Works by Ni Zan</strong>: Ni Zan (1301–1374), styled Yuanzhen with the sobriquet "Master of the Cloud Forest," was the most quintessentially literati of the Four Yuan Masters. His landscape paintings typically depicted Lake Tai stones using the "folded ribbon" texture stroke; the mood is bleak and desolate — in his own words, "casual freehand sketching, not seeking formal likeness, but purely for my own amusement." The specific works on view rotate with exhibitions, but the characteristic spare and pale quality of his style is unmistakable.</p><p>![Ni Zan landscape | AI visual reference](images/11-倪瓒-山水.png)</p><p><strong>Works by Wang Meng</strong>: Wang Meng (1308–1385), styled Shuming with the sobriquet "Woodcutter of Yellow Crane Mountain," was Zhao Mengfu''s maternal grandson. His landscapes are distinguished by their dense and layered compositions — a sharp contrast to Ni Zan''s spare palette. The museum''s Wang Meng holdings show the stylistic diversity of Yuan literati landscape painting.</p><p><strong>Huang Gongwang''s *Dwelling in the Fuchun Mountains</strong>*: While the "Wuyong Master" section of this masterwork is held by the National Palace Museum in Taipei and the "Remaining Mountain" section by the Zhejiang Provincial Museum, Shanghai Museum holds other works by Huang Gongwang and later copies of great value for the study of his art.</p><h3>6.3 Other Yuan Dynasty Artists</h3><p>Beyond Zhao Mengfu and the Four Masters, the museum also holds works by Yang Weizhen, Zhang Yu, Sheng Mao, Wang Mian, Zhu Derun, and Ke Jiusi, among other important Yuan dynasty painters and calligraphers — together forming a rich panorama of Yuan dynasty art.</p><h2>VII. Ming Dynasty: The Elegance of the Wu School and the Flowering of Many Styles</h2><h3>7.1 Early Ming: The Zhe School and Court Academy Painting</h3><p>Early Ming painting was dominated by the "Zhe School" (represented by Dai Jin and Wu Wei) and court academy painting. These painters carried on the traditions of Song dynasty painting, emphasizing technical correctness and faithful representation.</p><h3>7.2 Middle Ming: The Four Wu Masters and the Revival of Literati Painting</h3><p>In the middle Ming period (late fifteenth to early sixteenth century), as Suzhou prospered economically and culturally, the "Wu School" rose to prominence as a major movement in the history of Chinese painting.</p><p>The "Four Wu Masters" — <strong>Shen Zhou, Wen Zhengming, Tang Yin, and Qiu Ying</strong> — were the central figures of the Wu School.</p><p>Shanghai Museum holds many fine works by all Four Wu Masters:</p><p><strong>Works by Shen Zhou</strong>: Shen Zhou (1427–1509), styled Qinan with the sobriquet "Stone Field" and in later life "Old White Stone," was the founder of the Wu School. His landscapes followed Wang Meng in his early years and Huang Gongwang in his middle years; in later life he frequently painted scenes of the Jiangnan countryside, in a style that is powerful yet spare. The museum''s *Autumn Colors on the Western Mountain* and other works demonstrate the depth of this literati painting master.</p><p>![Shen Zhou''s Autumn Colors on the Western Mountain | AI visual reference](images/12-沈周-西山秋色图.png)</p><p><strong>Works by Wen Zhengming</strong>: Wen Zhengming (1470–1559), whose given name was Bi and courtesy name Zhengming, styled himself "Hermit of Hengshan." A student of Shen Zhou, he came to surpass his teacher in fame and influence. Both his calligraphy and his painting were outstanding: his small regular script is exquisite, his running script fluid, his landscape style delicate and moist. The museum holds several works by Wen Zhengming, including the *Running Script Western Garden Poems* and the *Regular Script: Biography of Gu Chunqian*.</p><p>![Wen Zhengming, running script | AI visual reference](images/13-文徵明-行书.png)</p><p><strong>Works by Tang Yin</strong>: Tang Yin (1470–1524), styled Bohu with the sobriquet "The Six Likenesses Hermit," was the most legendary literati painter of the Ming dynasty — brilliantly talented yet dogged by misfortune. His landscape, figure, and bird-and-flower paintings were all exceptional, fresh and spirited in style. The museum''s Tang Yin paintings reveal both technical mastery and the complex inner world of this celebrated "Jiangnan romantic genius."</p><p><strong>Works by Qiu Ying</strong>: Qiu Ying (about 1494–1552), styled Shifu with the sobriquet "Master of Ten Continents," was the only one of the Four Wu Masters from an artisan background. His painting was distinguished by meticulous brushwork and rich color, especially in figure painting — his court ladies and historical scenes are lavishly rendered, representing the high point of the Ming court academy style.</p><h3>7.3 Late Ming: Dong Qichang and the Songjiang School</h3><p>In the late Ming period (late sixteenth to early seventeenth century), as the influence of the Wu School waned, the Songjiang School, represented by <strong>Dong Qichang</strong> (1555–1636), rose to prominence.</p><p>Dong Qichang, styled Xuanzai with the sobriquets "Sibo" and "Fragrant Light Hermit," was one of the greatest painters, calligraphers, and theorists of the Ming dynasty. His "Northern and Southern Schools" theory — dividing landscape painting since the Tang dynasty into a "Southern School" (literati painting) and a "Northern School" (academic painting), championing the former and deprecating the latter — had a profound influence on the trajectory of Chinese painting from the Ming and Qing dynasties onward.</p><p>Shanghai Museum''s Dong Qichang holdings are exceptionally rich:</p><p><strong>The *Cursive Script Fang Ge Xing and Other Poems* scroll</strong>: Dong Qichang was accomplished in regular, running, and cursive scripts alike. His brushwork is airy and expansive, the energy flowing from line to line, capturing the lean and freely turning vitality of Huaisu''s cursive. His calligraphic and painting theories stressed "reading ten thousand volumes and traveling ten thousand miles," raising literati painting theory to a new level.</p><p>![Dong Qichang''s Cursive Script Fang Ge Xing scroll | AI visual reference](images/14-董其昌-草书放歌行.png)</p><p><strong>Ming dynasty calligraphy</strong>: Early Ming calligraphy was dominated by the "Court Cabinet Style" (represented by Shen Du) — technically accomplished but lacking individuality. The middle period was defined by the "Wu School of Calligraphy" (Zhu Yunming, Wen Zhengming, Wang Chong), diverse in style and vivid in personality. In the later period, Dong Qichang, Zhang Ruitu, Huang Daozhou, and Ni Yuanlu pushed toward a bolder, more eccentric calligraphic expression.</p><p>The museum''s Ming dynasty calligraphy collection covers virtually every phase and every important school of Ming calligraphic development.</p><h2>VIII. Qing Dynasty: The Revival of the Stele School and a Plurality of Approaches</h2><h3>8.1 Early Qing: The Four Wangs and the Orthodox Tradition</h3><p>Early Qing landscape painting was dominated by the "Four Wangs" — <strong>Wang Shimin, Wang Jian, Wang Hui, and Wang Yuanqi</strong> — who represented the mainstream of court painting and orthodox literati painting in the Qing dynasty, emphasizing the study of the ancients and development within the "Southern School" landscape tradition.</p><p>Shanghai Museum holds many works by the Four Wangs. While they are less innovative than the later "Eight Eccentrics of Yangzhou," they attained an extremely high standard in technical refinement and in sustaining the tradition.</p><h3>8.2 The Four Monk Painters: The Voice of Loyalist Sentiment</h3><p>In contrast to the gentle serenity of the Four Wangs, the "Four Monk Painters" — <strong>Bada Shanren (Zhu Da), Shitao, Hongren, and Kuncan</strong> — as loyalists to the fallen Ming dynasty, expressed through painting their grief and defiance under Qing rule.</p><p><strong>Bada Shanren''s</strong> works are spare and condensed, his images strange and distorted; the fish and birds in his paintings often stare upward with a "cold-eyed look at the world," expressing unmistakably his resentment of the new order.</p><p>![Bada Shanren bird-and-flower painting | AI visual reference](images/15-八大山人-花鸟.png)</p><p><strong>Shitao''s</strong> painting stressed "I use my own method," opposing blind imitation of the ancients. His *Bitter Melon Monk''s Notes on Painting* is an important work of classical painting theory.</p><p>![Shitao landscape | AI visual reference](images/16-石涛-山水.png)</p><p>The museum holds representative works by all four monk painters — treasures of art and vital material for the study of the political and cultural upheaval of the late Ming and early Qing.</p><h3>8.3 Mid-Qing: The Eight Eccentrics of Yangzhou and the Liberation of Individuality</h3><p>In the mid-Qing period (eighteenth century), in the commercially flourishing city of Yangzhou, a group of painters of strikingly unconventional and individualistic style emerged, collectively known as the "Eight Eccentrics of Yangzhou" — primarily <strong>Jin Nong, Huang Shen, Zheng Xie (Zheng Banqiao), Li Shan, Li Fangying, Wang Shishen, Gao Xiang, and Luo Ping</strong> (in practice, the "eight" was never strictly limited to eight figures).</p><p>The Eight Eccentrics broke with traditional conventions, emphasizing individuality and innovation; their subjects frequently included plum blossom, orchid, bamboo, and chrysanthemum — the "Four Gentlemen" — as symbols of literati integrity.</p><p>Shanghai Museum holds representative works by the Eight Eccentrics, including Zheng Banqiao''s orchids and bamboo, Jin Nong''s plum blossoms, and Luo Ping''s ghost paintings.</p><p>![Zheng Banqiao''s orchid and bamboo | AI visual reference](images/17-郑板桥-兰竹.png)</p><h3>8.4 Qing Dynasty Calligraphy: From the Model Book Tradition to the Stele School</h3><p>The most defining feature of Qing dynasty calligraphy was the rise of the "stele school."</p><p>In the early Qing, calligraphy was dominated by the "model book tradition" — learning from the lineage of model calligraphies stretching from the "Two Wangs" onward — as represented by Weng Fanggang, Liu Yong, Liang Tongshu, and Wang Wenzhi.</p><p>From the mid-Qing onward, with the growth of bronze and stone inscription studies, more and more ancient stelae were unearthed and examined. Calligraphers began drawing nourishment from Han and Wei dynasty carved inscriptions, giving rise to the "stele school" movement. Its leading figures included Deng Shiru, Yi Bingshou, Ruan Yuan, Bao Shichen, and He Shaoji.</p><p>By the late Qing, the stele school had become the mainstream of calligraphy; Zhao Zhiqian, Wu Changshuo, Kang Youwei, and Shen Zengzhi were all masters of this tradition.</p><p>Shanghai Museum holds representative works from every phase and every school of Qing dynasty calligraphy, fully representing the historical transition from the model book tradition to the stele school.</p><h2>IX. The Modern Era: Inheritance and Transformation</h2><h3>9.1 The Shanghai School: Where Tradition Meets the Modern Age</h3><p>After Shanghai opened as a treaty port in 1843, the city gradually became the economic and cultural center of China. A group of painters gathered in Shanghai and formed the "Shanghai School."</p><p>Shanghai School painting both inherited the literati tradition and absorbed elements from folk art and foreign culture, embracing subjects more in tune with urban popular taste and a style more vibrant and direct.</p><p>Early Shanghai School masters included <strong>Ren Xiong, Ren Xun, Ren Yi (Ren Bonian), and Ren Yu</strong> (collectively the "Four Rens"), as well as <strong>Zhao Zhiqian, Xugu, and Wu Changshuo</strong>; later figures included <strong>Zhang Daqian, Liu Haisu, Pan Tianshou, and Fu Baoshi</strong>.</p><p>Shanghai Museum has a dedicated "Shanghai Painting and Calligraphy Gallery," displaying works related to Shanghai. This is one of the new galleries in the museum''s East Building, organized into four thematic sections — "Artistic Lineage and Achievement," "Cultural and Regional Interactions," "Connoisseurship and Artistic Influence," and "At the Forefront: The Splendor of Shanghai" — systematically tracing the development of painting and calligraphy art in the Shanghai region.</p><h3>9.2 Modern Calligraphy: The Merging of Stele and Model Book Traditions, and New Directions</h3><p>Modern calligraphy, building on the Qing stele school, further expanded its stylistic range, with individual expression becoming ever more prominent.</p><p><strong>Wu Changshuo</strong> (1844–1927), whose original name was Junqing, styled Changshuo with the sobriquet "Fou Lu," was a complete master of Shanghai School painting, calligraphy, and seal carving. His calligraphy was known for seal script rooted in the Stone Drum inscriptions, with a brush manner powerful and seasoned — uniting calligraphy and seal carving into a single art.</p><p>![Wu Changshuo, seal script | AI visual reference](images/18-吴昌硕-篆书.png)</p><p><strong>Yu Youren</strong> (1879–1964), whose original name was Bocun, styled Youren, was a celebrated modern statesman and calligrapher. His creation of the "Standard Cursive Script" system regulated cursive-script forms, combining practical utility with artistic value, and played an important role in popularizing the cursive style.</p><p><strong>Li Shutong (Master Hongyi)</strong> (1880–1942) was one of the pioneers of Chinese spoken drama in his early years; in middle age he took monastic vows, receiving the Buddhist name Yanyin and the sobriquet Hongyi. His late calligraphy is ethereal and serene — stripped of all worldly traces — embodying the profound fusion of Buddhist thought and artistic vision that defined his later life.</p><p>Shanghai Museum holds important works by leading modern calligraphers, representing the inheritance and transformation of traditional calligraphy in the new era.</p><h2>X. The Visitor Experience and Cultural Significance of the Galleries</h2><h3>10.1 A Historical Survey Exhibition: A Three-Dimensional History of Chinese Culture</h3><p>Shanghai Museum''s calligraphy and painting galleries are organized as comprehensive historical surveys, presenting the development of Chinese calligraphy and painting in chronological sequence. This approach allows visitors to experience the three-thousand-year evolution of Chinese painting and calligraphy in one continuous space.</p><p>Currently, the survey exhibition rotates its works every six months, with a complete cycle spanning three years. Works are selected to be representative — typically a single work per artist, but with every major school in art history given representation. This curatorial philosophy reflects the museum''s profound understanding of the overall arc of Chinese painting and calligraphy history.</p><h3>10.2 The Eight Scenic Views of the Painting Gallery: Jiangnan Garden Aesthetics in a Museum Space</h3><p>The painting gallery in the East Building is designed with particular care. In addition to retaining the wooden floors and motion-activated lighting from the original museum, the new gallery has added "Eight Scenic Views" inspired by the museum''s own collection works, evoking the spatial sensibility of Jiangnan gardens. This approach to integrating the spatial imagery of a Jiangnan garden into a modern museum setting not only enriches the viewing environment but aligns the display space more closely with the cultural context of the works themselves.</p><h3>10.3 The Yukdao Studio and the Special Gallery: Dedicated Space for Large Format Works</h3><p>Many Chinese calligraphy and painting works are large in format and cannot be fully displayed in a conventional gallery. The East Building''s new Yukdao special gallery is designed specifically for such works.</p><p>Currently on display in this space is Wang Hui''s long handscroll *The Great River and Layered Peaks*, as well as the *Album of Great Seen Through Small*, which copies famous works by painters of many dynasties. These works, vast in scale and overwhelming in presence, can be seen in their entirety in the special gallery — a profound visual experience for the viewer.</p><h3>10.4 Cultural Significance: A Historical Meaning That Transcends Art</h3><p>The value of Shanghai Museum''s painting and calligraphy galleries extends far beyond art itself.</p><p>These works are direct reflections of ancient Chinese social life, intellectual thought, aesthetic taste, and human experience. Through them, we can learn about the clothing, housing, transportation, and entertainment of people in every historical period; feel the philosophical thought, literary fashions, and religious devotion of different eras; and appreciate the joys, sorrows, aspirations, and spiritual struggles of the literati across the centuries.</p><p>Most importantly, these works are powerful evidence of the unbroken continuity of Chinese civilization. From oracle bone inscriptions to modern calligraphy, from pre-Qin silk figure paintings to contemporary ink painting, the evolution of Chinese painting and calligraphy art clearly demonstrates how Chinese culture, through embracing diversity, absorbing outside influences, and constant innovation, has always maintained its core values and defining spiritual character.</p><h2>XI. Conclusion: Guardians of a Civilization''s Memory</h2><p>To walk into Shanghai Museum''s painting and calligraphy galleries is to encounter not only magnificent works of art but a history of Chinese civilization written in ink and color.</p><p>Here, Wang Xizhi''s Eastern Jin refinement, Yan Zhenqing''s Tang dynasty grandeur, Su Shi''s Northern Song brilliance, Ni Zan''s Yuan dynasty bleakness, Dong Qichang''s late Ming elegance, Bada Shanren''s loyalist grief, Wu Changshuo''s modern vigor — across a thousand years of time, they gather in this one gallery.</p><p>These works have survived wars, the erosion of time, and the upheavals of human history. That they survive at all is itself a heroic story of civilization''s preservation. From ancient collectors and connoisseurs, to modern cultural guardians, to the staff of Shanghai Museum today — generation after generation of people have devoted enormous effort to protecting these precious cultural heirlooms.</p><p>Today, when we stand before the *Lofty Scholars* scroll and gaze at the Wei-Jin intellectual painted by Sun Wei — at ease, picking at his clothes while holding forth in conversation; when we stand before the *Bitter Bamboo Shoots Letter* and feel the surging energy of Huaisu''s cursive brushwork; when we stand before a snow-covered temple in an ancient landscape and sense the spiritual fortitude of an ancient literatus holding firm through the bitter cold — we are not merely appreciating art. We are in dialogue with those who came before, in dialogue with civilization itself.</p><p>Shanghai Museum''s painting and calligraphy galleries are precisely such a place — where we can cross the boundaries of time and come face to face with history. Here, every work is a window, and through it, we can see a China that is richer, more profound, and more real.</p><h2>Appendix: Key Works in Shanghai Museum''s Painting and Calligraphy Galleries</h2><p>| Period | Artist | Work | Classification | Artistic Significance | |--------|--------|------|----------------|-----------------------| | Eastern Jin (Tang facsimile) | Wang Xizhi | *Shangyou Letter* scroll | First-Class National Cultural Relic | One of the Tang facsimiles closest to Wang Xizhi''s original brushwork | | Eastern Jin (Tang facsimile) | Wang Xianzhi | *Ya Tou Wan Letter* scroll | First-Class National Cultural Relic | Wang Xianzhi''s defining work in cursive script | | Tang | Huaisu | *Bitter Bamboo Shoots Letter* scroll | Prohibited from Export | Huaisu''s only undisputed authentic original | | Tang | Sun Wei | *Lofty Scholars* scroll | Prohibited from Export | Masterpiece of Tang figure painting; one of 195 artefacts prohibited from going abroad | | Five Dynasties | Xu Xi (attributed) | *Snow Bamboo* hanging scroll | First-Class National Cultural Relic | Key work for the study of Five Dynasties bird-and-flower painting | | Five Dynasties | Dong Yuan (attributed) | *Summer Mountains* scroll | First-Class National Cultural Relic | Defining work of the founder of Southern School landscape | | Northern Song | Emperor Huizong | *Willows, Crows, Reeds, and Geese* scroll | First-Class National Cultural Relic | Huizong''s own brushwork; fully documented provenance | | Northern Song | Wang Anshi | *Key Points of the Shurangama Sutra* scroll | Prohibited from Export | The only surviving authentic work by Wang Anshi | | Northern Song | Mi Fu | *Nine-Section Cursive Script Album* | First-Class National Cultural Relic | Defining example of Mi Fu''s calligraphy | | Yuan | Zhao Mengfu | *Guangfu Temple Pagoda Restoration Record in Running Script* | First-Class National Cultural Relic | Masterwork of Zhao Mengfu''s calligraphy | | Ming | Shen Zhou, Wen Zhengming, Tang Yin, Qiu Ying | Combined works of the Four Wu Masters | First-Class National Cultural Relic | Defining works of Ming dynasty literati painting | | Ming | Dong Qichang | *Cursive Script Fang Ge Xing and Other Poems* scroll | First-Class National Cultural Relic | Defining example of Dong Qichang''s calligraphy | | Qing | Bada Shanren | Various works | First-Class National Cultural Relic | Defining figure among early Qing loyalist painters | | Qing | Shitao | Various works | First-Class National Cultural Relic | Defining figure of the early Qing individualist school | | Qing | Zheng Banqiao | Orchid and Bamboo hanging scroll | First-Class National Cultural Relic | Defining figure of the Eight Eccentrics of Yangzhou | | Modern | Wu Changshuo | Seal script couplet and other works | First-Class National Cultural Relic | Defining figure of the Shanghai School | | Modern | Zhang Daqian | Various works | First-Class National Cultural Relic | Master of modern Chinese painting |</p><p>*This article was written based on official Shanghai Museum materials, academic research, and publicly available exhibition information, with the aim of being accurate, comprehensive, and engaging. Since the painting and calligraphy galleries operate on a rotating historical survey basis, with works changing every six months, the specific works on display should be confirmed on the day of your visit.*</p>',
  '[]'::jsonb,
  1,
  TRUE
) ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
