  'shanghai_museum_jade',
  'shanghai',
  'Chapter Five: The Beautiful Stone — Soul of a Nation',
  '第五章 石之美者，国之魂脉',
  '"The gentleman compares his virtue to jade — its warmth and luster speak of benevolence; its fine, close texture, of wisdom; its edge that cuts but never wounds',
  '🏛',
  'Museum',
  ARRAY[]::TEXT[],
  '<h2>A Guide to the Ancient Chinese Jade Gallery, Shanghai Museum East Branch</h2><h2>One: Walking into the Jade Gallery — Nine Thousand Years of Light</h2><p>Push open the door to the Ancient Chinese Jade Gallery at the Shanghai Museum East Branch, and the first thing you see is not a display case but a massive piece of Hetian nephrite — white and lustrous, its natural skin still a warm amber, standing quietly at the entrance, inviting every visitor to reach out and feel it. This is an intentional ritual: before you step into nine thousand years of jade civilization, you are asked to touch the temperature of jade with your own hands.</p><p>Many peoples of the world have cherished jade — the jade of the Maya in Mesoamerica, the greenstone of the Maori in New Zealand, the ancient jade of the Siberian steppe — but only the Chinese <strong>have, with an unbroken passion, bound jade to civilization itself</strong>, from the earliest recorded times to the fall of the last dynasty, across nine full millennia.</p><p>The Jade Gallery is organized chronologically into six major units, with more than 360 pieces laid out along the timeline: the mysterious prehistoric jades, the stately and dignified jades of the Xia, Shang, and Western Zhou, the lively and unconstrained jades of the Spring-Autumn and Warring States periods, the vigorous and magnificent jades of the Han and Jin, the fresh and diverse jades of the Tang, Song, Liao, and Jin dynasties, and the technically dazzling jades of the Yuan, Ming, and Qing. These six units correspond to six faces of jade''s cultural evolution: <strong>sacred jade, ritual jade, moral jade, burial jade, worldly jade, and artistic jade</strong> — in each period, jade takes on a different guise and reflects the deepest spiritual structures of its era.</p><h2>Two: What Is Jade? — A Spiritual Code Unique to China</h2><p>Before looking at individual objects, it helps to understand one central question: <strong>what, in the Chinese world, is jade?</strong></p><p>In the West, gold has been the ultimate symbol of wealth and power. In China, that position has, since antiquity, belonged to jade. But jade''s meanings are far richer than gold''s — it serves simultaneously as a ritual implement for communing with heaven and spirits, a marker of social rank and ceremonial order, a vessel for moral aspiration, and a protective charm against harm and an escort for the dead.</p><p>The Chinese character for jade is itself symbolic: three horizontal strokes representing heaven, earth, and humanity, with a single vertical line running through them — <strong>jade as the mediating axis connecting the three realms</strong>. The character for "nation" in classical Chinese contains the character for jade at its heart — the ancients had quietly declared that a country is guarded by jade.</p><p>The reverence for jade in ancient Chinese texts is breathtaking. Confucius ascribed to jade eleven virtues, encompassing benevolence, righteousness, wisdom, courage, and purity — the entire canon of the gentleman''s character. The Book of Songs used the phrase "cut and filed, carved and polished" to describe the gentleman''s work of self-cultivation — and those words were originally the technical vocabulary of jade workers. "Uncut jade cannot become a vessel" long ago transcended the craft domain to become China''s most instinctive philosophy of personal growth.</p><p>If there is one material in the world that compresses aesthetics, belief, politics, morality, and emotion into a single stone, that material can only be Chinese jade.</p><h2>Three: The Age of Sacred Jade — Spiritual Messages from Prehistoric Civilization</h2><h3>(Roughly 9,000 to 4,000 years ago)</h3><h3>3.1 The Beginning of All Things — The Dawn of the Jue Ring</h3><p>Humanity''s earliest encounter with jade predates writing by thousands of years.</p><p>At the Shuangta site in Taonan, Jilin province, archaeologists have found what may be the oldest known jade artifacts, dating back nearly nine thousand years. There were no states, no writing, not even cities yet — and yet people were already carefully polishing jade.</p><p>In the gallery, a <strong>jade jue ring of the Xinglongwa culture</strong> rests quietly in its case — a yellowish-green nephrite ring with a deliberate gap, roughly the size of a thumbnail. This single object pushes the relationship between jade and humanity back to nearly eight thousand years ago. It is among the earliest known mature jade ornaments in China and was found placed against the ear of the tomb occupant — likely the oldest known form of earring. Do not overlook that gap. The character "jue" shares its root with "decision" or "separation" — the gap is intentional, carrying connotations of resolve and departure. From this one detail, we can already glimpse the ancient Chinese impulse to invest every object with layers of symbolic meaning.</p><h3>3.2 Hongshan Culture — Where the Dragon Was Born</h3><p>Roughly 5,500 to 5,000 years ago, the people of the Liao River basin — the Hongshan culture — created the first great peak in the history of Chinese jade.</p><p>In the Hongshan spiritual world, jade was the only medium through which the gods could communicate with human beings. The dead, not the living, received jade — through the practice of "only jade for burial," they constructed underground pathways to the divine. Hongshan jade forms were drawn from the animal spirits they revered: curved cloud-shaped pendants symbolizing cosmic forces; <strong>jade pig-dragons</strong> (jue-form vessels) with round heads, large ears, and projecting snouts — a hybrid of pig and dragon that scholars widely recognize as one of the prototypes for the "first dragon of Chinese civilization"; and the famous <strong>C-shaped jade dragon</strong>, its coiled body like a question mark leaping across time — is it a dragon or a bear? An emissary of the sun or a shaman''s guardian? Archaeologists continue to debate.</p><p>![Hongshan culture jade pig-dragon](images/hongshan_zhulong.jpg) *A jade pig-dragon (jue-form vessel) of the Hongshan culture. Neolithic period, Hongshan culture (roughly 4000–3000 BC). Round head, large ears, projecting snout — a hybrid of pig and dragon, regarded as one of the prototypes for the "first dragon of Chinese civilization." Shanghai Museum collection.*</p><p>That debate is itself part of the attraction: <strong>Hongshan jade is mysterious, powerful, and points directly to the deepest spiritual impulses of human civilization</strong>.</p><h3>3.3 Liangzhu Culture — The Power Declaration of East Asia''s First State</h3><p>If Hongshan jade is the soul of primitive religion, Liangzhu jade is the power symbol of East Asia''s earliest "state."</p><p>Some 5,300 to 4,300 years ago, the people of the Taihu Lake basin — the Liangzhu culture — constructed an elaborate system of jade ritual objects to establish and maintain the hierarchical order of their pyramid-shaped society. <strong>Jade cong, jade bi, jade yue</strong> — three object types corresponding to three forms of power: ritual authority for communing with heaven and earth (the cong), the symbolism of heaven and earth (the bi), and the supreme military power of kingship (the yue).</p><p>The centerpiece of the gallery is a <strong>Liangzhu culture jade cong decorated with a deity-and-beast flying-bird motif</strong>, excavated from the Fuquanshan site in Qingpu. Square outside, circular inside, with low thin walls — at each of its four corners, a high platform has been carved using the relief subtraction technique and then incised with the dense "Liangzhu divine emblem" — a half-human, half-animal figure wearing a feathered crown, arms spread wide, riding astride an animal mask. This emblem appears repeatedly across Liangzhu sites; scholars believe it represents the image of the highest deity venerated by the Liangzhu people, a visual proclamation of the theocratic authority of the era.</p><p>![Liangzhu culture jade cong with deity-and-beast flying-bird motif](images/liangzhu_cong_1.jpg) *Liangzhu culture jade cong with deity-and-beast flying-bird motif. Neolithic period, Liangzhu culture (roughly 3300–2300 BC), height 5.6 cm. Excavated from the Fuquanshan site, Qingpu District, 2008. Square exterior, circular interior, with the "Liangzhu divine emblem" at each corner. Shanghai Museum collection.*</p><p>Another jade cong with the deity-and-bird motif stands 39.3 centimetres tall and is divided into fifteen sections — among the tallest surviving Liangzhu jade cong in existence. Fifteen sections means the jade worker had to carve, section by section, precisely symmetrical deity figures into extraordinarily hard jade, using only the most primitive rotary tools and quartz sand, guided by unaided eyes and bare hands — and produce a masterwork that professional craftsmen today still find astonishing.</p><p>![Liangzhu culture jade cong with deity-and-bird motif, fifteen sections](images/liangzhu_15_cong.jpg) *Liangzhu culture jade cong with deity-and-bird motif. Height 39.3 cm, fifteen sections — among the tallest surviving Liangzhu jade cong in existence. Each section carries a simplified deity figure, the workmanship exceptional. Shanghai Museum collection.*</p><p><strong>Liangzhu culture jade yue</strong> must not be overlooked either. The classical Chinese character for "king" evolved from the character for the yue axe. This jade yue bears not a single trace of use — it never felled a tree or split a stone. Its function was to declare that a particular person held the supreme power of life and death. This silent jade object tells us, more directly than any written record, that more than four thousand years ago, someone stood on the shore of Lake Taihu and, in the name of jade, first learned the meaning of "to rule."</p><h3>3.4 Other Prehistoric Jade Traditions</h3><p>The flowering of prehistoric Chinese jade was no solitary achievement. The gallery also displays a <strong>jade huang pendant of the Majiabang culture</strong> (Jiaxing, Zhejiang, roughly 7,000 years ago) — representing the earliest stirring of awareness in the lower Yangtze River region of the distinction between jade and common stone, a moment scholars call the "separation of jade from rock."</p><p>A <strong>Longshan culture jade axe with a deity-and-eagle motif</strong> comes from the Yellow River basin — blue-green nephrite, one face carved with an abstract divine face and the other with an eagle — two power totems combined in a single ritual weapon, a classic hybrid of ceremonial implement and military symbol, expressing the coalescence of military and divine authority in prehistory.</p><p><strong>Shijiahe culture</strong> objects come from Hubei, where the late-period jade production favored small human-head sculptures — square-faced, almond-eyed, broad-nosed, their expression hovering between concentrated attention and trance, bearing a strange resonance with the bronze figures of Sanxingdui, inviting vivid speculation about ancient networks of southern civilization.</p><h2>Four: The Age of Ritual Jade — The Dual Order of Bronze and Jade in the Xia, Shang, and Western Zhou</h2><h3>(Roughly 21st century BC to 771 BC)</h3><h3>4.1 "Ritual Embodied in Vessel" — The Civilizational Alliance of Jade and Bronze</h3><p>Entering the age of written civilization, jade underwent a profound transformation of role.</p><p>The rulers of the Xia, Shang, and Zhou had grasped a governing insight: <strong>if you want people to obey rules, first make them revere objects</strong>. Bronze ding vessels and jade ritual objects together formed the symbolic system of that era — bronze ding representing the weight of political power, jade ritual objects representing the legitimacy of hierarchical order. The two were complementary, and together the physical carriers of the concept of "rule through ritual."</p><p>The cases display side by side a Xia dynasty and a Shang dynasty <strong>jade gui tablet</strong>. The gui is one of the "six jade objects" described in the Zhou Rites — the Son of Heaven held the grand zhen gui, dukes held the huan gui, and marquises held the xin gui — different ranks holding different gui, with size and material directly indicating the holder''s position in the political order. A Xia dynasty jade zhang blade — blue-green nephrite turned yellow-white by long burial — narrow and elongated with double bevels — has been found scattered across sites in the Yellow, Yangtze, and Pearl River basins, physical proof of the early Chinese civilizational exchange network.</p><h3>4.2 Shang Dynasty Dragon-Form Jade Pendant — A Manifesto of Civilization at Its Zenith</h3><p>In the gallery''s sequence, a <strong>Shang dynasty dragon-form jade pendant</strong> draws the eye and holds it.</p><p>The dragon — the most central totem of Chinese civilization — appears for the first time as an unambiguous "dragon" in jade during the Shang dynasty. This jade dragon''s form corresponds almost perfectly to the character for "dragon" in oracle-bone script — pointed head, curved neck, S-shaped body — the most direct cross-verification between written character and material object. The appearance of the dragon-form jade pendant marks the moment when Chinese dragon reverence evolved from blurred totemic worship into a mature symbolic system with clear form and established conventions.</p><p>![Shang dynasty dragon-form jade pendant](images/shang_longpei.jpg) *Shang dynasty dragon-form jade pendant. Shang dynasty (roughly 1600–1046 BC). Blue-green nephrite, flat carved, dragon head turned back over body, body curves in an S-shape matching the oracle-bone character for "dragon." Shanghai Museum collection.*</p><p>The <strong>Shang dynasty jade qi axe with beast-face motif</strong> is equally worth studying. This jade qi is a ritual weapon whose main surface carries a beast face; the same pattern appears on both sides, rendered in double-line incision to simulate shallow relief. Those wide staring eyes — in the Shang world you could neither fail to revere nor fail to fear them, for they were the eyes of the divine, and the eyes of royal power. Traces of vermilion remaining on the surface indicate it took part in some solemn ritual, stained with blood or pigment, offered to something unseen.</p><p>![Shang dynasty jade qi axe with beast-face motif](images/shang_yuqi.jpg) *Shang dynasty jade qi axe with beast-face motif. Shang dynasty (roughly 1600–1046 BC). Dark blue-green nephrite, partially stained with vermilion, beast-face motif on both sides in double-line incision, round hole through the body. A ritual weapon embodying the fusion of military and divine power. Shanghai Museum collection.*</p><h3>4.3 Western Zhou Jade Assemblage Sets — Jade and the Social Order</h3><p>The Western Zhou period represents the most precisely designed chapter in ancient Chinese ritual culture.</p><p>Under the Zhou kinship system, aristocratic identity could not simply be asserted — it had to be proclaimed through visible objects. So the <strong>jade pendant assemblage</strong> came into being — multiple jade elements (huang crescents, heng crossbars, ju spacers, yu connectors, and chong-ya pendants) strung together on silk cord and worn across the chest, chiming softly with every step, that very sound itself an expression of ritual-music order. The Book of Songs says "thinking of the gentleman, warm as jade" — aristocrats had to maintain perfect posture and gait while wearing assemblages, for any faltering step would disturb the chiming pattern. Jade pendants became monitors of bodily deportment.</p><p>In the cases, a <strong>Western Zhou double-dragon-head jade huang crescent</strong> — white-blue nephrite, an arc-shaped pendant with a dragon head carved at each end — is a key structural element of the pendant assemblage, displayed alongside bronze ding and gui vessels that together constitute the complete world of that era''s elite.</p><h2>Five: The Age of Moral Jade — The Spirit of the Gentleman in the Spring-Autumn and Warring States Periods</h2><h3>(770–221 BC)</h3><h3>5.1 Ritual Collapses, Jade Turns Inward</h3><p>In 771 BC the Western Zhou fell. For the following five centuries, the established ritual order unraveled.</p><p>Yet strangely, the more the ritual system collapsed, the more deliberately the moral dimension of jade was emphasized. It was in this era of turmoil that Confucius articulated his celebrated formulation "the gentleman compares his virtue to jade," and the Confucian school mapped jade''s physical properties onto the ideal qualities of the gentleman''s character: jade''s warmth corresponds to benevolence, jade''s toughness to righteousness, jade''s purity to integrity, jade''s clear ring to music.</p><p>This is a remarkable intellectual substitution: <strong>when the ritual system failed, Confucians internalized order as individual virtue, and jade became the finest material symbol of that virtue</strong>. The gentleman is "warm and lustrous like jade" — wearing jade was not display but daily self-reminder: I must become what jade is.</p><h3>5.2 Warring States Dragon-and-Phoenix Jade Pieces — The Peak of Beauty and Freedom</h3><p>Warring States jade objects mark a historic liberation of form.</p><p>In that era of a hundred contending schools of thought, even jade became free and full of imagination. Traditional ritual vessel forms were abandoned in favor of densely coiling dragon patterns, phoenixes in extraordinary attitudes, and animals writhing in groups. The <strong>Warring States interlocked-dragon jade pendant</strong> in the gallery — blue-green nephrite, two dragons twining around each other, bodies curving into an elegant geometric shape — is the characteristic Warring States "W-shaped dragon" style, its surface decorated with grain-pattern knobs in shallow relief, each knob full and rounded as a ripe grain of rice.</p><p>The <strong>Warring States dragon-and-phoenix jade zhui sword-scabbard fitting</strong> is a component once set into the outside of a sword scabbard to enable wearing. Its surface is decorated at the narrow end with a dragon pattern, with a tiger on each side, and below that two phoenixes symmetrically arranged, each holding a small snake in its talons — the whole piece, no larger than a palm, conjures a complete cosmological scene of divine animals. To adorn a sword with jade was essentially to "ritualize" military force — elevating the sword from an instrument of killing to an expression of identity and virtue.</p><p>![Warring States dragon-and-phoenix jade zhui sword fitting](images/zhanguo_yuzhi.jpg) *Warring States dragon-and-phoenix jade zhui sword-scabbard fitting. Warring States period (475–221 BC). White-blue nephrite, rectangular sword accessory, narrow end with dragon pattern, tiger pattern on both sides, two phoenixes symmetrically arranged below, each grasping a small snake. Shanghai Museum collection.*</p><p>The <strong>Warring States phoenix-pattern jade she-style pendant</strong> derives from the Zhou archery tradition. The she was originally a protective ring worn on the archer''s thumb to pull the bowstring; by the mid-Warring States period, as ritual became secularized, the functional jade she gradually evolved into a purely decorative "she-style pendant" — the function disappeared but the meaning remained: the wearer was declaring possession of an aristocratic archer''s skill and status. This object-type evolution neatly symbolizes the broader arc of ritual in that era, moving from practical function to pure symbol.</p><p>![Warring States phoenix-pattern jade she-style pendant](images/zhanguo_shepei.jpg) *Warring States phoenix-pattern jade she-style pendant. Warring States period (475–221 BC). Evolved from the functional Zhou archery jade she into a purely decorative pendant, marking the transition of ritual from practical use to symbolic expression. Shanghai Museum collection.*</p><h2>Six: The Age of Burial Jade — The Han and Jin Dynasties'' Belief in Immortality</h2><h3>(206 BC to 420 AD)</h3><h3>6.1 The Han Dynasty — The Apotheosis of Jade and the Peak of Burial Jade</h3><p>The Han dynasty represents the absolute zenith of Chinese burial jade culture.</p><p>Han people believed jade could prevent the decomposition of the body. The logic was coherent: jade is hard and never rots, and in an era that prized immortality and the transformation of the soul into a transcendent being, encasing the body in jade was the most solemn form of hope. A complete burial jade system accordingly came into being: <strong>jade suits</strong> encased the whole body, <strong>jade plugs</strong> sealed the nine orifices, <strong>jade cicadas</strong> were placed in the mouth, <strong>jade grips</strong> were placed in both palms — a meticulous "immortality protection system," trading the treasury of a prince or king for the soul''s peaceful passage to the next world.</p><p>In the gallery, a <strong>Han dynasty cicada-form jade ham</strong> — small as a thumb, glowing white — was the most commonly used mouth piece in the Han burial tradition. The choice of the cicada was anything but arbitrary: the cicada lies dormant underground for years, then bursts upward one day to sing from the treetops, a perfect symbol of the Han aspiration for "resurrection after death" and "the soul ascending to heaven." Placed in the mouth of the deceased, that small cicada carried not only the temperature of jade but the entire afterlife imagining of a civilization.</p><p>A <strong>Eastern Han jade sheng amulet with four-directional spirit motifs</strong> is another object that demands attention. The sheng was the emblem of the Queen Mother of the West — a goddess in Chinese mythology who dwelt on Mount Kunlun and held the elixir of immortality. This jade sheng not only wards off evil but establishes a mystical connection with the Queen Mother of the West. The piece combines the Azure Dragon, White Tiger, Vermilion Bird, and Black Tortoise — the four directional guardians — with the sheng form, and the central bar is incised with the eight characters "long may sons and grandsons prosper, ten thousand years of longevity" — a concentrated distillation of the entire Han dynasty''s longing for life.</p><p>![Eastern Han jade sheng amulet with four-directional spirit motifs](images/han_siling.jpg) *Eastern Han jade sheng amulet with four-directional spirit motifs. Eastern Han dynasty (25–220 AD). White nephrite, the four guardian spirits of the four directions combined with the sheng form, the central bar incised "long may sons and grandsons prosper, ten thousand years of longevity." Shanghai Museum collection.*</p><h3>6.2 A Unique Object: The Jade Land Contract</h3><p>The gallery displays an extraordinarily rare <strong>Eastern Han jade land contract</strong>.</p><p>Land contracts of this kind — a contract for one''s burial plot in the underworld — have occasionally been found in clay, lead, or stone, but one made of jade is currently the only known example in all of China. It is blue-green nephrite, with inscriptions on both faces recording how, in the sixth year of the Jianchu reign (81 AD), a tomb occupant named Mi Ying purchased this land as her eternal resting place, documenting the boundaries in all four directions and informing the earth deity to protect the soul from disturbance.</p><p>A "purchase contract for the afterlife," carved in jade — it represents the highest level of solemnity and sincerity that Han people could bring to a covenant with the underworld. It also lets us see that the sacred nature of jade in the Han dynasty had fully permeated every dimension of existence, including the world beyond death.</p><p>![Eastern Han jade land contract](images/han_maidiquan.jpg) *Eastern Han jade land contract. Eastern Han dynasty, sixth year of Jianchu (81 AD). Blue-green nephrite, inscriptions on both faces recording the tomb occupant Mi Ying''s purchase of her burial land and the boundaries in all four directions. Currently the only known jade land contract in China. Shanghai Museum collection.*</p><h2>Seven: The Age of Worldly Jade — The Secular Beauty of the Tang, Song, Liao, and Jin Dynasties</h2><h3>(618–1279 AD)</h3><h3>7.1 The Tang Dynasty — Jade Steps Down from the Divine and Into Everyday Splendor</h3><p>With the reunification of the Sui-Tang era and the revival of national power, jade underwent a profound transformation toward the worldly.</p><p>The burial jade system declined as the fashion for lavish burial faded; jade was no longer solely a ritual implement for communing with the divine but became a component of flourishing daily life. Subjects expanded from divine animals, dragons, and phoenixes to flowers, human figures, landscapes, and flying celestial beings; technique moved from abstract geometry toward lifelike realism; vessel forms including cups, plates, and bowls for daily use began to appear in large numbers.</p><p><strong>Tang dynasty jade flying apsara</strong> represents the perfect fusion of Tang Buddhist art and jade carving. The apsara, from the Sanskrit "gandharva," entered China with Buddhism and merged with the native tradition of winged immortals to become one of the most romantically spirited Tang forms. This round-carved jade apsara has flowing ribbons and soars on clouds — the craftsman has achieved a seamless unity between the warmth and luster of white Hetian nephrite and the floating grace of the apsara itself, a vision of the Tang dynasty''s paradise at its most sumptuous.</p><p>![Tang dynasty jade flying apsara](images/tang_feitian.jpg) *Tang dynasty jade flying apsara. Tang dynasty (618–907 AD). White nephrite, round carving of a cloud-riding apsara. The apsara from Sanskrit "gandharva" — flowing ribbons, soaring on clouds — a classic example of the perfect fusion of Buddhist art and the Chinese jade carving tradition. Shanghai Museum collection.*</p><p>A <strong>Tang dynasty jade belt with musician figures</strong> is a superb witness to the cultural openness of that era. The complete belt consists of twelve square jade plaques and one tail piece, each plaque carved in relief with a musician from the Western regions — one playing a pipa lute, one blowing panpipes, one beating a waist drum, each fully absorbed in the music, with clearly distinguishable foreign dress. In the early Tang period, jade belts were codified into official dress regulations, restricted to officials of the third rank and above. This belt was once the declaration of power worn at the waist of a great Tang dignitary — and a snapshot of that magnificent, all-embracing era when the Silk Road brought the world to China''s door.</p><p>![Tang dynasty jade belt with musician figures](images/tang_yuedai.jpg) *Tang dynasty jade belt with musician figures. Tang dynasty (618–907 AD). Twelve square white jade plaques and one tail piece, each plaque carved in relief with a Western Regions musician — restricted to officials of the third rank and above — a superb witness to Silk Road cultural exchange. Shanghai Museum collection.*</p><h3>7.2 Song Dynasty — Jade as Painting and the Literati Sensibility</h3><p>Song dynasty jade changed its character markedly — less of the temple''s sanctity, more of the scholar''s refinement.</p><p>The economic prosperity and rise of urban culture in the two Song dynasties drew jade from exclusive aristocratic use to a broader social circle. Subjects familiar from daily life — flowers and birds, children, fish and insects — appeared in abundance, and carving technique grew increasingly lifelike and delicate. Scholars call this development "jade as painting" — as if a corner of an academy painting had been cut out and frozen in jade.</p><p>In the cases, a <strong>Song dynasty jade boy holding a lotus</strong> — white-blue nephrite, a round-cheeked child hugging a lotus bloom, endearingly cute and brimming with everyday warmth. "A boy holding a lotus" (lian in Chinese) carries the auspicious meaning of "may sons be born in abundance" (lian sheng gui zi), with roots in the Buddhist legend of "the doe mother giving birth from a lotus." In the Song world, Buddhist scripture and popular custom had merged entirely, and jade is the gentlest witness to that blending.</p><p>![Song dynasty jade boy holding a lotus](images/song_yutong.jpg) *Song dynasty jade boy holding a lotus. Song dynasty (960–1279 AD). White-blue nephrite, boy hugging a lotus bloom, round and endearing. A typical example of the secularization of Song dynasty jade and the rise of urban culture. Shanghai Museum collection.*</p><h3>7.3 Jin Dynasty — Spring Water Jade and Autumn Mountain Jade, the Dramatic Arrival of Steppe Sensibility</h3><p>A <strong>Jin dynasty spring water jade belt plaque</strong> in the gallery catches the eye at once: on a white nephrite ground, the black skin of the stone has been turned by the craftsman into a scene of a sea falcon (goshawk) stooping from the sky, talons seizing a swan in flight — the power of the falcon''s dive and the swan''s curving struggle perfectly rendered through the black-and-white contrast of the jade.</p><p>![Jin dynasty spring water jade belt plaque](images/jin_chunshui.jpg) *Jin dynasty spring water jade belt plaque. Jin dynasty (1115–1234 AD). White nephrite, natural black skin exploited to carve a scene of a sea falcon seizing a swan — a standout example of the Jin "spring water" jade subject and a classic case of nomadic culture absorbed into the jade carving tradition. Shanghai Museum collection.*</p><p>This is the most celebrated technique in Jin dynasty jade carving — "naturalistic color work" (qiao se): rather than demanding a pure stone, the craftsman works with the skin colors and natural variations, carving with nature rather than against it, creating "a scene that emerges from natural color." "Spring water" subjects derive from the spring hunting activities of the Jin imperial family; "autumn mountain" subjects depict tigers and deer scattered through autumn forests — the vitality of a nomadic people''s experience found entirely new modes of expression within the forms of Han jade culture. The result is one of the most surprising and delightful products of cultural collision.</p><h2>Eight: The Age of Artistic Jade — The Carving Zenith of the Yuan, Ming, and Qing Dynasties</h2><h3>(1271–1911 AD)</h3><h3>8.1 The Ming Dynasty — Antiquarian Spirit and the Art of Gold-Set Jeweled Work</h3><p>Ming dynasty jade presents two strikingly different and each fully realized faces: one looking backward to antiquity, the other embracing lavish luxury.</p><p>The antiquarian face grew from the scholarly tradition of bronze and stone studies that had flourished since the Northern Song. Literati were passionate about researching ancient bronzes, and jade workers accordingly modeled jade on Shang-Zhou bronze forms and motifs. The <strong>Ming dynasty jade gui vessel with double-dragon handles and lug-nail patterns</strong> in the gallery imitates a Shang-Zhou bronze gui in form, with archaic decoration and a deep, resonant presence — a way of condensing Ming scholars'' reverence for antiquity into jade.</p><p>The luxurious face belongs to the spectacular flowering of <strong>gold-set jeweled work</strong>. The thriving maritime trade of the Ming brought rubies, sapphires, emeralds, and spinels from Southeast Asia and West Asia into the court in quantity; jade workers combined these foreign gems with Chinese jade, using gold as the armature, jade as the primary material, and gem-stones as accents — a sumptuous richness that leaves the viewer transfixed. The <strong>Ming dynasty jade-inlaid silver-gilt xiapei pendant</strong> — a hanging ornament worn at the hem of a noblewoman''s ceremonial cape — is representative of this technique — it is not merely a piece of jewelry but a map of an entire empire''s trade.</p><p>![Ming dynasty jade-inlaid silver gilt pendant](images/ming_xiapei.jpg) *Ming dynasty jade-inlaid silver gilt pendant. Ming dynasty (1368–1644 AD). Silver gilt as base, inlaid with white nephrite, rubies, sapphires, and other precious materials. This pendant, worn on formal court dress by Ming dynasty noblewomen, is physical evidence of Ming maritime trade prosperity. Shanghai Museum collection.*</p><h3>8.2 The Qing Dynasty — Emperor Qianlong''s Jade Obsession and the Highest Peak of Chinese Jade History</h3><p>The highest peak in the history of Chinese jade occurs in the Qianlong period of the Qing dynasty.</p><p>Emperor Qianlong''s love of jade reached the edge of obsession — he composed over 800 imperial poems on jade objects in his lifetime, including more than 70 on "Hindustan jade" (Islamic-style jade from what is now northern India and Central Asia) alone. He wrote: "Fine as a hair in its veining, not a trace of the chisel''s mark" — that was his breathless wonder at the thinly carved walls of Hindustan jade work.</p><p>In the cases, a <strong>Qing dynasty gold-set jeweled floral jade box</strong> is quintessentially Hindustan in style: the walls are so thin they are nearly translucent, like a sheet of semi-transparent jade paper; the exterior is inlaid with rubies and emeralds, outlined in gold thread with floral patterns of exquisite refinement — a cross-civilizational dialogue between the court craft of the Mughal dynasty of India and Chinese jade culture, and the most beautiful jewel of global luxury trade in that era.</p><p>![Qing dynasty gold-set jeweled floral jade box](images/qing_yuhe.jpg) *Qing dynasty gold-set jeweled floral jade box. Qing dynasty (18th century), Hindustan style. Exceptionally thin walls, exterior with gold-thread floral patterns, inlaid with rubies and emeralds — a pinnacle of cross-civilizational jade dialogue between the Mughal court of northern India and Qing imperial jade carving. Shanghai Museum collection.*</p><p>A <strong>Qing dynasty jadeite brush washer with three chi-dragons</strong> is another unforgettable piece. Jadeite was not highly valued in Chinese jade culture before the Qing dynasty; it was only with the large-scale importation of Burmese jadeite during the Qianlong period that it gradually achieved its status as imperial jade of the highest order. This brush washer is white-green shot through with deep green; three chi-dragons peer over the rim, one of them spouting a stream of water whose green drops form naturally where the jade itself is green — the craftsman has used "naturalistic color work" to merge the natural and the artistic in a way that leaves the viewer marveling.</p><p>![Qing dynasty jadeite brush washer with three chi-dragons](images/qing_feicui.jpg) *Qing dynasty jadeite brush washer with three chi-dragons. Qing dynasty (1644–1912 AD). Jadeite, white ground shot with deep green, crabapple-shaped rim, three chi-dragons in relief peering over the edge, one spouting water — the green water drops form naturally in the stone''s green zone, an outstanding example of naturalistic color work. Shanghai Museum collection.*</p><p>As for the <strong>jade mountains</strong> of Yangzhou carving from the Qing dynasty — these are grand narrative works accumulating the mastery of generations. These jade mountains often weigh hundreds of pounds, taking landscape-and-figures as their subject, with plans drafted by court painters and then carved over years by master craftsmen from Suzhou and Yangzhou — epic works of Eastern sculptural art.</p><h2>Nine: Leaving the Jade Gallery — A Stone and a Civilization</h2><p>Having seen the whole gallery, looking back from the exit at that block of Hetian nephrite by the entrance, you feel something entirely different from when you arrived.</p><p>It is not just a stone. It is the material vessel of nine thousand years of Chinese spiritual life — from the first shaman''s hand that ever grasped jade in the mist of prehistory, to the mysterious craftsman who polished the Liangzhu jade cong, from the Han dynasty princes who lay down to their eternal night dressed in jade, to Emperor Qianlong''s happy sigh of wonder at a piece of thinly carved Hindustan work — jade witnessed the entire journey of this civilization from its earliest groping to its zenith.</p><p>The Chinese chose jade as the soul of their civilization, and not by accident. Jade has two faces: <strong>one hard, bending to no force; the other warm and lustrous, never using its hardness to injure others</strong>. Tenacity and gentleness coexist, strength and generosity live together — and this is precisely the highest ideal of the Chinese character, the deepest layer of a civilization''s self-understanding.</p><p>"A gentleman has no reason to set jade aside."</p><p>That line from two thousand years ago is still a people''s aspiration for itself.</p><h2>Appendix: Key Works in the Jade Gallery at a Glance</h2><p>| Artifact | Period | Material | Source/Site | Primary significance | |---|---|---|---|---| | Shijiahe late-period jade deity figure | Neolithic | Yellow-green nephrite | Hubei Shijiahe culture | Prehistoric shaman image, symbol of theocratic authority | | Liangzhu jade cong with deity-and-beast flying-bird motif | Roughly 3300–2300 BC | Yellow-green nephrite | Fuquanshan site, Qingpu | Carrier of the Liangzhu divine emblem, politico-religious authority | | Liangzhu jade cong with deity-and-bird motif (39.3 cm) | Roughly 3300–2300 BC | Red-brown from burial staining | Shanghai Museum collection | Among the tallest surviving Liangzhu jade cong | | Liangzhu culture jade yue axe | Roughly 3300–2300 BC | Yellow-green nephrite | Fuquanshan site, Qingpu | Supreme symbol of kingship and military power | | Shang dynasty dragon-form jade pendant | Roughly 1600–1046 BC | Blue-green nephrite | Shang culture | Marker of the mature phase of Chinese dragon symbolism | | Shang dynasty jade qi axe with beast-face motif | Roughly 1600–1046 BC | Dark blue-green nephrite | Shang culture | Ritual weapon, embodiment of divine and royal power | | Western Zhou double-dragon-head jade huang crescent | Roughly 1046–771 BC | White-blue nephrite | Western Zhou | Core element of the ritual pendant assemblage | | Warring States dragon-and-phoenix jade zhui sword fitting | 475–221 BC | White-blue nephrite | Warring States | Divine-animal cosmic imagery, ritualization of sword culture | | Han dynasty cicada-form jade ham | 206 BC – 220 AD | White nephrite | Han dynasty | Han belief in immortality and celestial ascent | | Eastern Han jade sheng amulet with four-directional spirit motifs | 25–220 AD | White nephrite | Eastern Han | Protective amulet and Queen Mother of the West veneration | | Eastern Han jade land contract | 81 AD (sixth year of Jianchu) | Blue-green nephrite | Eastern Han tomb | Only known jade land contract in China | | Tang dynasty jade belt with musician figures | 618–907 AD | White nephrite and silver | Tang dynasty | Official ritual object for third rank and above, Silk Road cultural fusion | | Tang dynasty jade flying apsara | 618–907 AD | White nephrite | Tang dynasty | Fusion of Buddhist art and Chinese jade tradition | | Jin dynasty spring water jade belt plaque | 1115–1234 AD | White nephrite (black skin) | Jin dynasty | Classic of naturalistic color work, northern nomadic culture absorbed | | Ming dynasty jade gui vessel with double-dragon handles | 1368–1644 AD | White nephrite | Ming dynasty | Antiquarian jade, literati bronze-and-stone aesthetic | | Qing dynasty jadeite brush washer with three chi-dragons | 1644–1912 AD | Jadeite | Qing dynasty | Classic of jadeite naturalistic color work | | Qing dynasty gold-set jeweled floral jade box | 18th century | Jade, gold, gemstones | Hindustan, imperial tribute | Finest example of cross-civilizational jade exchange |</p><p>*The content of this chapter was compiled based on firsthand observation of the Ancient Chinese Jade Gallery at the Shanghai Museum East Branch, official Shanghai Museum materials, and relevant academic research. Artifact descriptions follow the gallery''s own labels; historical analysis draws on published archaeological scholarship.*</p><p>*Image credits: All artifact photographs in this chapter are from the collection database of the Shanghai Museum''s official website (www.shanghaimuseum.net) and remain the copyright of the Shanghai Museum. Each photograph''s artifact name, period, material, and provenance have been verified against official Shanghai Museum collection records. Images are for internal reference purposes only; for public or commercial use, please contact the Shanghai Museum for authorization.*</p>',
  '[]'::jsonb,
  3,
  TRUE
) ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
