INSERT INTO city_guides (
  id, city_id, title_en, title_zh, subtitle, icon, badge,
  cover_images, body, meta_items, display_order, is_published
) VALUES (
  'shanghai_coffee',
  'shanghai',
  'Top Ten Must-Visit Independent Coffee Shops in Shanghai (Detailed Guide)',
  '上海独立咖啡必打卡前十名（详细版）',
  NULL,
  '☕',
  NULL,
  ARRAY[]::TEXT[],
  '<h3>1. O.P.S. CAFE — The Vanguard of Creative Specialty Drinks</h3><p><strong>Address:</strong> Unit 1, Lane 177, Taiyuan Road, Xuhui District <strong>Hours:</strong> 10:00 AM to 5:00 PM <strong>Average spend:</strong> 35 to 50 yuan</p><h2>The shop and its story</h2><p>O.P.S. CAFE opened in 2017 and is widely credited as the pioneer of creative specialty drinks in Shanghai — regarded as "one of the landmarks of Shanghai coffee culture." The space is under ten square metres, has no seating whatsoever, and requires customers to drink standing up; regulars affectionately call it the "stand-up coffee bar." The founder broke with the conventions of third-wave specialty coffee by drawing on the thinking of tea-making and bartending, releasing an entirely new menu every season with an emphasis on seasonality and experimentation.</p><p>This combination of distinctive service, genuine interaction, and constant innovation keeps long lines forming outside a shop barely bigger than a closet. When the weather turns cold or wet, the staff proactively hand out heat packs or share umbrellas — a level of care that has earned the shop a reputation as "Shanghai''s best-service coffee shop."</p><h2>The experience</h2><p>O.P.S. does not offer conventional espresso drinks (no lattes, no Americanos). It focuses exclusively on creative specialty drinks: five to six entirely new beverages each season, blending coffee with fruits, spirits, spices, tea, and more. Every cup comes with a dedicated card describing its flavor profile and how it was made, and the barista will walk you through it on the spot — so you learn while you drink.</p><h2>Signature drinks:</h2><ul><li><strong>Sweet Teeth:</strong> Made with buffalo milk, Earl Grey caramel, and oolong tea, topped with an orange foam — refreshing and perfect for summer</li><li><strong>Five-Finger Mountain Peach Special:</strong> The wild mulberry fruit is made into a topping foam; coconut milk carries an aroma that evokes a tropical beach</li><li><strong>Fermented and Candied:</strong> A tea foam that is clean and light, with the freshness of fruit tea</li></ul><h2>Food</h2><p>The shop focuses entirely on the coffee experience and does not serve food. Eat at a nearby restaurant first, or take your coffee for a stroll under the plane trees of Taiyuan Road.</p><h2>Why it''s worth the visit</h2><ul><li>Creative experience: encounter the most inventive coffee culture in Shanghai, with coffee treated as an art form fused with other ingredients</li><li>Interactive service: one-on-one explanation from the barista, a close view of the craft process, and a flavor card to take away</li><li>Cultural landmark: widely recognized as a bellwether for the Shanghai coffee scene</li><li>Seasonal surprise: an entirely new menu every quarter — every visit is different</li></ul><h2>Practical tips</h2><ul><li>Weekday queues run about 20 minutes; weekends can be 40 minutes. Arriving before 10:00 AM or after 2:00 PM helps.</li><li>No seating; drinks must be consumed standing or taken away.</li><li>Consider pairing with a visit to the nearby shop 3½ on the same day: O.P.S. for the standing creative experience in the morning, 3½ for a comfortable second cup in the afternoon.</li></ul><h3>2. D.ORINO COFFEE — The Pursuit of the Perfect Flat White</h3><p><strong>Address:</strong> 833 Kangding Road, Jing''an District <strong>Hours:</strong> 10:00 AM to 4:30 PM (Tuesday to Saturday; closed Sunday and Monday) <strong>Average spend:</strong> 30 to 50 yuan</p><h2>The shop and its story</h2><p>D.ORINO COFFEE is a tiny space that its owner built by hand over 20 days — the facade is so narrow it is easy to walk straight past. Inside, a single row of seats along one wall holds four or five people at most. The owner is barista, roaster, and artisan all in one; every lamp fitting and every cup in the shop was made by hand. That attention to the smallest detail is quietly extraordinary.</p><p>It is that craftsman''s spirit that has earned D.ORINO''s flat white the reputation of being "the best flat white in Shanghai." Many coffee lovers are willing to queue for two hours — because after one sip, you understand why Shanghai''s coffee community holds this place in such esteem.</p><h2>The experience</h2><p>D.ORINO is known for the flat white, but it is far from the only thing worth ordering. The menu includes two or three rotating single-origin espresso options (SOE), updated every two days, so every visit offers something fresh. Pour-over coffee is also available, including different grades of geisha bean.</p><h2>Signature drinks:</h2><ul><li><strong>Flat white (Australiano):</strong> Beneath the velvety micro-foam, the espresso and milk achieve perfect fusion — a ring of golden crema forms at the lip of the cup; every sip is as silky as melting dark chocolate</li><li><strong>Pour-over coffee:</strong> Available in light or medium-dark roast; the Colombian washed lot carries notes of chestnut and macadamia</li><li><strong>SOE selection:</strong> Rotating every two days to guarantee freshness</li></ul><h2>Food</h2><p>The shop focuses on coffee; simple baked goods are available. Check with staff on the day for specifics, as the owner adjusts these according to what''s available.</p><h2>Why it''s worth the visit</h2><ul><li>Craftsman spirit: every detail of the space, down to the light fittings, is handmade</li><li>The best flat white in Shanghai: try the drink that makes people queue for two hours</li><li>Intimate atmosphere: a tiny space that invites a real conversation with the barista</li><li>Fresh guarantee: SOE rotated every two days</li></ul><h2>Practical tips</h2><ul><li>Closed Sunday and Monday; open Tuesday to Saturday.</li><li>Very limited seating (four to five people maximum); takeaway or visiting at off-peak times is recommended.</li><li>The owner is quiet but extremely serious about his coffee — watch the process and you will see why.</li></ul><h3>3. Radar Coffee — A Coffee Radar on Sinan Road</h3><p><strong>Address:</strong> 27 Sinan Road, Huangpu District <strong>Hours:</strong> 7:30 AM to 5:00 PM (closed Tuesdays) <strong>Average spend:</strong> 25 to 40 yuan</p><h2>The shop and its story</h2><p>Radar Coffee is tucked away on Sinan Road — a tiny coffee station with space for only four or five people at a time. That doesn''t stop it from being a haven for serious coffee drinkers. The owner says little, but everything he does say is about coffee; his understanding of and passion for the subject runs deep. The handwritten menu on the wall lists each bean''s origin, processing method, and flavor notes — a simple gesture that speaks to real craft and sincerity.</p><p>The name is fitting: like a radar, the shop locks onto the ideal flavor of every bean it works with. That focus and care sets it apart from the noise of Shanghai''s crowded coffee scene.</p><h2>The experience</h2><p>Radar Coffee offers a solid range of espresso and pour-over options — light roast and dark roast, bitter and acidic and balanced, black coffee and milk coffee. The single-origin selection covers multiple beans, each with its own distinct character.</p><h2>Signature drinks:</h2><ul><li><strong>SOE flat white:</strong> Made with an Ethiopian Yirgacheffe SOE, the crema catches the light beautifully; the result is exceptional</li><li><strong>Hot Americano:</strong> Made with a Brazilian SOE — rich dark chocolate with a nutty aroma</li><li><strong>Pour-over:</strong> Several single-origin options; the owner will recommend based on your preferences</li></ul><h2>Food</h2><p>The shop focuses primarily on coffee; check with staff for any light food options on the day.</p><h2>Why it''s worth the visit</h2><ul><li>Professional coffee: brewed by an owner with a deep command of his craft</li><li>Handwritten menu: a genuine expression of sincerity</li><li>Intimate space: small enough to shut out the noise and concentrate on the coffee</li><li>Early opening: from 7:30 AM — perfect for early risers</li></ul><h2>Practical tips</h2><ul><li>Closed Tuesdays.</li><li>Very limited space; takeaway or a quick drink is the practical approach.</li><li>Going early in the morning has two advantages: Sinan Road is easier to navigate, and you get the place to yourself.</li></ul><h3>4. Three and a Half (3½) — The Comfortable Upgrade of O.P.S.</h3><p><strong>Address:</strong> Unit 1, Lane 305, Taiyuan Road, Xuhui District <strong>Hours:</strong> 9:00 AM to 6:00 PM <strong>Average spend:</strong> 35 to 50 yuan</p><h2>The shop and its story</h2><p>Three and a Half is a second location from the team behind O.P.S. CAFE, just a short distance away on the same street — and crucially, it has seats. The interior carries the same refined, pared-back aesthetic as O.P.S. The name is an interesting choice — like a musical interval of a minor third, it implies both continuity and variation.</p><p>Extending the creative specialty-drink ethos of O.P.S. while offering a more comfortable setting, Three and a Half brings both familiar O.P.S. classics and its own new creations. After opening on 15 June 2023, it quickly became another shop on Taiyuan Road where a queue is the norm.</p><h2>The experience</h2><p>Three and a Half carries forward the O.P.S. style: a selection of creative specialty drinks alongside a few classics to cover different preferences.</p><h2>Signature drinks:</h2><ul><li><strong>Sweet Teeth:</strong> A Three and a Half classic — the recipe has been updated; buffalo milk now replaces the original cream for a finer texture; Earl Grey is more pronounced; the overall mouthfeel is very smooth</li><li><strong>Yuanyang Shaved Ice:</strong> One of the signature specialties — a perfect blend of coffee and milk</li><li><strong>Glutinous Rice and Flowers; Berry and Cream Cake:</strong> Popular seasonal specials suited to anyone who enjoys a sweeter coffee experience</li></ul><h2>Food</h2><p>Check with staff on the day for food options. The shop focuses on coffee but offers a more complete environment than O.P.S.</p><h2>Why it''s worth the visit</h2><ul><li>Seating: unlike the standing experience at O.P.S., you can sit and linger</li><li>Quality continuity: the same creative specialty-drink philosophy, reliably delivered</li><li>Double the fun: stop at O.P.S. for the standing creative experience in the morning, then come here to relax in the afternoon</li><li>Second-floor space: occasionally opened for a more private experience</li></ul><h2>Practical tips</h2><ul><li>Still very popular; expect some waiting time.</li><li>Pairing with O.P.S. on the same day is ideal.</li><li>Follow the shop on social media; the second floor opens occasionally and is worth the experience.</li></ul><h3>5. Boonna — An Oasis for International Visitors</h3><p><strong>Address:</strong> 88 Xinle Road (near Xiangyang Road), Xuhui District <strong>Hours:</strong> Daily, 9:00 AM to 12:30 AM <strong>Average spend:</strong> 38 to 60 yuan</p><h2>The shop and its story</h2><p>Boonna is one of Shanghai''s most popular cafes. The purple frontage stands out clearly from a distance. Inside, the walls are hung with art photographs; bookshelves are lined with English and foreign-language books, making international visitors feel immediately at ease. Low, comfortable window seats invite relaxation; rows of tables with power outlets suit anyone working on a laptop.</p><p>Boonna is not just a cafe — it is a central node in Shanghai''s international community. It regularly draws expats working, meeting friends, and reading, making it a genuine "third space."</p><h2>The experience</h2><p>The menu is wide-ranging, from classic espresso drinks to creative beverages. In winter, the rich hot chocolate is a must; in summer, the smoothies and fresh juices are the coolest choice.</p><h2>Signature drinks:</h2><ul><li><strong>Espresso-based drinks:</strong> Americano, latte, cappuccino — consistently good</li><li><strong>Hot chocolate:</strong> A winter essential — thick, rich, like drinking melted chocolate</li><li><strong>Smoothies and fresh juices:</strong> The perfect summer choice, made with fresh fruit</li></ul><h2>Food</h2><p>Boonna offers excellent value in its food options, especially at lunch.</p><h2>Recommended food:</h2><ul><li><strong>Lunch set (38 yuan):</strong> A sandwich (beef, salmon, chicken, or vegetarian, on focaccia, panini, or baguette) plus a coffee, tea, or juice</li><li><strong>Sandwiches and light meals:</strong> Multiple sandwich and salad options for a quick lunch or afternoon snack</li><li><strong>Afternoon tea set:</strong> Coffee and pastries, ideal for a catch-up with friends</li></ul><h2>Why it''s worth the visit</h2><ul><li>Foreign-language books on the shelves for browsing while you drink</li><li>Low, comfortable seats and warm decor — genuinely relaxing</li><li>Excellent value: the 38-yuan lunch set covers a sandwich and a drink</li><li>Open until midnight: suitable at any hour</li><li>International community atmosphere: a real chance to meet people from around the world</li></ul><h2>Practical tips</h2><ul><li>Extremely popular; finding a seat can be difficult at peak hours.</li><li>The Xinle Road location is smoke-free on Tuesdays.</li><li>Boonna 3 (at 1690 Huaihai Road) is entirely non-smoking and has a large terrace — often a better choice.</li><li>WiFi is available but may be slow at peak times.</li></ul><h3>6. Garden Books — Where Books and Coffee Meet</h3><p><strong>Address:</strong> 325 Changle Road (near South Shaanxi Road), Xuhui District <strong>Hours:</strong> Monday to Friday, 10:00 AM to 10:00 PM; Saturday to Sunday, 10:00 AM to 11:00 PM <strong>Average spend:</strong> 40 to 70 yuan</p><h2>The shop and its story</h2><p>Garden Books is first and foremost a bookshop, with a cafe section inside. It is the best source of English-language books in Shanghai, carrying fiction, non-fiction, travel guides, American magazines, and language-learning titles. If a title you want is not in stock, they will order it for you.</p><p>Regular literary talks and events make it an important gathering point for Shanghai''s literary community. It also has a location in Beijing.</p><h2>The experience</h2><p>Drinking coffee surrounded by books is a comparatively rare experience in Shanghai. Garden Books'' coffee does not aim to compete with specialist cafes, but there is a particular pleasure in drinking it with so much to read.</p><h2>Signature drinks:</h2><ul><li><strong>Classic coffees:</strong> Americano, latte, cappuccino and other traditional options</li><li><strong>Ice cream coffee:</strong> A specialty combining coffee and ice cream, good for summer</li><li><strong>Tea:</strong> A variety of teas available for non-coffee drinkers</li></ul><h2>Food</h2><ul><li><strong>Light food and pastries:</strong> Simple pastries and light bites to accompany coffee or tea</li><li><strong>Snacks:</strong> Small bites that pair well with a book</li></ul><h2>Why it''s worth the visit</h2><ul><li>The atmosphere of reading among books is a distinctive cultural experience</li><li>Shanghai''s widest selection of English-language books — read in-store or order what you need</li><li>Regular literary events — a way into Shanghai''s literary scene</li><li>Quiet enough for reading and working</li><li>Family-friendly: a children''s book section is available</li></ul><h2>Practical tips</h2><ul><li>If a title isn''t in stock, they can order it for you (provide the title and author).</li><li>A good spot for a long sit, but please keep noise to a minimum out of respect for other readers.</li><li>Check the shop''s social media for information on literary events.</li><li>With a Beijing location as well, it''s possible to visit both if your trip includes both cities.</li></ul><h3>7. Old China Hand Reading Room — A Memory of Old Shanghai</h3><p><strong>Address:</strong> 27 Shaoxing Road (near South Shaanxi Road), Xuhui District <strong>Hours:</strong> Daily, 10:00 AM to midnight <strong>Average spend:</strong> 30 to 50 yuan</p><h2>The shop and its story</h2><p>The Old China Hand Reading Room is a vintage bookshop-cafe hidden on Shaoxing Road, opened in the autumn of 1996 by Shanghai photographer and world traveler Er Dongqiang, who had visited 41 countries before its founding. Inspired by the bookshop-cafes of Europe and expanded to twice its original size in 1999, it has become the first choice for Shanghai''s cultural community when they want a place to gather and talk.</p><p>Between an old piano and shelves heavy with books, the shop serves coffee and small plates. The dark green traditional Chinese signage and antique-style exterior feel like a portal back to 1930s Shanghai.</p><h2>A famous visitor</h2><p>The Old China Hand Reading Room is widely believed to have been a favorite haunt of the late pop legend Leslie Cheung. On an afternoon when he was in Shanghai for a concert, he came here alone, made himself tea, and spent several hours browsing the shelves. Ask the staff about him today and they may well produce a stack of guest books and memorial volumes. The shop has become one of the pilgrimage stops in Shanghai for Leslie Cheung''s fans.</p><h2>The experience</h2><p>Drinking coffee among an old piano, vintage trunks, and antique curiosities is a one-of-a-kind experience.</p><h2>Signature drinks:</h2><ul><li><strong>Classic coffees:</strong> Americano, latte — straightforward but reliable</li><li><strong>Pour-over:</strong> May be available on some days; ideal for slow sipping</li><li><strong>Chinese teas:</strong> The more fitting choice for the old Shanghai atmosphere</li></ul><h2>Food</h2><ul><li>Small cafe bites to pair with coffee</li><li>Pastries, possibly including traditional Chinese varieties</li></ul><h2>Why it''s worth the visit</h2><ul><li>A taste of 1930s Shanghai cultural atmosphere and vintage aesthetics</li><li>Cultural landmark: Shaoxing Road is Shanghai''s literary street, surrounded by publishing houses</li><li>Following in famous footsteps: the place Leslie Cheung loved</li><li>Quiet enough for reading, writing, and thinking</li><li>Atmospheric: coffee among books and a piano — also extremely photogenic</li></ul><h2>Practical tips</h2><ul><li>Open until midnight — especially atmospheric in the evening, when the old piano glows in the lamplight.</li><li>Suited to quiet visitors; not the place for a loud gathering.</li><li>If you are a Leslie Cheung fan, mention it to the staff — they will be delighted to share stories.</li><li>Shaoxing Road and its surroundings are worth exploring further, with several publishing houses and cultural institutions nearby.</li></ul><h3>8. Mia''s (formerly Aroma de Vida) — Vintage Aesthetics Over Coffee</h3><p><strong>Address:</strong> 45–47 Anfu Road (near Changshu Road), Xuhui District <strong>Hours:</strong> Daily, 9:00 AM to 11:30 PM <strong>Average spend:</strong> 35 to 55 yuan</p><h2>The shop and its story</h2><p>Mia''s (formerly Aroma de Vida) is a cafe steeped in vintage aesthetics. From outside you might think it is an antique shop — 1950s radios, 1920s mirrors, and Art Nouveau decorative pieces compete for attention in the window display. This arrangement is not a curated act of theater but the cumulative result of years of the owner''s personal collecting; every piece has its story.</p><p>Anfu Road has become one of Shanghai''s most fashionable streets for artistically minded shops and businesses, and Mia''s is its vintage landmark. Soft jazz, free WiFi, and affordable, tasty food have made it many people''s default place for an afternoon.</p><h2>The experience</h2><p>Mia''s coffee is not the most technically refined, but in this setting, that is beside the point. The barista may offer latte art to add a little flourish.</p><h2>Signature drinks:</h2><ul><li><strong>Classic coffees:</strong> Americano, latte, cappuccino — reliable for everyday enjoyment</li><li><strong>Latte art specials:</strong> The barista may produce seasonal or whimsical latte art</li><li><strong>Seasonal drinks:</strong> Hot mulled wine in winter, iced lemonade in summer</li></ul><h2>Food</h2><p>Mia''s offers inexpensive, satisfying Western and local dishes — great value.</p><h2>Recommended food:</h2><ul><li><strong>Lunch specials:</strong> A lunchtime draw for office workers in the neighborhood — very good value</li><li><strong>Brunch menu:</strong> A relaxed weekend crowd comes for the slow-paced Saturday and Sunday brunch</li><li><strong>Western and Chinese options:</strong> Sandwiches, salads, pasta; also lighter Chinese bites</li></ul><h2>Why it''s worth the visit</h2><ul><li>Vintage decor — 1950s radios, 1920s mirrors — ideal for photography</li><li>Good value: affordable food and coffee in a space that rewards lingering</li><li>Comfortable atmosphere: jazz and free WiFi invite you to work or chat</li><li>Anfu Road exploration: the street is full of interesting small shops and spaces worth browsing</li><li>Open from 9:00 AM to 11:30 PM — suitable at almost any hour</li></ul><h2>Practical tips</h2><ul><li>Can be crowded at lunchtime; avoiding 12:00 to 1:30 PM is a good idea.</li><li>Weekend brunch is popular — arriving early or at off-peak times is recommended.</li><li>Suited to visitors who appreciate vintage aesthetics and a quiet atmosphere.</li><li>Allow half a day to explore Anfu Road properly.</li></ul><h3>9. Coffee Tree — The Coffee Tree on Changle Road</h3><p><strong>Address:</strong> 291 Changle Road (near Fumin Road), Xuhui District <strong>Hours:</strong> Daily, 9:00 AM to 7:00 PM <strong>Average spend:</strong> 35 to 55 yuan <strong>Second location:</strong> 376 Wukang Road, inside the Ferguson Lane complex</p><h2>The shop and its story</h2><p>Coffee Tree is an excellent alternative when Boonna is full. A long narrow room with tables on both sides — entirely non-smoking. The left wall carries black-and-white photographs of Shanghai; a floor-length mirror runs the length of the right wall, making the space feel larger than it is. The design is both practical and pleasing.</p><p>Coffee Tree attracts families, ladies who lunch, and business people who come to use the free WiFi and browse magazines. It has a more local, neighborhood feel than Boonna — better suited to visitors who want a taste of everyday Shanghai cafe culture rather than an expat bubble.</p><h2>The experience</h2><p>Coffee Tree''s menu is solid and wide-ranging without pursuing novelty. Consistent quality, good for regular enjoyment.</p><h2>Signature drinks:</h2><ul><li><strong>Classic coffees:</strong> Americano, latte, cappuccino — reliable standards</li><li><strong>Pour-over:</strong> May be available; ask staff what they recommend that day</li><li><strong>Teas:</strong> A range of teas for non-coffee drinkers</li></ul><h2>Food</h2><p>A fuller food menu than Boonna — better suited to visitors who want a proper meal.</p><h2>Recommended food:</h2><ul><li><strong>Sandwiches and salads:</strong> Multiple fresh sandwich and salad options — healthy and light</li><li><strong>Light meals:</strong> Suitable for lunch or afternoon tea; portions are sensible</li><li><strong>Daily specials:</strong> Ask staff what the day''s special is</li></ul><h2>Why it''s worth the visit</h2><ul><li>Entirely non-smoking — particularly welcoming for families with children</li><li>Free WiFi with a reliable connection</li><li>Family-friendly: a relaxed atmosphere</li><li>Magazines available to browse while you unwind</li><li>Local neighborhood feel — a more everyday Shanghai cafe experience</li></ul><h2>Practical tips</h2><ul><li>The Wukang Road location is equally popular and positioned in the more fashionable Wukang Road area.</li><li>Closes at 7:00 PM — plan accordingly.</li><li>Good for visitors who need WiFi to work; plenty of power outlets are available.</li><li>For a more genuinely local Shanghai cafe experience than Boonna, this is the better choice.</li></ul><h3>10. Bliss — Vintage 1960s Coffee and Cocktails</h3><p><strong>Address:</strong> 181 Jinxian Road (near South Maoming Road), Jing''an District <strong>Hours:</strong> Tuesday to Friday, 5:00 PM to 2:00 AM; Saturday to Sunday, 11:30 AM to 2:00 AM <strong>Average spend:</strong> 40 to 80 yuan (coffee by day, cocktails by night)</p><h2>The shop and its story</h2><p>Bliss is another vintage pocket in Shanghai''s coffee landscape. Jinxian Road is full of cool cafes and restaurants, and Bliss is no exception. Wooden-paneled walls open into a 1960s diner-style cafe, fitted out in curved brown-and-yellow furniture that feels like a time capsule from an American roadside diner of that decade.</p><p>Classic snacks like popcorn reinforce the retro feel. Bliss operates as a coffee shop by day and transforms into a cocktail bar in the evening — a dual-purpose format that makes it one of the most distinctive spots on Jinxian Road.</p><h2>The experience</h2><p>The daytime cafe side of Bliss offers a traditional coffee experience — not the most technically refined, but the 1960s setting gives it a character all its own.</p><h2>Signature drinks:</h2><ul><li><strong>Classic coffees:</strong> Traditional espresso-based drinks for the afternoon</li><li><strong>Evening coffee cocktails:</strong> The after-dark menu includes coffee cocktails such as an Espresso Martini</li><li><strong>House specials:</strong> Seasonal and off-menu drinks at the owner''s discretion</li></ul><h2>Food</h2><ul><li><strong>Classic snacks:</strong> Popcorn and similar retro bites that reinforce the period atmosphere</li><li><strong>1960s diner-style light food:</strong> Simple American diner fare to pair with coffee or cocktails</li><li><strong>Evening snacks:</strong> A broader selection of small bites when the bar opens at night</li></ul><h2>Why it''s worth the visit</h2><ul><li>A fully realized 1960s diner theme — great for photography</li><li>Day-and-night dual use: coffee in the afternoon, cocktails at night — visit according to your mood</li><li>Still relatively undiscovered: a seat is almost always available</li><li>Jinxian Road exploration: the street is full of interesting cafes and restaurants to visit alongside</li><li>Open until 2:00 AM — one of the few places in Shanghai serving coffee and cocktails this late</li></ul><h2>Practical tips</h2><ul><li>Tuesday to Friday the doors don''t open until 5:00 PM — plan for later afternoon or evening.</li><li>Weekend opening is from 11:30 AM, making it an option for a late weekend brunch or post-lunch coffee.</li><li>In the evening it becomes a cocktail bar and stays open until 2:00 AM — a genuine option for late nights.</li><li>Allow two to three hours to explore Jinxian Road properly.</li><li>The experience is completely different in the day and at night — be aware of the transition.</li></ul><h2>Practical Summary</h2><h3>Coffee Culture and Etiquette</h3><h2>A few useful coffee terms in Mandarin:</h2><ul><li>Pour-over: Shouchong</li><li>Americano: Meishi</li><li>Latte: Natie</li><li>Iced Americano: Bing meishi</li><li>Flat white: Aobai</li></ul><p><strong>Avoid peak weekend mornings:</strong> Saturday and Sunday mornings are busy at most of these shops. Arriving before 10:00 AM or after 2:00 PM usually helps.</p><p><strong>Prepare for mobile payment:</strong> Many independent cafes accept only cash or mobile payment (WeChat Pay or Alipay). Setting up one of these before you go is strongly recommended.</p><h3>Exploring the Area</h3><p><strong>The Former French Concession area:</strong> Yongkang Road, Yueyang Road, and the Wukang Road corridor have the highest concentration of quality independent cafes in Shanghai — set aside half a day to explore this stretch.</p><p><strong>Use Dianping:</strong> Search "specialty coffee" (jingpin kafei) on the Dianping app and filter by neighborhood for up-to-date reviews and opening hours.</p><p><strong>Wander freely:</strong> The best cafes are often discovered by accident — an unassuming door, a small chalkboard sign, the sound of a grinder. Don''t hesitate to walk into somewhere that looks tiny; the surprises are usually inside.</p><p><strong>Plan your route:</strong> Group geographically close cafes on the same day. O.P.S. and Three and a Half on Taiyuan Road, for instance, work perfectly as a morning-and-afternoon pair.</p><h3>A Few More Tips</h3><p><strong>Expect changes:</strong> Shanghai''s independent cafe scene moves fast. Check hours and confirm the cafe is still open before heading out.</p><p><strong>Respect each cafe''s culture:</strong> Some shops like O.P.S. have their own distinctive culture (the standing-only rule) — embrace it rather than resist it, and you will get far more out of the experience.</p><p><strong>Support independent coffee:</strong> Every visit is a vote for Shanghai''s independent coffee culture.</p>',
  '[]'::jsonb,
  4,
  TRUE
) ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
  city_id = EXCLUDED.city_id,
  title_en = EXCLUDED.title_en,
  title_zh = EXCLUDED.title_zh,
